{"title_page": "West Genesee High School", "text_new": "{{Infobox school\n| name              = West Genesee High School\n| image             = \n| caption           = \n| motto             = We Celebrate Learning!\n| motto_translation = \n| address           = 5201 West Genesee Street\n| town              = [[Camillus, New York|Camillus]]\n| state             = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| zipcode           = 13031-2299\n| country           = United States\n| coordinates       = {{Coord|43.038909|N|76.265888|W|display=inline,title}}\n| other_names       = {{Hlist|West Genny|WG}}\n| type              = [[State school|Public]] high school\n| established       = {{Start date|1952}}\n| founder           = \n| closed            = \n| district          = [[West Genesee Central School District]]\n| ceeb              = 331175\n| us_nces_school_id = {{NCES School ID|363063004119|school_name=West Genesee Senior High School|access_date=Apr 25, 2012|ref_name=NCES}}\n| principal         = Wayne Ackles<ref>{{cite web |title=About West Genesee High School |url=https://www.westgenesee.org/west-genesee-high-school/about-west-genesee-high-school/ |website=West Genesee Central School District |accessdate=28 January 2019}}</ref>\n| principal_label   = Executive Principal\n| teaching_staff    = 100.09 {{FTE}}<ref name=\"NCES\" />\n| grades            = 9-12\n| enrollment        = 1,616 (2016-2017)<ref name=\"NCES\" />\n| ratio             = 16.15<ref name=\"NCES\" />\n| colors            = Navy blue and gold {{Color box|Navy}}{{Color box|Gold}}\n| mascot            = [[Wildcat]]\n| nickname          = Wildcats\n| yearbook          = Genesean \n| website           = {{URL|www.westgenesee.org/west-genesee-high-school}}\n}}\n\n'''West Genesee Senior High School''' (colloquially referred to as '''West Genny''' or '''WG''') is a 9-12 public high school in [[Camillus, New York|Camillus]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States. It is part of the [[West Genesee Central School District]].\n\n==Recognized Academic Programs==\nIn addition to general and Regents level courses, the school offers a number of college-level course options for students through a variety of different programs.\n\n===Advanced Placement Courses===\nWest Genesee High School offers a wide variety of [[Advanced Placement Program]] (AP) courses to its students.  These courses are generally considered \"much more rigorous than the general course offerings\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gsgi.co.uk/articles/curricula-and-exams/curricula/advanced-placement-ap|title=Advanced Placement (AP)|accessdate=2008-10-13|publisher=The Good Schools Guide International}}</ref>\n\nCourses offered include [[AP English Language and Composition|English Language & Composition]], [[AP English Literature and Composition|English Literature & Composition]], [[AP World History|World History]], [[AP United States History|US History]], [[AP Statistics|Statistics]], [[AP Calculus|Calculus]], [[AP Physics|Physics]], [[AP Biology|Biology]], [[AP French Language|French Language]], [[AP Spanish Language|Spanish Language]], [[AP Studio Art|Studio Art]], [[AP Music Theory|Music Theory]].<ref name=\"advanced\">{{cite web|url=http://westgenesee.org/wghscouncil_collegdesc.asp|title=College and Advanced Placement Course Descriptions|accessdate=2008-10-13|publisher=West Genesee Central School District}}</ref>\n\n===Syracuse University Project Advance===\nIn Addition to AP courses, the school offers a number of courses through the [[Syracuse University]] [http://supa.syr.edu/ Project Advance (SUPA)] program.  The students receive Syracuse University college credits, but the courses are taught by teachers named adjunct instructors by S.U. and are taught in classrooms at the high school as a part of a student's regular day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://supa.syr.edu/about/index.php|title=SUPA - About us|accessdate=2008-10-13|year=2007|publisher=Project Advance}}</ref>\n\nCourses offered through [[Project Advance]] include [[Economics]], Psychology, Public Affairs, and Sociology.<ref name=\"advanced\"/>\n\n===Onondaga Community College===\nThe school also offers courses for college credit through [[Onondaga Community College]], a local community college.  Like the SUPA courses, these courses are taught in classrooms at the high school.\n\nCourses include [[Financial Accounting]], [[Astronomy]], [[Computer-aided design|CAD]], [[Computer Information Systems]], Introduction to Business, [[Photography]] and [[Precalculus]].<ref name=\"advanced\"/>\n\n== West Genesee Wildcats ==\nWest Genesee High School's athletic teams are known as the \"Wildcats\".  Their colors are navy blue and gold.  All of the teams compete in the [[New York State Public High School Athletic Association|NYSPHAA]]'s Section 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.section3online.com/directoriesinformation/section3schoolwebsites.html |title=Section 3 Websites |accessdate=2008-10-13 |publisher=Section3Online.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090309152241/http://www.section3online.com/directoriesinformation/section3schoolwebsites.html |archivedate=March 9, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nStudents are able to participate in [[baseball]], [[basketball]], [[bowling]], [[cheerleading]], [[Cross country running|cross-country]], [[American football|football]], [[golf]], [[hockey]], [[lacrosse]], [[soccer]], [[softball]], [[Swimming (sport)|swimming]], [[tennis]], [[Track and field athletics|track]], [[volleyball]], and [[Submission wrestling|wrestling]].<ref name=\"profile\">{{cite web|url=http://westgenesee.org/pdf/WGProfile.PDF |title=WG Profile |accessdate=2008-10-13 |date=July 2008 |publisher=West Genesee Central School District |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928212606/http://westgenesee.org/pdf/WGProfile.PDF |archivedate=September 28, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nA number of West Genesee's athletic teams have won state championships: Marching band (34), boys' lacrosse (15), girls' lacrosse (7), wrestling (5), boys' hockey (3), girls' swimming (3), boys' track (2), girls' hockey (2), football, boys' golf, and boys' swimming (1) and boys' basketball (1).<ref name=\"about\">{{cite web|url=http://www.westgenesee.org/District/District/District_AboutUsFacts.cfm|title=About Us - West Genesee Facts and Figures |accessdate=26 November 2017 |publisher=[[West Genesee Central School District]]}}</ref> The marching band has also won the national championship 5 times.\n\n===Lacrosse===\nThe boys' lacrosse team, coached by Shaun Smith,  is widely recognized as one of the premier high school lacrosse teams in the United States. Hall of Fame coach Mike Messere was the head coach from 1975-2018. During his tenure, the Wildcats' finished the season 1st in the national high school rankings 8 times since 1990.\n\nThe team has won 15 New York State championships, including four consecutive between 2002 and 2005, and 34 Section III championships.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.section3lax.com/state.htm|title=State Champions|accessdate=2008-10-13|publisher=Section III Lacrosse}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.section3lax.com/section.htm|title=Section III Champions|accessdate=2008-10-13|publisher=Section III Lacrosse}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2011, the program has produced 52 high school [[All-America]]ns since 1971.\n\n[[John Desko]], the head coach of [[Syracuse University]]'s [[Syracuse Orange men's lacrosse|men's lacrosse team]] is a former player and alumnus of the school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://suathletics.com/roster.asp?playerid=2302&sport=192&roster=265|title=John Desko|publisher=Syracuse University|accessdate=2008-10-13}}</ref>\n\nThe girls' lacrosse team is also a regional power.  The team began in 1995 and quickly rose to local and national prominence.  The team has won six state championships in 2001, 2002, 2003, 2007, 2008, and 2012.<ref name=\"ladyCats\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wglax.com/pages/ladycats.html |title=West Genesee Lady Wildcat Lacrosse |accessdate=2008-10-13 |publisher=WGLax.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080521004510/http://wglax.com/pages/ladycats.html |archivedate=2008-05-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Between 2001 and 2003, the Lady 'Cats won 67 consecutive games, and as of 13 October 2008 the team has won 48 consecutive games dating back to the beginning of the 2007 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nysphsaa.org/records/g_lax.asp|title=NYSPHAA - Record Book|accessdate=2008-10-13|publisher=NYSPHAA|date=2008-06-19}}</ref><ref name=\"ladyCats\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wglax.com/pages/Lady%20Cats%20Stats,%20Facts%20and%20Video.htm |title=West Genesee Lady 'Cats Facts, Stats, and Video |publisher=WGLax.com |accessdate=2008-10-13 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080521180220/http://wglax.com/pages/Lady+Cats+Stats,+Facts+and+Video.htm |archivedate=2008-05-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.syracuse.com/today/index.ssf/2008/06/west_genesee_captures_boys_gir.html|title=West Genesee captures boys, girls lax titles|accessdate=2008-10-13|publisher=Syracuse Online|date=2008-06-14}}</ref>\n\n===Ice hockey===\nThe West Genesee hockey team is a 3-time New York State Champion winning in 1990, 2001, and 2010, when the team was undefeated. The Wildcats have won 11 Section 3 championships including seven straight between 2008 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=History|url=http://westgeneseehockey.com/history/|website=WestGeneseeHockey.com|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref> Coach Frank Colabufo has an all-time record of 390-146-39.<ref>{{cite web|title=Season Results|url=http://westgeneseehockey.com/history/season-results/|website=WestGeneseeHockey.com|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe most successful alumni is Rob Michel. He currently plays in the [[Philadelphia Flyers]] organization.\n\n===Basketball===\nIn the winter of 2018/19, the boys' basketball team secured the first state championship in the team's existence, and the girls' team was runner up in the state championship.\n\n===Football===\nIn the fall of 2007, the football team claimed its first New York State Class AA Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.syracuse.com/news/2007/11/west_genesee_ludden_are_footba.html|title=West Genesee, Ludden are football champs|accessdate=2008-10-13|author=Neil Kerr|date=2007-11-25|work=News from The Post Standard|publisher=Syracuse Online}}</ref> The team is coached by Joe Corley, a position he has held since May 2008.\n\n==Clubs and activities==\nIn addition to academics and athletics, West Genesee High School also offers a number of clubs and other extracurricular activities.\n\nThese include [[United States Academic Decathlon|Academic Decathlon]], Business Club, Drama Club,  Future Business Leaders of America (FBLA), Technical Theatre club,  Foreign Language Clubs, [[Model United Nations|Model UN]], [[National Honor Society|Honor Society]], R<sup>2</sup> (Respect and Responsibility), Positivity Project (replacing R<sup>2</sup>), Ski Club, [[Student governments in the United States|Student Council and Class Senates]], Yearbook Club, ECOS (Environmental group), and Outdoor Club.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Public high schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Schools in Onondaga County, New York]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox school\n| name              = West Genesee High School\n| image             = \n| caption           = \n| motto             = We Celebrate Learning!\n| motto_translation = \n| address           = 5201 West Genesee Street\n| town              = [[Camillus, New York|Camillus]]\n| state             = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| zipcode           = 13031-2299\n| country           = United States\n| coordinates       = {{Coord|43.038909|N|76.265888|W|display=inline,title}}\n| other_names       = {{Hlist|West Genny|WG}}\n| type              = [[State school|Public]] high school\n| established       = {{Start date|1952}}\n| founder           = \n| closed            = \n| district          = [[West Genesee Central School District]]\n| ceeb              = 331175\n| us_nces_school_id = {{NCES School ID|363063004119|school_name=West Genesee Senior High School|access_date=Apr 25, 2012|ref_name=NCES}}\n| principal         = Wayne Ackles<ref>{{cite web |title=About West Genesee High School |url=https://www.westgenesee.org/west-genesee-high-school/about-west-genesee-high-school/ |website=West Genesee Central School District |accessdate=28 January 2019}}</ref>\n| principal_label   = Executive Principal\n| teaching_staff    = 100.09 {{FTE}}<ref name=\"NCES\" />\n| grades            = 9-12\n| enrollment        = 1,616 (2016-2017)<ref name=\"NCES\" />\n| ratio             = 16.15<ref name=\"NCES\" />\n| colors            = Navy blue and gold {{Color box|Navy}}{{Color box|Gold}}\n| mascot            = [[Wildcat]]\n| nickname          = Wildcats\n| yearbook          = Genesean \n| website           = {{URL|www.westgenesee.org/west-genesee-high-school}}\n}}\n\n'''West Genesee Senior High School''' (colloquially referred to as '''West Genny''' or '''WG''') is a 9-12 public high school in [[Camillus, New York|Camillus]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States. It is part of the [[West Genesee Central School District]].\n\n==Recognized Academic Programs==\nIn addition to general and Regents level courses, the school offers a number of college-level course options for students through a variety of different programs.\n\n===Advanced Placement Courses===\nWest Genesee High School offers a wide variety of [[Advanced Placement Program]] (AP) courses to its students.  These courses are generally considered \"much more rigorous than the general course offerings\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gsgi.co.uk/articles/curricula-and-exams/curricula/advanced-placement-ap|title=Advanced Placement (AP)|accessdate=2008-10-13|publisher=The Good Schools Guide International}}</ref>\n\nCourses offered include [[AP English Language and Composition|English Language & Composition]], [[AP English Literature and Composition|English Literature & Composition]], [[AP World History|World History]], [[AP United States History|US History]], [[AP Statistics|Statistics]], [[AP Calculus|Calculus]], [[AP Physics|Physics]], [[AP Biology|Biology]], [[AP French Language|French Language]], [[AP Spanish Language|Spanish Language]], [[AP Studio Art|Studio Art]], [[AP Music Theory|Music Theory]].<ref name=\"advanced\">{{cite web|url=http://westgenesee.org/wghscouncil_collegdesc.asp|title=College and Advanced Placement Course Descriptions|accessdate=2008-10-13|publisher=West Genesee Central School District}}</ref>\n\n===Syracuse University Project Advance===\nIn Addition to AP courses, the school offers a number of courses through the [[Syracuse University]] [http://supa.syr.edu/ Project Advance (SUPA)] program.  The students receive Syracuse University college credits, but the courses are taught by teachers named adjunct instructors by S.U. and are taught in classrooms at the high school as a part of a student's regular day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://supa.syr.edu/about/index.php|title=SUPA - About us|accessdate=2008-10-13|year=2007|publisher=Project Advance}}</ref>\n\nCourses offered through [[Project Advance]] include [[Economics]], Psychology, Public Affairs, and Sociology.<ref name=\"advanced\"/>\n\n===Onondaga Community College===\nThe school also offers courses for college credit through [[Onondaga Community College]], a local community college.  Like the SUPA courses, these courses are taught in classrooms at the high school.\n\nCourses include [[Financial Accounting]], [[Astronomy]], [[Computer-aided design|CAD]], [[Computer Information Systems]], Introduction to Business, [[Photography]] and [[Precalculus]].<ref name=\"advanced\"/>\n\n== West Genesee Wildcats ==\nWest Genesee High School's athletic teams are known as the \"Wildcats\".  Their colors are navy blue and gold.  All of the teams compete in the [[New York State Public High School Athletic Association|NYSPHAA]]'s Section 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.section3online.com/directoriesinformation/section3schoolwebsites.html |title=Section 3 Websites |accessdate=2008-10-13 |publisher=Section3Online.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090309152241/http://www.section3online.com/directoriesinformation/section3schoolwebsites.html |archivedate=March 9, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nStudents are able to participate in [[baseball]], [[basketball]], [[bowling]], [[cheerleading]], [[Cross country running|cross-country]], [[American football|football]], [[golf]], [[hockey]], [[lacrosse]], [[soccer]], [[softball]], [[Swimming (sport)|swimming]], [[tennis]], [[Track and field athletics|track]], [[volleyball]], and [[Submission wrestling|wrestling]].<ref name=\"profile\">{{cite web|url=http://westgenesee.org/pdf/WGProfile.PDF |title=WG Profile |accessdate=2008-10-13 |date=July 2008 |publisher=West Genesee Central School District |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928212606/http://westgenesee.org/pdf/WGProfile.PDF |archivedate=September 28, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nA number of West Genesee's athletic teams have won state championships: Marching band (34), boys' lacrosse (15), girls' lacrosse (7), wrestling (5), boys' hockey (3), girls' swimming (3), boys' track (2), girls' hockey (2), football, boys' golf, and boys' swimming (1) and boys' basketball (1).<ref name=\"about\">{{cite web|url=http://www.westgenesee.org/District/District/District_AboutUsFacts.cfm|title=About Us - West Genesee Facts and Figures |accessdate=26 November 2017 |publisher=[[West Genesee Central School District]]}}</ref> The marching band has also won the national championship 5 times.\n\n===Lacrosse===\nThe boys' lacrosse team, coached by Shaun Smith,  is widely recognized as one of the premier high school lacrosse teams in the United States. Hall of Fame coach Mike Messere was the head coach from 1975-2018. During his tenure, the Wildcats' finished the season 1st in the national high school rankings 8 times since 1990.\n\nThe team has won 15 New York State championships, including four consecutive between 2002 and 2005, and 34 Section III championships.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.section3lax.com/state.htm|title=State Champions|accessdate=2008-10-13|publisher=Section III Lacrosse}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.section3lax.com/section.htm|title=Section III Champions|accessdate=2008-10-13|publisher=Section III Lacrosse}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2011, the program has produced 52 high school [[All-America]]ns since 1971.\n\n[[John Desko]], the head coach of [[Syracuse University]]'s [[Syracuse Orange men's lacrosse|men's lacrosse team]] is a former player and alumnus of the school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://suathletics.com/roster.asp?playerid=2302&sport=192&roster=265|title=John Desko|publisher=Syracuse University|accessdate=2008-10-13}}</ref>\n\nThe girls' lacrosse team is also a regional power.  The team began in 1995 and quickly rose to local and national prominence.  The team has won six state championships in 2001, 2002, 2003, 2007, 2008, and 2012. <ref name=\"ladyCats\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wglax.com/pages/ladycats.html |title=West Genesee Lady Wildcat Lacrosse |accessdate=2008-10-13 |publisher=WGLax.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080521004510/http://wglax.com/pages/ladycats.html |archivedate=2008-05-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Between 2001 and 2003, the Lady 'Cats won 67 consecutive games, and as of 13 October 2008 the team has won 48 consecutive games dating back to the beginning of the 2007 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nysphsaa.org/records/g_lax.asp|title=NYSPHAA - Record Book|accessdate=2008-10-13|publisher=NYSPHAA|date=2008-06-19}}</ref><ref name=\"ladyCats\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wglax.com/pages/Lady%20Cats%20Stats,%20Facts%20and%20Video.htm |title=West Genesee Lady 'Cats Facts, Stats, and Video |publisher=WGLax.com |accessdate=2008-10-13 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080521180220/http://wglax.com/pages/Lady+Cats+Stats,+Facts+and+Video.htm |archivedate=2008-05-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.syracuse.com/today/index.ssf/2008/06/west_genesee_captures_boys_gir.html|title=West Genesee captures boys, girls lax titles|accessdate=2008-10-13|publisher=Syracuse Online|date=2008-06-14}}</ref>\n\n===Ice hockey===\nThe West Genesee hockey team is a 3-time New York State Champion winning in 1990, 2001, and 2010, when the team was undefeated. The Wildcats have won 11 Section 3 championships including seven straight between 2008 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=History|url=http://westgeneseehockey.com/history/|website=WestGeneseeHockey.com|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref> Coach Frank Colabufo has an all-time record of 390-146-39.<ref>{{cite web|title=Season Results|url=http://westgeneseehockey.com/history/season-results/|website=WestGeneseeHockey.com|accessdate=25 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe most successful alumni is Rob Michel. He currently plays in the [[Philadelphia Flyers]] organization.\n\n===Basketball===\nIn the winter of 2018/19, the boys' basketball team secured the first state championship in the teams existence, and the girls' team was runner up in the state championship.\n\n===Football===\nIn the fall of 2007, the football team claimed its first New York State Class AA Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.syracuse.com/news/2007/11/west_genesee_ludden_are_footba.html|title=West Genesee, Ludden are football champs|accessdate=2008-10-13|author=Neil Kerr|date=2007-11-25|work=News from The Post Standard|publisher=Syracuse Online}}</ref>The team is coached by Joe Corley, a position he has held since May 2008.\n\n==Clubs and activities==\nIn addition to academics and athletics, West Genesee High School also offers a number of clubs and other extracurricular activities.\n\nThese include [[United States Academic Decathlon|Academic Decathlon]], Business Club, Drama Club,  Future Business Leaders of America (FBLA), Technical Theatre club,  Foreign Language Clubs, [[Model United Nations|Model UN]], [[National Honor Society|Honor Society]], R<sup>2</sup> (Respect and Responsibility), Positivity Project (replacing R<sup>2</sup>), Ski Club, [[Student governments in the United States|Student Council and Class Senates]], Yearbook Club, ECOS (Environmental group), and Outdoor Club.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Public high schools in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Schools in Onondaga County, New York]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: teams existence \u2192 team's existence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/West_Genesee_High_School"}
{"title_page": "Bukovina Germans", "text_new": "[[File:Bucov.png|thumb|right|200px|Ethnic groups in entire Bukovina according to the 1930 Romanian census, with German-speaking populations marked in black in both the southern and northern part of the region.]]\n\nThe '''Bukovina Germans''' ({{lang-de|Bukowina Deutsche}} or ''Buchenland Deutsche'') were a [[German diaspora|German]] [[ethnic group]] which settled in [[Bukovina]], a historical region situated at the crossroads of [[Central Europe|Central]] and [[Eastern Europe]]. Their demographic presence lasted from the last quarter of the 18th century, when Bukovina was [[Treaty of K\u00fc\u00e7\u00fck Kaynarca|annexed]] by the [[Habsburg Monarchy|Habsburg Empire]], until 1940, when nearly all Bukovina Germans (almost 100,000 people)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jachomowski |first1=Dirk |title=Die Umsiedlung der Bessarabien-, Bukowina- und Dobrudschadeutschen |date=1984 |publisher=R. Oldenbourg |isbn=9783486524710 |pages=88-95 |language=de}}</ref> were resettled into the Third Reich as a part of ''[[Heim ins Reich]]'' national socialist population transfer policy.\n\nAccording to the 1910 Imperial Austrian census, the Bukovina Germans represented an ethnic minority accounting for approximately 21% of the multi-ethnic population of the [[Duchy of Bukovina]] ({{lang-de|Herzogtum Bukowina}}). Subsequently, in absolute numbers, 75,533 ethnic Germans (or {{circa}} 9% of population) were registered in Bukovina when it was under Royal Romanian administration in an official census in 1930.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Middle Ages ===\n\n{{multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | header    =\n | header_align = left/right/center\n | header_background =\n | footer\n | footer_align = left/right/center\n | footer_background =\n | width     =\n | image1    = Historical Baia Suceava CoA 14th century.png\n | width1    = 135\n | caption1  = 14th century seal of Baia, evoking the legend of [[Hubertus|Saint Hubertus]], the patron saint of hunters\n | image2    = Catedrala Catolic\u0103 din Baia3.jpg\n | width2    = 210\n | caption2  = Ruins of the medieval Roman Catholic Cathedral in [[Baia]] ({{lang-de|Moldenmarkt}}), [[Suceava County]], north-eastern [[Romania]]\n}}\n\nEthnic Germans known as [[Transylvanian Saxons]] (who were mainly craftsmen and merchants stemming from present-day [[Luxembourg]] and [[Rhine]]-[[Moselle]] areas of [[Western Europe]]), had sparsely settled in the western mountainous regions of the [[Moldavia|Principality of Moldavia]] over the course of the late medieval [[Ostsiedlung]] migration (which, in this particular case, took place throughout the 13th and 14th centuries).\n\nThese settlers encouraged trade and urban development. Additionally, they founded (and were also briefly in charge under the title of [[Schulthei\u00df]]) of some notable medieval settlements such as [[Baia]] ({{lang-de|Stadt Molde or Moldenmarkt}}), the first capital of the Principality of Moldavia, or [[T\u00e2rgu Neam\u021b]] ({{lang-de|Niamtz}}).<ref>Hugo Weczerka, Das mittelalterliche und fr\u00fchneuzeitliche Deutschtum im F\u00fcrstentum Moldau, M\u00fcnchen 1960</ref> Subsequently, most of them were gradually [[Cultural assimilation|assimilated]] in these local cultures.\n\n=== Modern Age and Habsburg rule ===\n\nFollowing the [[Russo-Turkish War (1768\u201374)|Russo-Turkish War]], in 1774\u201375 the [[Habsburg Monarchy]] annexed northwestern Moldavia which was predominantly inhabited by [[Romanians]] (as many as 85 percent), with smaller numbers of [[Ukrainians]] (including [[Hutsuls]] and [[Ruthenians]]), [[Armenians]], [[Poland|Poles]], and [[Judaism|Jews]].<ref name=\"romanians1774-1866\">Keith Hitchins. ''The Romanians 1774-1866.'' Oxford: Clarendon Press (1996), pp. 226</ref>\n\nSince then, the region has been known as Bukovina ({{lang-de|Bukowina or Buchenland}}). From 1774 to 1786, settlement of German craftsmen and farmers in existing villages increased (see also: [[Josephine colonization]]). The settlers included [[Zipser Germans]] from the [[Spi\u0161|Zips]] region of [[Upper Hungary]] (present-day [[Slovakia]]), [[Banat Swabians]] from [[Banat]], and ethnic Germans from [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria|Galicia]] (more specifically [[Evangelical Lutheranism|Evangelical Lutheran]] [[Protestants]]), but also immigrants from the [[Palatinate (region)|Rhenish Palatinate]], the [[Margraviate of Baden|Baden]] and [[Landgraviate of Hesse-Darmstadt|Hesse]] principalities, as well as from impoverished regions of the [[Bohemian Forest]] ({{lang-de|B\u00f6hmewald}}).\n\nThus, four distinct [[German dialects|German linguistic groups]] were represented as follows:\n\n* [[Austrian High German]] (''\u00d6sterreichisches Hochdeutsch'') was spoken in urban centres like [[Chernivtsi]] (''Czernowitz''), [[R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi]] (''Radautz''), [[Suceava]] (''Suczawa''), [[Gura Humorului]] (''Gura Humora''), [[C\u00e2mpulung Moldovenesc|C\u00e2mpulung]] (Kimpolung), and [[Siret]] (''Sereth'');\n* Bohemian-[[Bavarian German]] (''Deutschb\u00f6hmisch'' or ''B\u00f6hmerw\u00e4ldisch'') was spoken by woodsmen in [[Huta Veche|Alth\u00fctte]], [[Cr\u0103sni\u0219oara Nou\u0103|Neuh\u00fctte]], [[Gura Putnei|Karlsberg]], {{ill|Voievodeasa, Romania|lt=F\u00fcrstenthal|ro|Voievodeasa, Suceava}}, [[Vadu Negrilesei|Schwarzthal]], [[Poiana Micului|Buchenhain]], Dealu Ederii (''Lichtenberg''), Bori (early colony in Gura Humorului), and Clit (''Glitt'');\n* [[Palatine Rhine Franconian]] (''Pf\u00e4lzisch'') was spoken in farming villages like [[Arbore|Arbora]], [[B\u0103deu\u021bi|Deutsch Badeutz]], [[Fr\u0103t\u0103u\u021bii Vechi|Alt Fratautz]], [[Fr\u0103t\u0103u\u021bii Noi|Neu Fratautz]], [[Ili\u0219e\u0219ti|Illischestie]], [[I\u021bcani|Itzkany]], [[Satu Mare, Suceava|Deutsch Satulmare]] and [[Tereblecea|Tereblestie]];\n* [[Zipser German]] (''Zipserisch'') was spoken by mine workers and their descendants in [[C\u00e2rlibaba]] (''Mariensee'' or ''Ludwigsdorf''), [[Iacobeni, Suceava|Iacobeni]] (''Jakobeny''), [[Stulpicani]] (''Stulpikany''), and elsewhere.<ref>Willi Kosiul, ''Die Bukowina und ihre Buchenlanddeutschen'' (2012, {{ISBN|3942867095}}), volume 2</ref>\n\nDuring the 19th century, the developing German middle class comprised much of the intellectual and political elite of the region; the language of official business and education was predominantly German, particularly among the upper classes. Population growth and a shortage of land led to the establishment of daughter settlements in [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]], [[Bessarabia]], and [[Dobruja]].\n\nAfter 1840, a shortage of land caused the decline into poverty of the German rural lower classes; in the late 19th century parts of the German rural population alongside a few Romanians emigrated to the Americas, mainly to the [[United States]] (most notably to [[Kansas]]) but also to [[Canada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bukovinasociety.org |title=Bukovina Society of the Americas Home Page |publisher=Bukovinasociety.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com/~bakerroots/bukovina.html |title=Bukovina Germans |publisher=Freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bukovinasociety.org/ellingson-brzl-2001-a.html |title=Bukovina Immigration to North America |publisher=Bukovinasociety.org |accessdate=2013-03-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120609062842/http://www.bukovinasociety.org/ellingson-brzl-2001-a.html# |archive-date=2012-06-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBetween 1849 and 1851, and from 1863 to 1918, the [[Duchy of Bukovina]] became an independent [[crown land]] within the [[Austrian Empire]] (see also: [[Cisleithania]]). However, in comparison to other Austrian crown lands, Bukovina remained an underdeveloped region on the periphery of the realm, primarily supplying raw materials.\n\nThe [[University of Chernivtsi|Franz Josephs Universit\u00e4t]] in Czernowitz was founded in 1875, then the easternmost German-speaking university. In 1910\u20131911, the Bukovinan Reconciliation (a political agreement between the peoples of Bukovina and their political representatives in the [[Landtag]] assembly on the question of autonomous regional administration) took place between the representatives of the nationalities.\n\n<gallery class=center>\nFile:Chernivtsi - \u0427\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0456\u0432\u0446\u0456 1.jpg|[[Chernivtsi|Cern\u0103u\u021bi]] ({{lang-de|Czernowitz}}) town hall, {{circa}} 1905\nFile:Palatul Administrativ din Suceava19.jpg|[[Suceava]] ({{lang-de|Suczawa}}) town hall (nowadays administrative palace), early 20th century\nFile:Biserica romano-catolica din Gura Humorului11.jpg|Roman Catholic church in [[Gura Humorului]] ({{lang-de|Gura Humora}}), early 20th century\nFile:Jakobeny (BildID 15716697).jpg|View of [[Iacobeni, Suceava|Iacobeni]] ({{lang-de|Jakobeny}}), a Zipser German village, early 20th century\nFile:Vatra Dornei 1.jpg|Bilingual German-Romanian postcard from [[Vatra Dornei]] ({{lang-de|Dorna-Watra}}), early 20th century\nFile:Biserica Adormirea Maicii Domnului din Ilisesti.jpg|Former Evangelical Lutheran (now Orthodox) church in [[Ili\u0219e\u0219ti]] ({{lang-de|llischestie}})\n</gallery>\n\n=== Early 20th century and Kingdom of Romania ===\n\n[[File:Deutsche_Siedlungsgebiete_in_Osteuropa_1925.jpg|thumb|right|Map of German minorities in Eastern Europe during the interwar period, also highlighting German settlements in the Kingdom of Romania, including Bukovina.]]\n\nFrom 1918 to 1919, following the end of [[World War I]] and the dissolution of the Austro-Hungarian Empire, Bukovina became part of the [[Kingdom of Romania]]. At the [[General Congress of Bukovina]] held on November 28, 1918,<ref name=\"Livezeanu2000\">{{cite book|author=Irina Livezeanu|title=Cultural Politics in Greater Romania: Regionalism, Nation Building & Ethnic Struggle, 1918-1930|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5ysbpAyJjoAC&pg=PA59|year=2000|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=0-8014-8688-2|pages=59\u2013}}</ref> the political representatives of the Bukovina Germans voted and supported the union of Bukovina with the Romanian kingdom, alongside the Romanian and Polish representatives.\n\nFrom 1933 up until 1940, some German societies and organizations opposed the [[propaganda]] of the [[Third Reich]] and the [[National Socialist German Workers Party|National Socialist]]-aligned so-called 'Reformation Movement'. Beginning in 1938 however, due to the poor economic situation and the powerful [[Nazi propaganda|national socialist propaganda]], a pro Third Reich mentality developed within the Bukovina German community. Because of this, many increased their preparedness for evacuation.\n\n=== Outbreak of World War II ===\n\n{{Main|Heim ins Reich}}\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 121-0693, Graz, Bahnhof, Volksdeutsche Umsiedler.jpg|thumb|Bukovina and [[Bessarabia Germans]] arriving in [[Graz]], [[Austria]], in November, 1940, on their way of resettlement to Nazi-occupied Poland.]]\n\nWhen Nazi Germany signed the [[Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact]] with the [[Soviet Union]] in 1939 (just before the outbreak of [[World War II]]), the fate (unknown to those affected) of the Germans in Bukovina was sealed. In a secret supplementary protocol, it was agreed (among other points) that the northern part of Bukovina would be annexed by the Soviet Union under a territorial re-organization in [[Central Europe|Central]]-[[Eastern Europe]], with the German sub-populations therein undergoing compulsory resettlement to other future Nazi-occupied territories. Under this accord, the Soviet Union occupied northern Romania in 1940. \n\nConsequently, the Third Reich resettled nearly the entire German population of Bukovina (about 96,000 ethnic Germans) to, most notably, Nazi-occupied [[Poland]], where the incoming evacuees were frequently compensated with expropriated farms. From 1941 to 1944, Bukovina was entirely Romanian. Additionally, most of the Jewish population ({{circa}} 30% of the regional population as a whole) were murdered by the Third Reich in collaboration with fascist Romania under Marshal [[Ion Antonescu]] during the [[Holocaust]].\n\n=== Resettlement in the wake of World War II ===\n\nIn 1944\u201345, as the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Russian front]] moved closer, the Bukovina Germans settled in Polish areas (like the remaining German population), fled westward or wherever they could manage. Some remained in East Germany; others went to Austria. In 1945, the 7,500 or so remaining Germans in Bukovina were evacuated to Germany, ending (except for a very feeble number of individuals) a significant German presence in Bukovina, Romania after 1940. During the postwar era, the Bukovina Germans, as other 'homeland refugees', assimilated into the Federal Republic, Austria, or the [[East Germany|German Democratic Republic]] ({{lang-de|Deutsche Demokratische Republik}}).<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1080/02619288.1984.9974569 | volume=3 | title=The Second World War resettlement of the Bukovina\u2010Germans | year=1984 | journal=Immigrants | pages=49\u201368 | author=Welisch Sophie}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\n\nThe Romanian 1930 census recorded {{circa}} 75,000 ethnic Germans in Bukovina.<ref>Hannelore Baier, Martin Bottesch, u. a.: Geschichte und Traditionen der deutschen Minderheit in Rum\u00e4nien (Lehrbuch f\u00fcr die 6. und 7. Klasse der Schulen mit deutscher Unterrichtssprache). Media\u0219 2007, S. hier 19-36.</ref> Thus, the Bukovina Germans made up 12.46% of the total population of the interwar [[Suceava County]] at that time. According to the [[Demographic history of Romania#20 October 2011 census|2011 Romanian census]], the German minority in southern Bukovina makes up only 0.11% of the total population (including Zipsers and smaller numbers of [[Regat Germans]] in [[F\u0103lticeni]]).<ref>Rezultatele finale ale Recens\u0103m\u00e2ntului din 2011: \u201eTab8. Popula\u021bia stabil\u0103 dup\u0103 etnie \u2013 jude\u021be, municipii, ora\u0219e, comune\". Institutul Na\u021bional de Statistic\u0103 din Rom\u00e2nia. (July, 2013) - http://www.recensamantromania.ro/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/sR_Tab_8.xls</ref>\n\n== {{anchor|Organisation}}Organisations ==\n\nThe political representation of the Bukovina Germans (and of all other [[Germans of Romania|German-speaking groups in contemporary Romania]]) is the [[Democratic Forum of Germans in Romania|DFDR/FDGR]] ({{lang-de|Demokratisches Forum der Deutschen in Rum\u00e4nien}}, {{lang-ro|Forumul Democrat al Germanilor din Rom\u00e2nia}}) which has a local branch operating in Suceava County.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crainou.ro/2015/08/10/spiritul-autentic-german-a-dominat-la-ceas-de-sarbatoare-suceava/| title = Spiritul autentic german a dominat la ceas de s\u0103rb\u0103toare Suceava (in Romanian)| work = Crain Nou| author = Alin Dima| date = 10 August 2015| accessdate = 6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter World War II, the Bukovina Germans who settled in West Germany founded the ''[[Landsmannschaft der Buchenlanddeutschen]] im Bundesrepublik Deutschland'' (Homeland Association of the Bukovina Germans in the [[Germany|Federal Republic of Germany]]).\n\n== {{anchor|People}}Notable people ==\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Elisabeth Axmann]], writer\n* [[Alfred Kuzmany]], Nazi general\n* [[Stefan Baretzki]], Auschwitz guard who murdered more than 8,000 people\n* [[:ro:Franz Des Loges|Franz Des Loges]], former mayor of Suceava\n* [[Alfred Eisenbeisser]], professional footballer\n* [[Shantel|Stefan Hantel]] (partly Bukovina German), musician\n* [[:ro:Anton Keschmann|Anton Keschmann]], politician in the [[Austrian Parliament|Imperial Austrian Parliament]]\n* [[Olha Kobylianska]] (partly Bukovina German), writer\n* [[Roman Neumayer]], inductee into German Ice Hockey Hall of Fame\n* [[:de:George Ostafi|George Ostafi]], abstract painter\n* [[Viktor Pestek]], Auschwitz guard who helped a prisoner escape, for which he was executed in 1944\n* [[Francisc Rainer]], physiologist and anthropologist\n* [[:ro:Ludovic Iosif Urban Rudescu|Ludovic Iosif Urban Rudescu]], biologist\n* [[Gregor von Rezzori]] (partly Bukovina German), writer\n* [[Constantin Schumacher]] (partly German), professional footballer\n* [[:de:Ludwig Adolf Staufe-Simiginowicz|Ludwig Adolf Staufe-Simiginowicz]] (partly Bukovina German), poet\n* [[J\u00f3zef Weber|Joseph Weber]], Roman Catholic prelate\n* [[Lothar R\u0103d\u0103ceanu|Lothar W\u00fcrzel]], journalist, linguist, and politician\n* [[:ro:Hugo Weczerka|Hugo Weczerka]], regional historian\n{{div col end}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of Governors of Bukovina]]\n* [[List of Landeshauptmann of Bukovina]]\n* [[Jahn Cern\u0103u\u021bi]]\n* [[Bukovina Society Headquarters and Museum]]\n* [[Bessarabia Germans]]\n* [[Dobrujan Germans]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.bukovinasociety.org/ Bukovina Society of the Americas]\n\n{{German diaspora}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Bukovina-German people|*]]\n[[Category:People from Bukovina|Germans]]\n[[Category:Ethnic German groups in Romania]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian people of German descent]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Bucov.png|thumb|right|200px|Ethnic groups in entire Bukovina according to the 1930 Romanian census, with German-speaking populations marked in black in both the southern and northern part of the region.]]\n\nThe '''Bukovina Germans''' ({{lang-de|Bukowina Deutsche}} or ''Buchenland Deutsche'') were a [[German diaspora|German]] [[ethnic group]] which settled in [[Bukovina]], a historical region situated at the crossroads of [[Central Europe|Central]] and [[Eastern Europe]]. Their demographic presence lasted from the last quarter of the 18th century, when Bukovina was [[Treaty of K\u00fc\u00e7\u00fck Kaynarca|annexed]] by the [[Habsburg Monarchy|Habsburg Empire]], until 1940, when nearly all Bukovina Germans (almost 100,000 people)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jachomowski |first1=Dirk |title=Die Umsiedlung der Bessarabien-, Bukowina- und Dobrudschadeutschen |date=1984 |publisher=R. Oldenbourg |isbn=9783486524710 |pages=88-95 |language=de}}</ref> were resettled into the Third Reich as a part of ''[[Heim ins Reich]]'' national socialist population transfer policy.\n\nAccording to the 1910 Imperial Austrian census, the Bukovina Germans represented an ethnic minority accounting for approximately 21% of the multi-ethnic population of the [[Duchy of Bukovina]] ({{lang-de|Herzogtum Bukowina}}). Subsequently, in absolute numbers, 75,533 ethnic Germans (or {{circa}} 9% of population) were registered in Bukovina when it was under Royal Romanian administration in an official census in 1930.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Middle Ages ===\n\n{{multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | header    =\n | header_align = left/right/center\n | header_background =\n | footer\n | footer_align = left/right/center\n | footer_background =\n | width     =\n | image1    = Historical Baia Suceava CoA 14th century.png\n | width1    = 135\n | caption1  = 14th century seal of Baia, evoking the legend of [[Hubertus|Saint Hubertus]], the patron saint of hunters\n | image2    = Catedrala Catolic\u0103 din Baia3.jpg\n | width2    = 210\n | caption2  = Ruins of the medieval Roman Catholic Cathedral in [[Baia]] ({{lang-de|Moldenmarkt}}), [[Suceava County]], north-eastern [[Romania]]\n}}\n\nEthnic Germans known as [[Transylvanian Saxons]] (who were mainly craftsmen and merchants stemming from present-day [[Luxembourg]] and [[Rhine]]-[[Moselle]] areas of [[Western Europe]]), had sparsely settled in the western mountainous regions of the [[Moldavia|Principality of Moldavia]] over the course of the late medieval [[Ostsiedlung]] migration (which, in this particular case, took place throughout the 13th and 14th centuries).\n\nThese settlers encouraged trade and urban development. Additionally, they founded (and were also briefly in charge under the title of [[Schulthei\u00df]]) of some notable medieval settlements such as [[Baia]] ({{lang-de|Stadt Molde or Moldenmarkt}}), the first capital of the Principality of Moldavia, or [[T\u00e2rgu Neam\u021b]] ({{lang-de|Niamtz}}).<ref>Hugo Weczerka, Das mittelalterliche und fr\u00fchneuzeitliche Deutschtum im F\u00fcrstentum Moldau, M\u00fcnchen 1960</ref> Subsequently, most of them were gradually [[Cultural assimilation|assimilated]] in these local cultures.\n\n=== Modern Age and Habsburg rule ===\n\nFollowing the [[Russo-Turkish War (1768\u201374)|Russo-Turkish War]], in 1774\u201375 the [[Habsburg Monarchy]] annexed northwestern Moldavia which was predominantly inhabited by [[Romanians]] (as many as 85 percent), with smaller numbers of [[Ukrainians]] (including [[Hutsuls]] and [[Ruthenians]]), [[Armenians]], [[Poland|Poles]], and [[Judaism|Jews]].<ref name=\"romanians1774-1866\">Keith Hitchins. ''The Romanians 1774-1866.'' Oxford: Clarendon Press (1996), pp. 226</ref>\n\nSince then, the region has been known as Bukovina ({{lang-de|Bukowina or Buchenland}}). From 1774 to 1786, settlement of German craftsmen and farmers in existing villages increased (see also: [[Josephine colonization]]). The settlers included [[Zipser Germans]] from the [[Spi\u0161|Zips]] region of [[Upper Hungary]] (present-day [[Slovakia]]), [[Banat Swabians]] from [[Banat]], and ethnic Germans from [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria|Galicia]] (more specifically [[Evangelical Lutheranism|Evangelical Lutheran]] [[Protestants]]), but also immigrants from the [[Palatinate (region)|Rhenish Palatinate]], the [[Margraviate of Baden|Baden]] and [[Landgraviate of Hesse-Darmstadt|Hesse]] principalities, as well as from impoverished regions of the [[Bohemian Forest]] ({{lang-de|B\u00f6hmewald}}).\n\nThus, four distinct [[German dialects|German linguistic groups]] were represented as follows:\n\n* [[Austrian High German]] (''\u00d6sterreichisches Hochdeutsch'') was spoken in urban centres like [[Chernivtsi]] (''Czernowitz''), [[R\u0103d\u0103u\u021bi]] (''Radautz''), [[Suceava]] (''Suczawa''), [[Gura Humorului]] (''Gura Humora''), [[C\u00e2mpulung Moldovenesc|C\u00e2mpulung]] (Kimpolung), and [[Siret]] (''Sereth'');\n* Bohemian-[[Bavarian German]] (''Deutschb\u00f6hmisch'' or ''B\u00f6hmerw\u00e4ldisch'') was spoken by woodsmen in [[Huta Veche|Alth\u00fctte]], [[Cr\u0103sni\u0219oara Nou\u0103|Neuh\u00fctte]], [[Gura Putnei|Karlsberg]], {{ill|Voievodeasa, Romania|lt=F\u00fcrstenthal|ro|Voievodeasa, Suceava}}, [[Vadu Negrilesei|Schwarzthal]], [[Poiana Micului|Buchenhain]], Dealu Ederii (''Lichtenberg''), Bori (early colony in Gura Humorului), and Clit (''Glitt'');\n* [[Palatine Rhine Franconian]] (''Pf\u00e4lzisch'') was spoken in farming villages like [[Arbore|Arbora]], [[B\u0103deu\u021bi|Deutsch Badeutz]], [[Fr\u0103t\u0103u\u021bii Vechi|Alt Fratautz]], [[Fr\u0103t\u0103u\u021bii Noi|Neu Fratautz]], [[Ili\u0219e\u0219ti|Illischestie]], [[I\u021bcani|Itzkany]], [[Satu Mare, Suceava|Deutsch Satulmare]] and [[Tereblecea|Tereblestie]];\n* [[Zipser German]] (''Zipserisch'') was spoken by mine workers and their descendants in [[C\u00e2rlibaba]] (''Mariensee'' or ''Ludwigsdorf''), [[Iacobeni, Suceava|Iacobeni]] (''Jakobeny''), [[Stulpicani]] (''Stulpikany''), and elsewhere.<ref>Willi Kosiul, ''Die Bukowina und ihre Buchenlanddeutschen'' (2012, {{ISBN|3942867095}}), volume 2</ref>\n\nDuring the 19th century, the developing German middle class comprised much of the intellectual and political elite of the region; the language of official business and education was predominantly German, particularly among the upper classes. Population growth and a shortage of land led to the establishment of daughter settlements in [[Galicia (Eastern Europe)|Galicia]], [[Bessarabia]], and [[Dobruja]].\n\nAfter 1840, a shortage of land caused the decline into poverty of the German rural lower classes; in the late 19th century parts of the German rural population alongside a few Romanians emigrated to the Americas, mainly to the [[United States]] (most notably to [[Kansas]]) but also to [[Canada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bukovinasociety.org |title=Bukovina Society of the Americas Home Page |publisher=Bukovinasociety.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com/~bakerroots/bukovina.html |title=Bukovina Germans |publisher=Freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bukovinasociety.org/ellingson-brzl-2001-a.html |title=Bukovina Immigration to North America |publisher=Bukovinasociety.org |accessdate=2013-03-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120609062842/http://www.bukovinasociety.org/ellingson-brzl-2001-a.html# |archive-date=2012-06-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBetween 1849 and 1851, and from 1863 to 1918, the [[Duchy of Bukovina]] became an independent [[crown land]] within the [[Austrian Empire]] (see also: [[Cisleithania]]). However, in comparison to other Austrian crown lands, Bukovina remained an underdeveloped region on the periphery of the realm, primarily supplying raw materials.\n\nThe [[University of Chernivtsi|Franz Josephs Universit\u00e4t]] in Czernowitz was founded in 1875, then the easternmost German-speaking university. In 1910\u20131911, the Bukovinan Reconciliation (a political agreement between the peoples of Bukovina and their political representatives in the [[Landtag]] assembly on the question of autonomous regional administration) took place between the representatives of the nationalities.\n\n<gallery class=center>\nFile:Chernivtsi - \u0427\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0456\u0432\u0446\u0456 1.jpg|[[Chernivtsi|Cern\u0103u\u021bi]] ({{lang-de|Czernowitz}}) town hall, {{circa}} 1905\nFile:Palatul Administrativ din Suceava19.jpg|[[Suceava]] ({{lang-de|Suczawa}}) town hall (nowadays administrative palace), early 20th century\nFile:Biserica romano-catolica din Gura Humorului11.jpg|Roman Catholic church in [[Gura Humorului]] ({{lang-de|Gura Humora}}), early 20th century\nFile:Jakobeny (BildID 15716697).jpg|View of [[Iacobeni, Suceava|Iacobeni]] ({{lang-de|Jakobeny}}), a Zipser German village, early 20th century\nFile:Vatra Dornei 1.jpg|Bilingual German-Romanian postcard from [[Vatra Dornei]] ({{lang-de|Dorna-Watra}}), early 20th century\nFile:Biserica Adormirea Maicii Domnului din Ilisesti.jpg|Former Evangelical Lutheran (now Orthodox) church in [[Ili\u0219e\u0219ti]] ({{lang-de|llischestie}})\n</gallery>\n\n=== Early 20th century and Kingdom of Romania ===\n\n[[File:Deutsche_Siedlungsgebiete_in_Osteuropa_1925.jpg|thumb|right|Map of German minorities in Eastern Europe during the interwar period, also highlighting German settlements in the Kingdom of Romania, including Bukovina.]]\n\nFrom 1918 to 1919, following the end of [[World War I]] and the dissolution of the Austro-Hungarian Empire, Bukovina became part of the [[Kingdom of Romania]]. At the [[General Congress of Bukovina]] held on November 28, 1918,<ref name=\"Livezeanu2000\">{{cite book|author=Irina Livezeanu|title=Cultural Politics in Greater Romania: Regionalism, Nation Building & Ethnic Struggle, 1918-1930|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5ysbpAyJjoAC&pg=PA59|year=2000|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=0-8014-8688-2|pages=59\u2013}}</ref> the political representatives of the Bukovina Germans voted and supported the union of Bukovina with the Romanian kingdom, alongside the Romanian and Polish representatives.\n\nFrom 1933 up until 1940, some German societies and organizations opposed the [[propaganda]] of the [[Third Reich]] and the [[National Socialist German Workers Party|National Socialist]]-aligned so-called 'Reformation Movement'. Beginning in 1938 however, due to the poor economic situation and the powerful [[Nazi propaganda|national socialist propaganda]], a pro Third Reich mentality developed within the Bukovina German community. Because of this, many increased their preparedness for evacuation.\n\n=== Outbreak of World War II ===\n\n{{Main|Heim ins Reich}}\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 121-0693, Graz, Bahnhof, Volksdeutsche Umsiedler.jpg|thumb|Bukovina and [[Bessarabia Germans]] arriving in [[Graz]], [[Austria]], in November, 1940, on their way of resettlement to Nazi-occupied Poland.]]\n\nWhen Nazi Germany signed the [[Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact]] with the [[Soviet Union]] in 1939 (just before the outbreak of [[World War II]]), the fate (unknown to those affected) of the Germans in Bukovina was sealed. In a secret supplementary protocol, it was agreed (among other points) that the northern part of Bukovina would be annexed by the Soviet Union under a territorial re-organization in [[Central Europe|Central]]-[[Eastern Europe]], with the German sub-populations therein undergoing compulsory resettlement to other future Nazi-occupied territories. Under this accord, the Soviet Union occupied northern Romania in 1940. \n\nConsequently, the Third Reich resettled nearly the entire German population of Bukovina (about 96,000 ethnic Germans) to, most notably, Nazi-occupied [[Poland]], where the incoming evacuees were frequently compensated with expropriated farms. From 1941 to 1944, Bukovina was entirely Romanian. Additionally, most of the Jewish population ({{circa}} 30% of the regional population as a whole) were murdered by the Third Reich in collaboration with fascist Romania under Marshal [[Ion Antonescu]] during the [[Holocaust]].\n\n=== Resettlement in the wake of World War II ===\n\nIn 1944\u201345, as the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Russian front]] moved closer, the Bukovina Germans settled in Polish areas (like the remaining German population), fled westward or wherever they could manage. Some remained in East Germany; others went to Austria. In 1945, the 7,500 or so remaining Germans in Bukovina were evacuated to Germany, ending (except for a very feeble number of individuals) a significant German presence in Bukovina, Romania after 1940. During the postwar era, the Bukovina Germans, as other 'homeland refugees', assimilated into the Federal Republic, Austria, or the [[East Germany|German Democratic Republic]] ({{lang-de|Deutsche Demokratische Republik}}).<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1080/02619288.1984.9974569 | volume=3 | title=The Second World War resettlement of the Bukovina\u2010Germans | year=1984 | journal=Immigrants | pages=49\u201368 | author=Welisch Sophie}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\n\nThe Romanian 1930 census recorded {{circa}} 75,000 ethnic Germans in Bukovina.<ref>Hannelore Baier, Martin Bottesch, u. a.: Geschichte und Traditionen der deutschen Minderheit in Rum\u00e4nien (Lehrbuch f\u00fcr die 6. und 7. Klasse der Schulen mit deutscher Unterrichtssprache). Media\u0219 2007, S. hier 19-36.</ref> Thus, the Bukovina Germans made up 12.46% of the total population of the interwar [[Suceava County]] at that time. According to the [[Demographic history of Romania#20 October 2011 census|2011 Romanian census]], the German minority in southern Bukovina makes up only 0.11% of the total population (including Zipsers and smaller numbers of [[Regat Germans]] in [[F\u0103lticeni]]).<ref>Rezultatele finale ale Recens\u0103m\u00e2ntului din 2011: \u201eTab8. Popula\u021bia stabil\u0103 dup\u0103 etnie \u2013 jude\u021be, municipii, ora\u0219e, comune\". Institutul Na\u021bional de Statistic\u0103 din Rom\u00e2nia. (July, 2013) - http://www.recensamantromania.ro/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/sR_Tab_8.xls</ref>\n\n== {{anchor|Organisation}}Organisations ==\n\nThe political representation of the Bukovina Germans (and of all other [[Germans of Romania|German-speaking groups in contemporary Romania]]) is the [[Democratic Forum of Germans in Romania|DFDR/FDGR]] ({{lang-de|Demokratisches Forum der Deutschen in Rum\u00e4nien}}, {{lang-ro|Forumul Democrat al Germanilor din Rom\u00e2nia}}) which has a local branch operating in Suceava County.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crainou.ro/2015/08/10/spiritul-autentic-german-a-dominat-la-ceas-de-sarbatoare-suceava/| title = Spiritul autentic german a dominat la ceas de s\u0103rb\u0103toare Suceava (in Romanian)| work = Crain Nou| author = Alin Dima| date = 10 August 2015| accessdate = 6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter World War II, the Bukovina Germans who settled in West Germany founded the ''[[Landsmannschaft der Buchenlanddeutschen]] im Bundesrepublik Deutschland'' (Homeland Association of the Bukovina Germans in the [[Germany|Federal Republic of Germany]]).\n\n== {{anchor|People}}Notable people ==\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Elisabeth Axmann]], writer\n* [[Stefan Baretzki]], Auschwitz guard who murdered more than 8,000 people\n* [[:ro:Franz Des Loges|Franz Des Loges]], former mayor of Suceava\n* [[Alfred Eisenbeisser]], professional footballer\n* [[Shantel|Stefan Hantel]] (partly Bukovina German), musician\n* [[:ro:Anton Keschmann|Anton Keschmann]], politician in the [[Austrian Parliament|Imperial Austrian Parliament]]\n* [[Olha Kobylianska]] (partly Bukovina German), writer\n* [[Roman Neumayer]], inductee into German Ice Hockey Hall of Fame\n* [[:de:George Ostafi|George Ostafi]], abstract painter\n* [[Viktor Pestek]], Auschwitz guard who helped a prisoner escape, for which he was executed in 1944\n* [[Francisc Rainer]], physiologist and anthropologist\n* [[:ro:Ludovic Iosif Urban Rudescu|Ludovic Iosif Urban Rudescu]], biologist\n* [[Gregor von Rezzori]] (partly Bukovina German), writer\n* [[Constantin Schumacher]] (partly German), professional footballer\n* [[:de:Ludwig Adolf Staufe-Simiginowicz|Ludwig Adolf Staufe-Simiginowicz]] (partly Bukovina German), poet\n* [[J\u00f3zef Weber|Joseph Weber]], Roman Catholic prelate\n* [[Lothar R\u0103d\u0103ceanu|Lothar W\u00fcrzel]], journalist, linguist, and politician\n* [[:ro:Hugo Weczerka|Hugo Weczerka]], regional historian\n{{div col end}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of Governors of Bukovina]]\n* [[List of Landeshauptmann of Bukovina]]\n* [[Jahn Cern\u0103u\u021bi]]\n* [[Bukovina Society Headquarters and Museum]]\n* [[Bessarabia Germans]]\n* [[Dobrujan Germans]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.bukovinasociety.org/ Bukovina Society of the Americas]\n\n{{German diaspora}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Bukovina-German people|*]]\n[[Category:People from Bukovina|Germans]]\n[[Category:Ethnic German groups in Romania]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian people of German descent]]\n", "name_user": "Rosenborg BK Fan", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e{{anchor|People}}Notable people:Minor update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bukovina_Germans"}
{"title_page": "Railway stations in Coimbatore", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n\n{{Coimbatore\u2013Shoranur line}}\n[[File:Coimbatore_junction.jpg|200 px|thumb|Coimbatore Main]] \n[[File:North_coimbatore_railway_yard.jpg|200 px|thumb|Coimbatore North]]\n\n'''Coimbatore''' or '''Kovai''' is a major city in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Tamil Nadu]]. It is the second largest city and [[urban agglomeration]] in the state after [[Chennai]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypopulation.de/India-TamilNadu.html|title=Tamil N\u0101du (India): State, Major Cities, Towns & Agglomerations - Statistics & Maps on City Population|access-date=28 June 2015}}</ref> and the sixteenth largest [[List of million-plus urban agglomerations in India|urban agglomeration in India]]. It is administered by the [[Coimbatore Municipal Corporation]] and is the administrative capital of [[Coimbatore district]]. It is one of the fastest growing tier-II cities in India and a major textile, industrial, commercial, educational, information technology, healthcare and manufacturing hub of Tamil Nadu.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pibmumbai.gov.in/scripts/detail.asp?releaseId=E2011IS3 |title=Indian Government press release|publisher=Press Information Bureau, Government of India|date=31 October 2011 |access-date=31 January 2013}}</ref> It is often referred to as the \"[[Manchester]] of [[South India]]\" due to its cotton production and textile industries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.winentrance.com/general_knowledge/india_misscellaneous/nick-names-indian-places.html|title=Nicknames of places in India|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=EMA-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=XkwMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6189,9133960&dq=manchester+of+south+india+coimbatore&hl=en|title=Manchester of South India|newspaper=The Indian Express|access-date=28 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nTrain service in Coimbatore started in 1861, upon construction of the [[Podanur]] \u2013 [[Madras]] line connecting Kerala and the west coast with the rest of India.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-hist.html|title = IR History \u2013 Early days|work= 1832-1869 | publisher= IRFCA| access-date = 23 December 2013}}</ref> Coimbatore lies on the [[Coimbatore - Shoranur railway line|Coimbatore - Shoranur]] [[Indian gauge|Broad gauge railway line]].  Until 1956, the [[Coimbatore railway division]] was functioning with Podanur as its Headquarters.  In 1956, the headquarters was shifted to Olavakkode, of Kerala state, and was named Olavakkod railway division.  In 1980, Olavakkod division was renamed Palakkad railway division.  It comprised Kerala and western districts of Tamil Nadu.  The revenue from railway stations of western Tamil Nadu, especially Coimbatore, was used to develop railway stations in Kerala, which some saw as unfair.  Because of this, protests arose in Tamil Nadu to form new railway division with Coimbatore as its headquarters.  Ultimately, a new Salem railway division was carved out of the Palakkad railway division in 2006 with Salem as its headquarters.  The city falls under the [[Salem railway division|Salem Division]] of the [[Southern Railway zone]] of [[Indian Railways]]. The major railway station is the [[Coimbatore Junction railway station|Coimbatore Junction]] which is the second largest income generating station in the [[Southern Railway zone]] after [[Chennai Central]] and is amongst the top hundred booking stations of [[Indian Railways]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.indianrail.gov.in/7days_Avl.html|title = Indian Railways Passenger Reservation Enquiry|work=Availability in trains for Top 100 Booking Stations of Indian Railways |last= |first= | publisher= IRFCA| access-date = 23 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.raac.co.in/railway.php|title=Railways in Coimbatore|publisher=raac.co.in|access-date=6 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/coimbatore-junction-neglected/article2413499.ece|title=Coimbatore Junction neglected|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=31 August 2011}}</ref> Other major railway stations catering to the city include [[Coimbatore North Junction railway station|Coimbatore North Junction]], [[Podanur Junction railway station|Podanur Junction]] and minor stations at [[Peelamedu]], [[Singanallur]], [[Irugur Junction railway station|Irugur Junction]], [[Perianaikanpalayam]], [[Madukkarai railway station|Madukkarai]], Somanur, [[Sulur]] & Thudiyalur .\n\n==List of railway stations==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"text-align:center; width:60%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"12\" | <span style=\"color:BLACK;\">'''List of railway stations in Coimbatore'''</span>\n|-\n|'''S.No.'''\n|'''Name'''\n|'''Native name'''\n|'''Station Code'''\n|-\n| 1 || {{rws|Coimbatore Junction}} || \u0b95\u0bcb\u0baf\u0bae\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0b9a\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1  || CBE\n|-\n| 2 || {{rws|Podanur Junction}} || \u0baa\u0bcb\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0ba9\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0b9a\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1  || PTJ\n|-\n| 3 || {{rws|Coimbatore North Junction}} || \u0b95\u0bcb\u0baf\u0bae\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0bb5\u0b9f\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1 \u0b9a\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1  || CBF\n|-\n| 4 || {{rws|Peelamedu}} || \u0baa\u0bc0\u0bb3\u0bae\u0bc7\u0b9f\u0bc1  || PLMD\n|-\n| 5 || {{rws|Singanallur}} || \u0b9a\u0bbf\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbe\u0ba8\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd  || SHI\n|-\n| 6 || {{rws|Irugur Junction}} || \u0b87\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0b9a\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1  || IGU\n|-\n| 7 || {{rws|Periyanaickenpalayam railway station}} || \u0baa\u0bc6\u0bb0\u0bbf\u0baf\u0ba8\u0bbe\u0baf\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bbe\u0bb3\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bae\u0bcd  || PKM\n|-\n| 8 || {{rws|Madukkarai}} || \u0bae\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb0\u0bc8  || MDKI\n|-\n| 9 || {{rws|Tiruppur Somanur railway station}} || \u0b9a\u0bcb\u0bae\u0ba9\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd  || SNO\n|-\n| 10 || {{rws|Sulur Road railway station}} || \u0b9a\u0bc2\u0bb2\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0bb0\u0bcb\u0b9f\u0bc1  || SUU\n|-\n| 11 || {{rws|Thudiyalur railway station}} || \u0ba4\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bb2\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd  || TDE\n|-\n| 12 || {{rws|Karamadai railway station}} || \u0b95\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0bae\u0b9f\u0bc8  || KAY\n|-\n| 13 || {{rws|Kinathukadavu railway station}} || \u0b95\u0bbf\u0ba3\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0b9f\u0bb5\u0bc1    || CNV\n|-\n| 14 || [[Ettimadai railway station]] ||\u0b8e\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0bae\u0b9f\u0bc8 || ETMD\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"text-align:center; width:60%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"12\" | <span style=\"color:BLACK;\">'''List of Defunct railway stations in Coimbatore'''</span>\n|-\n|'''S.No.'''\n|'''Name'''\n|'''Status'''\n|'''Station Code'''\n|-\n| 1 || {{rws|Chettipalayam}} || Defunct || CIM\n|-\n| 2 || Urumandampalayam ||closed   || \n|-\n| 3 ||  Veerapandi ||closed || \n|-\n| 4 || Pudupalayam || closed || \n|-\n| 5 || Nallatipalayam||closed   || \n|-\n| 6 || Koilpalayam ||closed  || \n|-\n| 7 || Tamaraikulam||closed || \n|}\n\n==Metrorail==\n{{main|Coimbatore Metro}}\nThree metrorail routes have been proposed. Two circular routes, in the northern and southern parts of the city and a dual linear line connecting the Eastern and Western parts. The Northern Route starts from [[Gandhipuram]] via [[Ganapathy]], Sivanandha colony, Saibaba colony, [[R. S. Puram, Coimbatore|RS Puram]], Townhall, [[Coimbatore Junction|City Railway Station]] and ends in [[Gandhipuram]]. The second circular Route starts from [[Podanur Junction|Podanur]] via Trichy Road, Sungam, Redfields, Race Course, [[Coimbatore Junction|City Railway Station]], [[Ukkadam]] and ends at [[Podanur Junction|Podanur]]. A linear line was also proposed from [[Chinniampalayam]], [[Coimbatore International Airport]], CODISSIA, [[PSG Tech]], [[Lakshmi Mills]], [[Gandhipuram]], [[Coimbatore North Junction]], Cowley Brown Road and [[Tamil Nadu Agricultural University|TNAU]]. Recently [[Vadavalli]] and [[Thondamuthur]] are the two new areas that has been included in the linear line as part of the phase extension.<ref>{{cite news|agency=Times News Network |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-08-22/coimbatore/33321368_1_monorail-project-kozhikode-monorail-monorail-network |title=Corporation speeds up work to begin mono rail project |newspaper=The Times of India |date= 22 August 2012|accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Karthik Madhavan |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/article3856605.ece |title=A fresh look at Mass Public Transport System for city |newspaper=The Hindu |date=2012-09-04 |accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref> In 2017,Tamil Nadu government announced that CMRL would prepare DPR and feasibility report for Coimbatore metro rail project and will be funded by German-based company.\n\n==Coimbatore suburban circular railway==\n[[Coimbatore suburban circular railway]] is a circular suburban railway planned for coimbatore city. The circular railway line will help run through Coimbatore Junction, Podanur, Vellalore, Irugur, Singanallur, Peelamedu and Coimbatore North (see map). This will certainly help decongest the city roads. A senior official with the Salem division says if the revival of an old line can bring about so many benefits, it can be considered.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Railway stations in Tamil Nadu}}\n{{Railways in Southern India}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Coimbatore|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of railway stations in India|Coimbatore]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n\n{{Coimbatore\u2013Shoranur line}}\n[[File:Coimbatore_junction.jpg|200 px|thumb|Coimbatore Main]] \n[[File:North_coimbatore_railway_yard.jpg|200 px|thumb|Coimbatore North]]\n\n'''Coimbatore''' or '''Kovai''' is a major city in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Tamil Nadu]]. It is the second largest city and [[urban agglomeration]] in the state after [[Chennai]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypopulation.de/India-TamilNadu.html|title=Tamil N\u0101du (India): State, Major Cities, Towns & Agglomerations - Statistics & Maps on City Population|access-date=28 June 2015}}</ref> and the sixteenth largest [[List of million-plus urban agglomerations in India|urban agglomeration in India]]. It is administered by the [[Coimbatore Municipal Corporation]] and is the administrative capital of [[Coimbatore district]]. It is one of the fastest growing tier-II cities in India and a major textile, industrial, commercial, educational, information technology, healthcare and manufacturing hub of Tamil Nadu.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pibmumbai.gov.in/scripts/detail.asp?releaseId=E2011IS3 |title=Indian Government press release|publisher=Press Information Bureau, Government of India|date=31 October 2011 |access-date=31 January 2013}}</ref> It is often referred to as the \"[[Manchester]] of [[South India]]\" due to its cotton production and textile industries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.winentrance.com/general_knowledge/india_misscellaneous/nick-names-indian-places.html|title=Nicknames of places in India|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=EMA-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=XkwMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6189,9133960&dq=manchester+of+south+india+coimbatore&hl=en|title=Manchester of South India|newspaper=The Indian Express|access-date=28 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nTrain service in Coimbatore started in 1861, upon construction of the [[Podanur]] \u2013 [[Madras]] line connecting Kerala and the west coast with the rest of India.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-hist.html|title = IR History \u2013 Early days|work= 1832-1869 | publisher= IRFCA| access-date = 23 December 2013}}</ref> Coimbatore lies on the [[Coimbatore - Shoranur railway line|Coimbatore - Shoranur]] [[Indian gauge|Broad gauge railway line]].  Until 1956, the [[Coimbatore railway division]] was functioning with Podanur as its Headquarters.  In 1956, the headquarters was shifted to Olavakkode, of Kerala state, and was named Olavakkod railway division.  In 1980, Olavakkod division was renamed Palakkad railway division.  It comprised Kerala and western districts of Tamil Nadu.  The revenue from railway stations of western Tamil Nadu, especially Coimbatore, was used to develop railway stations in Kerala, which some saw as unfair.  Because of this, protests arose in Tamil Nadu to form new railway division with Coimbatore as its headquarters.  Ultimately, a new Salem railway division was carved out of the Palakkad railway division in 2006 with Salem as its headquarters.  The city falls under the [[Salem railway division|Salem Division]] of the [[Southern Railway zone]] of [[Indian Railways]]. The major railway station is the [[Coimbatore Junction railway station|Coimbatore Junction]] which is the second largest income generating station in the [[Southern Railway zone]] after [[Chennai Central]] and is amongst the top hundred booking stations of [[Indian Railways]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.indianrail.gov.in/7days_Avl.html|title = Indian Railways Passenger Reservation Enquiry|work=Availability in trains for Top 100 Booking Stations of Indian Railways |last= |first= | publisher= IRFCA| access-date = 23 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.raac.co.in/railway.php|title=Railways in Coimbatore|publisher=raac.co.in|access-date=6 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/coimbatore-junction-neglected/article2413499.ece|title=Coimbatore Junction neglected|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=31 August 2011}}</ref> Other major railway stations catering to the city include [[Coimbatore North Junction railway station|Coimbatore North Junction]], [[Podanur Junction railway station|Podanur Junction]] and minor stations at [[Peelamedu]], [[Singanallur]], [[Irugur Junction railway station|Irugur Junction]], [[Perianaikanpalayam]], [[Madukkarai railway station|Madukkarai]], Somanur, [[Sulur]] & Thudiyalur .\n\n==List of railway stations==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"text-align:center; width:60%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"12\" | <span style=\"color:BLACK;\">'''List of railway stations in Coimbatore'''</span>\n|-\n|'''S.No.'''\n|'''Name'''\n|'''Native name'''\n|'''Station Code'''\n|-\n| 1 || {{rws|Coimbatore Junction}} || \u0b95\u0bcb\u0baf\u0bae\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0b9a\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1  || CBE\n|-\n| 2 || {{rws|Podanur Junction}} || \u0baa\u0bcb\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0ba9\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0b9a\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1  || PTJ\n|-\n| 3 || {{rws|Coimbatore North Junction}} || \u0b95\u0bcb\u0baf\u0bae\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0bb5\u0b9f\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bc1 \u0b9a\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1  || CBF\n|-\n| 4 || {{rws|Peelamedu}} || \u0baa\u0bc0\u0bb3\u0bae\u0bc7\u0b9f\u0bc1  || PLMD\n|-\n| 5 || {{rws|Singanallur}} || \u0b9a\u0bbf\u0b99\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bbe\u0ba8\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb2\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd  || SHI\n|-\n| 6 || {{rws|Irugur Junction}} || \u0b87\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0b9a\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bc1  || IGU\n|-\n| 7 || {{rws|Periyanaickenpalayam railway station}} || \u0baa\u0bc6\u0bb0\u0bbf\u0baf\u0ba8\u0bbe\u0baf\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bbe\u0bb3\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bae\u0bcd  || PKM\n|-\n| 8 || {{rws|Madukkarai}} || \u0bae\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb0\u0bc8  || MDKI\n|-\n| 9 || {{rws|Tiruppur Somanur railway station}} || \u0b9a\u0bcb\u0bae\u0ba9\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd  || SNO\n|-\n| 10 || {{rws|Sulur Road railway station}} || \u0b9a\u0bc2\u0bb2\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0bb0\u0bcb\u0b9f\u0bc1  || SUU\n|-\n| 11 || {{rws|Thudiyalur railway station}} || \u0ba4\u0bc1\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bb2\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd  || TDE\n|-\n| 12 || {{rws|Karamadai railway station}} || \u0b95\u0bbe\u0bb0\u0bae\u0b9f\u0bc8  || KAY\n|-\n| 13 || {{rws|Kinathukadavu railway station}} || \u0b95\u0bbf\u0ba3\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0b9f\u0bb5\u0bc1    || CNV\n|-\n| 14 || {{rws|Ettimadai railway station}} ||\u0b8e\u0b9f\u0bcd\u0b9f\u0bbf\u0bae\u0b9f\u0bc8 || ETMD\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"text-align:center; width:60%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"12\" | <span style=\"color:BLACK;\">'''List of Defunct railway stations in Coimbatore'''</span>\n|-\n|'''S.No.'''\n|'''Name'''\n|'''Status'''\n|'''Station Code'''\n|-\n| 1 || {{rws|Chettipalayam}} || Defunct || CIM\n|-\n| 2 || Urumandampalayam ||closed   || \n|-\n| 3 ||  Veerapandi ||closed || \n|-\n| 4 || Pudupalayam || closed || \n|-\n| 5 || Nallatipalayam||closed   || \n|-\n| 6 || Koilpalayam ||closed  || \n|-\n| 7 || Tamaraikulam||closed || \n|}\n\n==Metrorail==\n{{main|Coimbatore Metro}}\nThree metrorail routes have been proposed. Two circular routes, in the northern and southern parts of the city and a dual linear line connecting the Eastern and Western parts. The Northern Route starts from [[Gandhipuram]] via [[Ganapathy]], Sivanandha colony, Saibaba colony, [[R. S. Puram, Coimbatore|RS Puram]], Townhall, [[Coimbatore Junction|City Railway Station]] and ends in [[Gandhipuram]]. The second circular Route starts from [[Podanur Junction|Podanur]] via Trichy Road, Sungam, Redfields, Race Course, [[Coimbatore Junction|City Railway Station]], [[Ukkadam]] and ends at [[Podanur Junction|Podanur]]. A linear line was also proposed from [[Chinniampalayam]], [[Coimbatore International Airport]], CODISSIA, [[PSG Tech]], [[Lakshmi Mills]], [[Gandhipuram]], [[Coimbatore North Junction]], Cowley Brown Road and [[Tamil Nadu Agricultural University|TNAU]]. Recently [[Vadavalli]] and [[Thondamuthur]] are the two new areas that has been included in the linear line as part of the phase extension.<ref>{{cite news|agency=Times News Network |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-08-22/coimbatore/33321368_1_monorail-project-kozhikode-monorail-monorail-network |title=Corporation speeds up work to begin mono rail project |newspaper=The Times of India |date= 22 August 2012|accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Karthik Madhavan |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/article3856605.ece |title=A fresh look at Mass Public Transport System for city |newspaper=The Hindu |date=2012-09-04 |accessdate=2013-01-31}}</ref> In 2017,Tamil Nadu government announced that CMRL would prepare DPR and feasibility report for Coimbatore metro rail project and will be funded by German-based company.\n\n==Coimbatore suburban circular railway==\n[[Coimbatore suburban circular railway]] is a circular suburban railway planned for coimbatore city. The circular railway line will help run through Coimbatore Junction, Podanur, Vellalore, Irugur, Singanallur, Peelamedu and Coimbatore North (see map). This will certainly help decongest the city roads. A senior official with the Salem division says if the revival of an old line can bring about so many benefits, it can be considered.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Railway stations in Tamil Nadu}}\n{{Railways in Southern India}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Coimbatore|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of railway stations in India|Coimbatore]]\n", "name_user": "Harinath Krishnamurthy", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Railway_stations_in_Coimbatore"}
{"title_page": "Takashi Imamura", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese rower}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Takashi Imamura\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Japanese\n| sport          = [[rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth year and age|1934}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Takashi Imamura''' (born 1934) is a Japanese [[rowing (sport)|rower]]. He competed in the [[Rowing at the 1956 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's eight|men's eight]] event at the [[1956 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/im/takashi-imamura-1.html |title=Takashi Imamura Olympic Results |accessdate=11 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Imamura, Takashi}}\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Japanese male rowers]]\n[[Category:Olympic rowers of Japan]]\n[[Category:Rowers at the 1956 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Japan-rowing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Japanese rower}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Takashi Imamura\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Japanese\n| sport          = [[rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth year and age|1934}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Takashi Imamura''' (born 1934) is a Japanese [[rowing (sport)|rower]]. He competed in the [[Rowing at the 1956 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's eight|men's eight]] event at the [[1956 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/im/takashi-imamura-1.html |title=Takashi Imamura Olympic Results |accessdate=11 August 2018}}</ref>\n