{"title_page": "The Priory (play)", "text_new": "{{Infobox play\n| name       = The Priory\n| image      = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt  = \n| caption    = \n| writer     = Michael Wynne\n| setting    = \n| premiere   = 2009\n| place      = [[Royal Court Theatre]]<br>[[London]]\n| orig_lang  = \n| series     = \n| subject    = \n| genre      = \n| web        = \n}}\n\n'''''The Priory''''' is a play by [[Michael Wynne (playwright)|Michael Wynne]] that opened at the downstairs theatre of the [[Royal Court Theatre]] in [[London]] in 2009. The production starred [[Jessica Hynes]], [[Rupert Penry-Jones]], [[Charlotte Riley]], [[Alastair Mackenzie]], [[Joseph Millson]] and [[Rachael Stirling]]. After receiving good reviews, its run was extended.  Michael Wynne won the Olivier Award for 'Best New Comedy' for ''The Priory''. Stirling was nominated for a [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Performance in a Supporting Role]] for her role as Rebecca.<ref name=\"Evening Standard\">{{cite news | author=Viv Groskop | title=Rachael Stirling is a rising stage star \u2013 and she's in love with her ass | url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/theatre/article-23806855-rachael-stirling-is-a-rising-stage-star-and-shes-in-love-with-her-ass.do | work=The London Evening Standard | date=17 February 2010 | accessdate=14 July 2011 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605071255/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/theatre/article-23806855-rachael-stirling-is-a-rising-stage-star-and-shes-in-love-with-her-ass.do | archivedate=5 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nFollowing her split from her boyfriend, Kate decides to invite a group of her closest friends to a renovated and supposedly haunted priory, for a New Year's Eve party. However, as the drinks and drugs start to flow, personal revelations begin to emerge leading to near tragedy and a fraught morning after.\n\n==Characters==\n* Kate: a budding author who has suffered personal tragedy throughout the previous year and is looking forward to a better one. \n*Daniel: a gay architect who surfs the internet looking for love.\n* Carl: a \"resting\" actor, best known for a coffee commercial, now happily working in a garden centre and Kate's college boyfriend.\n* Rebecca: Carl's [[BAFTA]] award winning wife and obsessive mother of his two small children.\n* Ben: an award winning travel writer.\n* Laura: a counter girl at [[Harvey Nichols]] and Ben's fianc\u00e9 of one day, the pair having met the night before.\n\n==Original production==\nThe premiere of the play was at the [[Royal Court Theatre]] in London. It was directed by [[Jeremy Herrin]] and starred [[Jessica Hynes]] as Kate, [[Joseph Millson]] as Daniel, [[Rupert Penry-Jones]] as Carl, [[Rachael Stirling]] as Rebecca, [[Alastair Mackenzie]] as Ben and [[Charlotte Riley]] as Laura.\n\n\"...Wynnes sharp, funny writing and Jeremy Herrins exceptionally well acted production ensure total authenticity so that by the end the play feels positively radical in this main stage bastion of the cutting edge... His (Michael Wynne's) control of situation and character is impressively mature...\" - Michael Coveney WHATS ON STAGE\n\n\"...It is a perceptive piece, laced with Wynne\u2019s customary wit and insight. And it has serious points to make about success, failure, peer pressure and loneliness...\" - Sarah Hemming FINANCIAL TIMES\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{OlivierAward Comedy 2001\u20132025}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Priory}}\n[[Category:2009 plays]]\n[[Category:English plays]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox play\n| name       = The Priory\n| image      = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt  = \n| caption    = \n| writer     = Michael Wynne\n| setting    = \n| premiere   = 2009\n| place      = [[Royal Court Theatre]]<br>[[London]]\n| orig_lang  = \n| series     = \n| subject    = \n| genre      = \n| web        = \n}}\n\n'''''The Priory''''' is a play by [[Michael Wynne (playwright)|Michael Wynne]] that opened at the downstairs theatre of the [[Royal Court Theatre]] in [[London]] in 2009. The production starred [[Jessica Hynes]], [[Rupert Penry-Jones]], [[Charlotte Riley]], [[Alastair Mackenzie]], [[Joseph Millson]] and [[Rachael Stirling]]. After receiving good reviews, its run was extended.  Michael Wynne won the Olivier Award for 'Best New Comedy' for \"The Priory\". Stirling was nominated for a [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Performance in a Supporting Role]] for her role as Rebecca.<ref name=\"Evening Standard\">{{cite news | author=Viv Groskop | title=Rachael Stirling is a rising stage star \u2013 and she's in love with her ass | url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/theatre/article-23806855-rachael-stirling-is-a-rising-stage-star-and-shes-in-love-with-her-ass.do | work=The London Evening Standard | date=17 February 2010 | accessdate=14 July 2011 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605071255/http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/theatre/article-23806855-rachael-stirling-is-a-rising-stage-star-and-shes-in-love-with-her-ass.do | archivedate=5 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nFollowing her split from her boyfriend, Kate decides to invite a group of her closest friends to a renovated and supposedly haunted priory, for a New Year's Eve party. However, as the drinks and drugs start to flow, personal revelations begin to emerge leading to near tragedy and a fraught morning after.\n\n==Characters==\n* Kate: a budding author who has suffered personal tragedy throughout the previous year and is looking forward to a better one. \n*Daniel: a gay architect who surfs the internet looking for love.\n* Carl: a \"resting\" actor, best known for a coffee commercial, now happily working in a garden centre and Kate's college boyfriend.\n* Rebecca: Carl's [[BAFTA]] award winning wife and obsessive mother of his two small children.\n* Ben: an award winning travel writer.\n* Laura: a counter girl at [[Harvey Nichols]] and Ben's fianc\u00e9 of one day, the pair having met the night before.\n\n==Original production==\nThe premiere of the play was at the [[Royal Court Theatre]] in London. It was directed by [[Jeremy Herrin]] and starred [[Jessica Hynes]] as Kate, [[Joseph Millson]] as Daniel, [[Rupert Penry-Jones]] as Carl, [[Rachael Stirling]] as Rebecca, [[Alastair Mackenzie]] as Ben and [[Charlotte Riley]] as Laura.\n\n\"...Wynnes sharp, funny writing and Jeremy Herrins exceptionally well acted production ensure total authenticity so that by the end the play feels positively radical in this main stage bastion of the cutting edge... His (Michael Wynne's) control of situation and character is impressively mature...\" - Michael Coveney WHATS ON STAGE\n\n\"...It is a perceptive piece, laced with Wynne\u2019s customary wit and insight. And it has serious points to make about success, failure, peer pressure and loneliness...\" - Sarah Hemming FINANCIAL TIMES\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{OlivierAward Comedy 2001\u20132025}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Priory}}\n[[Category:2009 plays]]\n[[Category:English plays]]\n", "name_user": "Schazjmd", "label": "safe", "comment": "changed quotation marks to italics for play title", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Priory_(play)"}
{"title_page": "Macey Cruthird", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name           = Macey Cruthird\n| image          = \n| imagesize      = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1992|11|12}}\n| birth_place    = [[Baytown, Texas]], [[United States]]\n| yearsactive    = 2002 \u2014 present\n| spouse         = \n| height         =  5' 0\" \n}}\n\n'''Macey Cruthird''' (born November 12, 1992) is an [[United States|American]] actress best known as the character ''Hayley Shanowski'' in the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] [[sitcom]] ''[[Hope & Faith]]''.\n\n==Career==\nMacey has trained in numerous acting and auditioning workshops in Los Angeles and her hometown of [[Frisco, Texas]]. She was cast in two pilots for [[Warner Brothers]], \"House Blend\" and \"The Misadventures of Fiona Plum,\" before landing her spot on \"Hope & Faith.\" She's also done numerous commercials, including Toyota, McDonald's, [[TJ Maxx]] and others, as well as print work.\n\nMacey made her feature film debut in the independent family film, \"Come Away Home,\" which premiered during the summer of 2005 and starred [[Paul Dooley]], [[Martin Mull]], [[Thomas Gibson]] and [[Lea Thompson]]. Additionally, she had the opportunity to work with one of her best friends, actress [[Jordan-Claire Green]], in the movie.\n\nMacey's other skills and hobbies include singing, dancing, piano, playing guitar, snow skiing and outdoor sports of all kinds, especially water sports. She is an avid animal lover and is particularly fond of her little Maltese puppy, Gidget.<ref>[http://www.cuddlypuppies.com/celebritypups/ Celebrity Pups<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nMacey had a recurring role on the sitcom ''[[Two and a Half Men]]'', as Megan, Jake's girlfriend<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qOUyBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA239&lpg=PA239&dq=Macey+Cruthird+two+and+a+half&source=bl&ots=lO2Yq1d97c&sig=ACfU3U29ZuN766WZYRuZwRxTb6a7wJXbww&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjauYeH1t7iAhVqoYsKHaihDVQQ6AEwCXoECE8QAQ#v=onepage&q=Macey%20Cruthird%20two%20and%20a%20half&f=false|title=The American Family on Television: A Chronology of 121 Shows, 1948-2004|last=Brooks|first=Marla|date=2015-03-12|publisher=McFarland|isbn=9781476606903|language=en}}</ref>\n\nShe appeared in [[sitcom]], ''Deeply Irresponsible'' as Alison Atlin in 2007.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Terrace |first1=Vincent |title=Encyclopedia of Unaired Television Pilots, 1945-2018 |date=2018 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9781476672069 |page=55 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ufx0DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA55 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCruthird has a sister named Bailey who is a successful singer and also guest starred in one episode of Hope & Faith. Cruthird went to St Joseph's school of Yorkville, New York.\n\nIn 2004, Cruthird was nominated for the [[Young Artist Award]] Best Performance in a TV Series (Comedy or Drama) - Young Actress Age Ten or Younger\nfor ''Hope & Faith''.\n\nIn 2006, Cruthird was nominated for the [[Young Artist Award]] Best Performance in a TV Series (Comedy) - Supporting Young Actress\nfor ''Hope & Faith''.\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''The (Mis)Adventures of Fiona Plum''\n| Unknown\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''House Blend''\n| Courtney Harper\n| Unsold television pilot\n|-\n| 2003 - 2006\n| ''[[Hope & Faith]]''\n| Hayley Shanowski\n| Main role; 56 episodes<br>Nominated - Young Artist Award Best Performance in a TV Series (Comedy or Drama) <small>(2004)</small><br>Nominated - Young Artist Award Best Performance in a TV Series (Comedy or Drama) <small>(2006)</small>\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''Come Away Home''\n| Holly\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Deeply Irresponsible''\n| Alyson Atlin\n| \n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Hank (2009 TV series)|Hank]]''\n| Maddie\n| \n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Hawthorne (TV series)|Hawthorne]]''\n| Cassie Maxwell\n| One episode\n|-\n| 2010 - 2011\n| ''[[Two and a Half Men]] \n|Megan \n|4 episodes\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''The Occupants''\n| Ruth\n| Completed Film\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=1314002|name=Macey Cruthird}}\n* http://www.superiorpics.com/macey_cruthird/\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cruthird, Macey}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Texas]]\n[[Category:American child actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Baytown, Texas]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name           = Macey Cruthird\n| image          = \n| imagesize      = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1992|11|12}}\n| birth_place    = [[Baytown, Texas]], [[United States]]\n| yearsactive    = 2002 \u2014 present\n| spouse         = \n| height         =  5' 0\" \n}}\n\n'''Macey Cruthird''' (born November 12, 1992) is an [[United States|American]] actress best known as the character ''Hayley Shanowski'' in the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] [[sitcom]] ''[[Hope & Faith]]''.\n\n==Career==\nMacey has trained in numerous acting and auditioning workshops in Los Angeles and her hometown of [[Frisco, Texas]]. She was cast in two pilots for [[Warner Brothers]], \"House Blend\" and \"The Misadventures of Fiona Plum,\" before landing her spot on \"Hope & Faith.\" She's also done numerous commercials, including Toyota, McDonald's, [[TJ Maxx]] and others, as well as print work.\n\nMacey made her feature film debut in the independent family film, \"Come Away Home,\" which premiered during the summer of 2005 and starred [[Paul Dooley]], [[Martin Mull]], [[Thomas Gibson]] and [[Lea Thompson]]. Additionally, she had the opportunity to work with one of her best friends, actress [[Jordan-Claire Green]], in the movie.\n\nMacey's other skills and hobbies include singing, dancing, piano, playing guitar, snow skiing and outdoor sports of all kinds, especially water sports. She is an avid animal lover and is particularly fond of her little Maltese puppy, Gidget.<ref>[http://www.cuddlypuppies.com/celebritypups/ Celebrity Pups<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nMacey had a recurring role on the sitcom ''[[Two and a Half Men]]'', as Megan, Jake's girlfriend<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qOUyBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA239&lpg=PA239&dq=Macey+Cruthird+two+and+a+half&source=bl&ots=lO2Yq1d97c&sig=ACfU3U29ZuN766WZYRuZwRxTb6a7wJXbww&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjauYeH1t7iAhVqoYsKHaihDVQQ6AEwCXoECE8QAQ#v=onepage&q=Macey%20Cruthird%20two%20and%20a%20half&f=false|title=The American Family on Television: A Chronology of 121 Shows, 1948-2004|last=Brooks|first=Marla|date=2015-03-12|publisher=McFarland|isbn=9781476606903|language=en}}</ref>\n\nShe appeared in [[sitcom]], ''Deeply Irresponsible'' as Alison Atlin in 2007.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Terrace |first1=Vincent |title=Encyclopedia of Unaired Television Pilots, 1945-2018 |date=2018 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=9781476672069 |page=55 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ufx0DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA55 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCruthird has a sister named Bailey who is a successful singer and also guest starred in one episode of Hope & Faith. Cruthird went to St Joseph's school of Yorkville, New York.\n\nIn 2004, Cruthird was Nominated for the  Young Artist Award Best Performance in a TV Series (Comedy or Drama) - Young Actress Age Ten or Younger\nfor ''Hope & Faith''.\n\nIn 2006, Cruthird was nominated for the Young Artist Award Best Performance in a TV Series (Comedy) - Supporting Young Actress\nfor ''Hope & Faith''.\n\n== Filmography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''The (Mis)Adventures of Fiona Plum''\n| Unknown\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''House Blend''\n| Courtney Harper\n| Unsold television pilot\n|-\n| 2003 - 2006\n| ''[[Hope & Faith]]''\n| Hayley Shanowski\n| Main role; 56 episodes<br>Nominated - Young Artist Award Best Performance in a TV Series (Comedy or Drama) <small>(2004)</small><br>Nominated - Young Artist Award Best Performance in a TV Series (Comedy or Drama) <small>(2006)</small>\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''Come Away Home''\n| Holly\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Deeply Irresponsible''\n| Alyson Atlin\n| \n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Hank (2009 TV series)|Hank]]''\n| Maddie\n| \n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Hawthorne (TV series)|Hawthorne]]''\n| Cassie Maxwell\n| One episode\n|-\n| 2010 - 2011\n| ''[[Two and a Half Men]] \n|Megan \n|4 episodes\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''The Occupants''\n| Ruth\n| Completed Film\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=1314002|name=Macey Cruthird}}\n* http://www.superiorpics.com/macey_cruthird/\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cruthird, Macey}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Texas]]\n[[Category:American child actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Baytown, Texas]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n", "name_user": "Pastabeans", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Macey_Cruthird"}
{"title_page": "Richard Varick", "text_new": "{{short description|American Politician}}\n{{short description|American Politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix   = Mayor\n| name               = Richard Varick\n| honorific-suffix   =\n| image              = RichardVarick.jpg\n| caption            = Portrait of Varick by [[Henry Inman (painter)|Henry Inman]] (ca. 1831)\n| imagesize          =\n| order              = [[List of mayors of New York City|45th Mayor of New York City]]\n| governor1          = [[George Clinton (vice president)|George Clinton]] (1789 - 1795)<br/>[[John Jay]] (1795 - 1801)\n| term_start         = October 12, 1789\n| term_end           = December 31, 1801\n| predecessor        = [[James Duane]]\n| successor          = [[Edward Livingston]]\n| order2             = [[New York State Attorney General|2nd Attorney General of New York]]\n| term_start2        = May 14, 1788\n| term_end2          = September 29, 1789\n| governor2          = [[George Clinton (vice president)|George Clinton]]\n| predecessor2       = [[Egbert Benson]]\n| successor2         = [[Aaron Burr]]\n| order3             = [[Speaker of the New York State Assembly|6th Speaker of the New York State Assembly]] \n| term_start3        = January 12, 1787\n| term_end3          = December 10, 1788\n| predecessor3       = [[John Lansing Jr.]]\n| successor3         = [[John Lansing Jr.]]\n| order4             = [[Recorder of New York City|15th Recorder of New York City]]\n| term_start4        = February 20, 1784\n| term_end4          = September 29, 1789\n| predecessor4       = [[John Watts (New York politician)|John Watts]]\n| successor4         = [[Samuel Jones (NY comptroller)|Samuel Jones]]\n| birth_date         = March 15, 1753\n| birth_place        = [[Hackensack, New Jersey|Hackensack]], [[Bergen County, New Jersey|Bergen County]], [[Province of New Jersey]]\n| death_date         = July 30, 1831 (aged 78)\n| death_place        = [[Jersey City, New Jersey]]\n| resting_place      = [[First Reformed Dutch Church, Hackensack|First Reformed Dutch Church Cemetery]]\n| nationality        = American\n| party              = [[Federalist Party|Federalist]]\n| spouse             = Maria Roosevelt\n| relations          = \n| branch             = [[File:Seal of the United States Board of War and Ordnance.svg|23px]] [[Continental Army]]<br/>{{flagicon|New York|1778}} [[New York State Militia]]\n| serviceyears       = 1775 - 1784 [[Continental Army]]<br/>1784 - 1801 [[New York State Militia]]\n| rank               = [[File:Union Army colonel rank insignia.png|35px]] [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]\n| battles            = \n}}\n\n'''Richard Varick''' (March 15, 1753 \u2013 July 30, 1831) was an American lawyer, military officer, and politician. A major figure in the development of post-Independence New York City and State, Varick became the [[List of mayors of New York City|45th Mayor of New York City]] in 1789 and served eleven concurrent one-year terms until 1801.<ref name=\"dlib\">{{cite web|title=Guide to the Papers of Richard Varick 1743-1871 (Bulk 1775-1830)  MS 655|url=http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/nyhs/varick/|website=dlib.nyu.edu|publisher=[[New-York Historical Society]]|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref> \n\nPrevious to his terms as mayor, Varick served as the [[Recorder of New York City|14th Recorder of New York City]] from 1784 to 1789. An office that no longer exists, it is equatable to 'Chief Legal Officer'. Along with [[Samuel Jones (New York comptroller)|Samuel Jones]], Varick codified New York State's first statutes after Revolution in the [[Laws of New York]] (2 vols., 1789). This body of work laid the whole foundation for Varick to institute the [[Law of New York]], the [[New York City Administrative Code]], and the [[Rules of New York City]] during his terms as mayor.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/history/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/varick-richard|title=Richard Varick|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=www.encyclopedia.com|publisher=|access-date=October 16, 2019}}</ref>. Under his leadership, the progenitors of the [[New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene|New York City Department of Health]], the [[New York Stock Exchange]], and many others would be created creating the basis of modern New York City. \n\nDuring the [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]], he served as [[George Washington]]'s aide-de-camp and private secretary. Varick's body of work from this era would lead to the ''Varick Transcripts'' which now live in the [[Library of Congress]]. The value of these documents has been noted throughout their lifetime as invaluable to the understanding of the formation of the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/history/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/varick-richard|title=Richard Varick|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=www.encyclopedia.com|publisher=|access-date=October 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nVarick was a founder of the [[Society of the Cincinnati]] and the [[American Bible Society]]. He was also a longtime trustee of [[Columbia University]].\n\n==Early life==\nHe was born on March 15, 1753, at [[Hackensack, New Jersey|Hackensack]] in [[Bergen County, New Jersey]] to John Varick and Jane (n\u00e9e Dey) Varick.<ref name=\"Cushman2010\">{{cite book|last1=Cushman|first1=Paul|title=Richard Varick : A Forgotten Founding Father : revolutionary war soldier, Federalist politician, mayor of New York|date=2010|publisher=Modern Memoirs|location=Amherst, MA|isbn=978-0-9772337-6-2|url=https://play.google.com/store/books/details?id=aDOUOnCcpQYC}}</ref> His mother grew up in her father's house, the [[Dey Mansion]], which would go on to play a pivotal role in the revolution.\n\nBoth Varick's parents ancestors had emigrated with the [[Dutch West India Company]] in the early to mid 17th century and remained in the greater New York City area. Amongst Varick's ancestors are [[Joris Jansen Rapelje]], a member of the [[Council of Twelve Men]] which was the first democratic body in the history of the United States (1641).\n\n===Education===\nLittle is known about the specifics of Varick's education before university, though surviving letters indicate that he was educated by private tutors and studied Latin, French, and other subjects. He enrolled in King's College (the original name of [[Columbia University]]) in [[New York City]] in 1771 where he studied under [[John Morin Scott]]. Varick clerked for Scott during his education and after being admitted into the New York Bar in October 1774, Scott made him an offer to be a partner in his firm. Unusually, Varick had not yet graduated from King's College despite having passed the bar and never formally graduated. Later in his career, Varick would become a trustee of King's College for over thirty years.<ref name=\"Lefkowitz2003\">{{cite book|last=Lefkowitz|first=Arthur|title=George Washington's Indispensable Men|date=2003|publisher=Stackpole Books|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OHhyDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA219&lpg=PA219&dq=%22george+washington%22+%22richard+varick%22+trusted&source=bl&ots=tGR1fKUCQX&sig=ACfU3U2VhSeS7RTNhnLUqmjqSUy4gc1C8A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj3vtLDuvrkAhUYFjQIHUIzBtM4ChDoATAEegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=%22george%20washington%22%20%22richard%20varick%22%20trusted&f=false|accessdate=1 October 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\n===American Revolutionary War===\n====Service under General Schuyler & Northern Army====\n[[File:Richard varick officer continental army.png|thumb|left|Richard Varick painted c.1787 by [[Ralph Earl]]. The portrait shows Varick in his Continental Army officers uniform although he retired his commission in 1783. The blue decoration is that of the Society of the Cincinnati.]] Eight months into his career in private practice, the [[American Revolutionary War]] began. At the influence of his employer, John Morin Scott, Varick suspended his studies and enlisted in the militia. On June 28, 1775, he was appointed captain of the [[1st New York Regiment]] and after only three days as field officer, was appointed military secretary under General [[Philip Schuyler]]. It was thought that Scott, understanding the administrative and intellectual value of his young partner, secured the appointment. Varick departed New York City with Schuyler on July 4, 1775, to head north to [[Fort Ticonderoga]] and launch the campaign to drive the British out of Canada. En route, the traveling party stopped in Albany briefly where Varick would first meet General [[Benedict Arnold]], who would become a good friend, also played a significant role in Varick's life until Arnold's treason in 1780.\n\nBy the summer of 1776, Schuyler had been felled by multiple illnesses and was reeling from a series of losses on the battlefield. Varick, by this juncture, in part out of necessity, and in part by appointment, was performing three jobs at once: private secretary to Schuyler, quartermaster for all the northern forts held by the Continental Army, and the Northern Army's deputy muster master general. Laterally, actual battlefield commands had been outsourced to Arnold and General [[Horatio Gates]]. Schuyler, recognizing the burden Varick was carrying, promoted him to Lieutenant Colonel. Varick's almost total control of the administration for the Northern Army lead to an even closer friendship between Arnold and Varick.\n\nThat same summer, Arnold was planning his attack effort to stop the British advance down [[Lake Champlain]] in what would be one of the first battles in the history of the [[U.S. Navy]]. With a dearth of available ships, the armada was largely built from scratch by Varick who solved the crisis by contacting his wide network in New York City and the surrounding area to send materials and coastal men who were qualified for such work. While the [[Battle of Valcour Island]] ended in defeat for the navy, it succeeded in slowing the British advance for the winter as they retreaded to their Canadian bases.\n\nVarick also faced run-ins with fellow officers who were not part of Schuyler's faction. General [[Anthony Walton White]], who had briefly served at Washington's aide-de-camp, was accused by Schuyler of looting a private home on the frontier. After denying the charges, White barged into Varick's offices and challenged him to a duel, under the impression that Varick had spoken negatively to his character. Varick, unarmed, narrowly escaped White's attempt to murder him after Varick declined the challenge. \n \nAfter the disastrous [[Battle of Saratoga]], Schuyler was removed from duty by the [[Continental Congress]] in August 1777 and replaced by General Gates. With factionalism rife within the Northern Army, Varick was aligned with Arnold which pitted him against Gates, whom he disliked regardless. Their circle of friendship had also grown to include [[Henry Brockholst Livingston]] and [[Matthew Clarkson]]. Their camaraderie was rudely defined as \"the New York gang\" by [[James Wilkinson]], a partisan of General Gates'.\n\nVarick would quietly and capably continue in his role as the Northern Army's deputy muster master general, though not as Gates' aide-de-camp or private secretary, until January 12, 1780 when the department was abolished by the Continental Congress in a larger reorganization.\n\n====Service under General Arnold====\n[[File:Benedict Arnold. Copy of engraving by H. B. Hall after John Trumbull, published 1879., 1931 - 1932 - NARA - 532921.tif|thumb|Benedict Arnold]]\nVarick briefly resumed his law in private practice, which proved challenging in his politically volatile hometown of New York City\u2014which was under occupation by the enemy. In August 1780, Benedict Arnold approached Varick about joining his staff at his newly appointed position as commanding officer of [[West Point, New York|West Point]] (then an active military instillation) as his [[aide-de-camp]] and inspector-general.<ref name=\"Cushman2010\"/><ref name=\"Jameson1900\">{{cite book|last1=Jameson|first1=J. F.|last2=Buel|first2=J. W.|title=American Reference Library: Encyclopedic dictionary of American Reference|date=1900|publisher=American Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gOtBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA326&lpg=PA326|accessdate=21 June 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWithin three months, Arnold's treason was discovered and he fled to British territory. Varick, along with [[David Franks (aide-de-camp)|David Franks]], were arrested. Varick had been ill in bed when informed both of Arnold's treason and his own arrest. Contemporary reports described Varick as spending several days on the edge of madness about Arnold's defection. Despite Arnold writing to Washington personally to say that his aides were not complicit, both Varick and Franks were detained by Washington as a precautionary measure. After a court of inquiry completed its investigation, they found Varick not guilty, and delivered the following:\n\n<blockquote>\u201c''That Lieutenant Colonel Varick\u2019s conduct with respect to the base Peculations and Treasonable Practices of the late General Arnold is not only unimpeachable but think him entitled (throughout every part of his conduct) to a degree of Merit that does him great honor as an Officer and particularly distinguishes him as a sincere Friend to his Country\u2026''\u201d</blockquote>\n\n====Service under General Washington====\nA by-product of the above was the introduction of Varick to [[George Washington]], which would lead to the two working together for the rest of their careers, and lives. This relationship began in 1781 when Washington petitioned the Continental Congress to establish team of writers to record and preserve all of his, and the army's, papers, planning, and correspondence for use by future generations. This would be under the supervision \u201cof a Man of character in whom entire confidence can be placed\u201d. Washington appointed Varick in this role, which made use of his highly respected administrative skills, and would fully rehabilitate his name after the Arnold scandal. Establishing his office at [[Poughkeepsie]], Varick and his assistants spent more than two years in compiling the forty-four folio volumes known as the [[Varick Transcripts]]. Varick served under Washington solely until Washington retired his commission in 1783.<ref name=\"albanyinstitute\">{{cite web|title=Colonel Richard Varick (1753-1831)|url=http://www.albanyinstitute.org/details/items/colonel-richard-varick-1753-1831.html|website=www.albanyinstitute.org|publisher=[[Albany Institute of History and Art]]|accessdate=21 June 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"metmuseum\">{{cite web|title=Relates to General Richard Montgomery {{!}} Letter from Richard Varick to DeWitt Clinton, Governor of New York, requesting repayment of cash he has advanced for expenditures relating to the Internment<!--sic--> of the Remains of the late General Montgomery {{!}} The Met|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/667757|website=metmuseum.org|publisher=[[The Metropolitan Museum of Art]]|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nUpon completing the assigned duties after years or work, General Washington wrote:\n<blockquote>\u201c''I take this first opportunity of signifying my entire approbation of the manner in which you have executed the important duties of recording secretary; and the satisfaction I feel in having my papers so properly arranged, and so correctly recorded; and beg you will accept my thanks for the care and attention which you have given to this business and beg you be persuaded, that I shall take pleasure in asserting on every occasion, the sense of entertainment of the fidelity, skill and indefatigable industry manifested by you in the performance of your public duties''.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Writings of Washington|url=http://www.archive.org/stream/cu31924092900400/cu31924092900400_djvu.txt|website=www.archive.org|pages=113\u2013114|publisher=New York Free Press|accessdate=16 October 2019}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nAfter he retired from his service in the Continental Army, Varick would remain in service as a colonel in the [[New York State Militia]] until 1801.<ref name=\"Cushman2010\"/>\n\n=====<div style=\"text-align: center;\">The Varick Transcripts</div>=====\nThe Varick Transcripts are deposited in the [[Library of Congress]]. The value of these documents has been noted throughout their lifetime as invaluable to the understanding of the formation of the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/history/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/varick-richard|title=Richard Varick|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=www.encyclopedia.com|publisher=|access-date=October 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs originally provisioned by Congress, the stated duties by General Washington to Colonel Varick as Recording Secretary would include categorizing, transcribing, and assembling all Washington's papers. The resulting 44 letterbooks contain copies of all documents dating from May, 1775 to June, 1785. Categories of papers, records, and correspondence are organized as follows;\n{{columns-list|colwidth=15em|style=text-align: center| font-style: italic;|\n* Continental Congress\n* Continental and State Military Personnel\n* Civil Officials and Private Citizens\n* Foreign Officers and Subjects of Foreign Nations\n* Enemy Officers and British Subjects\n* Continental Army Council Proceedings (War Council Proceedings)\n* General Orders\n* Personal Correspondence\n}}\n\n==Political career==\n===Pre-Mayor===\n[[File:Richard varick 1805 john trumbull.png|thumb|left|Richard Varick (c.1805) by [[John Trumbull]]]] Varick was the [[Recorder of New York City]] from 1784 to 1789. An office that no longer exists, it is equatable to 'Chief Legal Officer'. In this office, along with [[Samuel Jones (New York comptroller)|Samuel Jones]], he codified New York State's first statutes after Revolution in the [[Laws of New York]] (2 vols., 1789). This body of work laid the whole foundation for the [[Law of New York]], the [[New York City Administrative Code]], and the [[Rules of New York City]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/history/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/varick-richard|title=Richard Varick|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=www.encyclopedia.com|publisher=|access-date=October 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nConcurrently to the above, he was a member of the [[New York State Assembly]] from [[Manhattan|New York County]] from 1786 to 1788. During his term as a member of the New York State Assembly, he was [[Speaker of the New York State Assembly|Speaker]] during the sessions of 1787 and 1788. Varick was appointed the [[New York State Attorney General]] from 1788 to 1789.\n\nRemarkably, due to the elitist nature of the [[New York Constitution|New York State Constitution of 1777]], almost all government positions in the city and state of New York were appointed by the [[Council of Appointment]]. Few, if any, general elections or other democratic functions would exist until 1802. Thus, in the year 1788, Varick was simultaneously the Recorder of New York City, a State Assemblyman representing New York City, the Speaker of the House of the State of New York, and the Attorney General of the State of New York. Though Varick is on record protesting the egregious nature of his occupying multiple offices, it was rationalized at the time that as both an expert administrator and lawyer, he was an ideal choice to fill these myriad offices and to build swiftly the various mechanisms of government. And, that the subsequent laws were codified quickly in the nascent days of an independent New York City and State to ensure the function, and growth, of both entities.\n\n===Mayor of New York City===\n[[File:Richard Varick Signature 1796.jpg|thumb|right|Signature of Richard Varick while Mayor of New York (1798)]]\nMost notably, Varick was the [[Mayor of New York City]] for twelve years during the formative post-Independence era from 1789 to 1801.<ref name=\"Marcus1985\">{{cite book|last1=Marcus|first1=Maeva|last2=Perry|first2=James R.|title=The Documentary History of the Supreme Court of the United States, 1789-1800: Suits against states|date=1985|publisher=[[Columbia University Press]]|isbn=9780231088725|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K7jhBkyoKSUC&pg=PA107&lpg=PA107|accessdate=21 June 2017|language=en}}</ref> While Mayor, he focused on the yellow fever epidemics which struck repeatedly.\n\n==Philanthropy & Charity==\n===American Bible Society===\nVarick was a founder of the [[American Bible Society]] in 1816.<ref name=\"sunypress\">{{cite web|title=Richard Varick: A Forgotten Founding Father|url=https://www.sunypress.edu/p-5293-richard-varick-a-forgotten-foun.aspx|website=www.sunypress.edu|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Wosh1994\">{{cite book|last1=Wosh|first1=Peter J.|title=Spreading the Word: The Bible Business in Nineteenth-century America|date=1994|publisher=[[Cornell University Press]]|isbn=0801429285|url=https://archive.org/details/spreadingwordbib00wosh|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/spreadingwordbib00wosh/page/16 16]|accessdate=21 June 2017|language=en}}</ref> He would later become president (succeeding [[John Jay]]) in 1828 until his death in 1831.\n\n===Society of the Cincinnati===\nHe was an original member of the [[Society of the Cincinnati]] beginning in 1783, and president of the New York chapter until his death. As such, he was responsible for maintaining the legacy of George Washington. From 1790 to 1836, celebrations of Washington's birthday in the City included Tammany Hall dinners, Washington Benevolent Society parades and an intimate open house held each February 22 by [[Mary Simpson (house servant)|Mary Simpson]] (c. 1752-March 18, 1836), at her John Street grocery. Varick was a member of, and generous contributor to, many charitable organizations in New York City.<ref name=\"Cushman2010\"/>\n\n==Personal life & family==\nHe and his wife Maria Roosevelt, daughter of [[Isaac Roosevelt (politician)|Isaac Roosevelt]], were married on May 8, 1786 in New York City and resided at 52 Wall Street initially then moved to a larger home on lower Broadway. His father-in-law was the patrilineal great-great-grandfather of President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt|Franklin Delano Roosevelt]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Whittelsey|first1=Charles Barney|title=The Roosevelt Genealogy, 1649-1902|date=1902|publisher=Press of J.B. Burr & Company|url=https://archive.org/details/rooseveltgenealo00whit|page=[https://archive.org/details/rooseveltgenealo00whit/page/33 33]|accessdate=21 June 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nVarick was one of seven children, his siblings being: Abraham Varick (the great-grandfather of Anna Maria Romeyn Varick, who married [[George Lauder (Scottish industrialist)|George Lauder]] of the [[Lauder Greenway Family]].); Dr. John Varick Jr.; Anne Elting; Sarah Froeligh; Jane De Witt (wife of [[Simeon De Witt]]); and Maria Gilbert.\n\n==Death & burial==\nVarick died on July 30, 1831 and is interred at the [[First Reformed Dutch Church, Hackensack|First Reformed Dutch Church Cemetery]] in [[Hackensack, New Jersey]].<ref>[http://www.northjersey.com/story/entertainment/2017/10/19/celebrities-buried-bergen-county-new-jersey/758867001/ NorthJersey.com]. Accessed November 22, 2017.</ref>\n\n==Honorifics==\nThe Town of [[Varick, New York]], Varick Street in [[Jersey City]] and [[Varick Street (Manhattan)|Varick Street]] (where he once owned property) in [[Manhattan]] in the [[City of New York]] bear his name.<ref>[http://www.lowermanhattan.info/news/downtown_street_names_and_44900.aspx Downtown Street Names and the Stories They Tell] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070822123311/http://www.lowermanhattan.info/news/downtown_street_names_and_44900.aspx |date=August 22, 2007 }}, LowerManhattan.info. Accessed August 22, 2007. \"An extension of Seventh Avenue leading south from Clarkson Street, Varick Street got its name from Richard Varick, who served as the mayor of the city from 1791 to 1801.\"</ref><ref name=\"Longoria2017\">{{cite news|last1=Longoria|first1=Patricia|title=The Dutch roots of Ithaca's Dey Street|url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/local/2017/05/25/dutch-roots-ithacas-dey-street/345293001/|accessdate=21 June 2017|work=[[The Poughkeepsie Journal]]|date=25 May 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|New York City|New York State|Military history}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.loc.gov/collections/george-washington-papers/articles-and-essays/series-notes/series-3-varick-transcripts|The Varick Transcripts] [[Library of Congress]]\n* [http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/nyhs/varick.html Richard Varick Papers,1743-1871] [[New-York Historical Society]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061012123254/http://hackensackhigh.org/~rkc/hackensack/varick/varick.html Photographs of gravesite]\n*[http://politicalgraveyard.com/bio/vanwagenen-vaudain.html Political Graveyard]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | before = [[John Lansing, Jr.]] | title = [[Speaker of the New York State Assembly]] | years = 1787\u20131788 | after = [[John Lansing, Jr.]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[James Duane]] | title = [[Mayors of New York City|Mayor of New York City]] | years = 1789\u20131801 | after = [[Edward Livingston]]}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{succession box | before = [[John Watts (New York)|John Watts]] | title = [[Recorder of New York City]] | years = 1784\u20131789 | after = [[Samuel Jones (NY comptroller)|Samuel Jones]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Egbert Benson]] | title = [[New York State Attorney General]] | years = 1788\u20131789 | after = [[Aaron Burr]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{SpeakerNYAssembly}}\n{{NYSAttorneyGeneral}}\n{{PreConsolidationNYCMayors}}\n{{NYC Recorder}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Varick, Richard}}\n[[Category:1753 births]]\n[[Category:People from New York City]]\n[[Category:Mayors of New York City]]\n[[Category:Members of the New York State Assembly]]\n[[Category:New York (state) in the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:New York (state) militiamen in the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:Continental Army officers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Bank of New York]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:American people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:Aides-de-camp of George Washington]]\n[[Category:Columbia College (New York) alumni]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the New York State Assembly]]\n[[Category:New York State Attorneys General]]\n[[Category:New York City Recorders]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Hackensack, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People of New Jersey in the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:Burials at First Reformed Dutch Church, Hackensack]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Federalists]]\n[[Category:19th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:18th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:1831 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American Politician}}\n{{short description|American Politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix   = Mayor\n| name               = Richard Varick\n| honorific-suffix   =\n| image              = RichardVarick.jpg\n| caption            = Portrait of Varick by [[Henry Inman (painter)|Henry Inman]] (ca. 1831)\n| imagesize          =\n| order              = [[List of mayors of New York City|45th Mayor of New York City]]\n| governor1          = [[George Clinton (vice president)|George Clinton]] (1789 - 1795)<br/>[[John Jay]] (1795 - 1801)\n| term_start         = October 12, 1789\n| term_end           = December 31, 1801\n| predecessor        = [[James Duane]]\n| successor          = [[Edward Livingston]]\n| order2             = [[New York State Attorney General|2nd Attorney General of New York]]\n| term_start2        = May 14, 1788\n| term_end2          = September 29, 1789\n| governor2          = [[George Clinton (vice president)|George Clinton]]\n| predecessor2       = [[Egbert Benson]]\n| successor2         = [[Aaron Burr]]\n| order3             = [[Speaker of the New York State Assembly|6th Speaker of the New York State Assembly]] \n| term_start3        = January 12, 1787\n| term_end3          = December 10, 1788\n| predecessor3       = [[John Lansing Jr.]]\n| successor3         = [[John Lansing Jr.]]\n| order4             = [[Recorder of New York City|15th Recorder of New York City]]\n| term_start4        = February 20, 1784\n| term_end4          = September 29, 1789\n| predecessor4       = [[John Watts (New York politician)|John Watts]]\n| successor4         = [[Samuel Jones (NY comptroller)|Samuel Jones]]\n| birth_date         = March 15, 1753\n| birth_place        = [[Hackensack, New Jersey|Hackensack]], [[Bergen County, New Jersey|Bergen County]], [[Province of New Jersey]]\n| death_date         = July 30, 1831 (aged 78)\n| death_place        = [[Jersey City, New Jersey]]\n| resting_place      = [[First Reformed Dutch Church, Hackensack|First Reformed Dutch Church Cemetery]]\n| nationality        = American\n| party              = [[Federalist Party|Federalist]]\n| spouse             = Maria Roosevelt\n| relations          = \n| branch             = [[File:Seal of the United States Board of War and Ordnance.svg|23px]] [[Continental Army]]<br/>{{flagicon|New York|1778}} [[New York State Militia]]\n| serviceyears       = 1775 - 1784 [[Continental Army]]<br/>1784 - 1801 [[New York State Militia]]\n| rank               = [[File:Union Army colonel rank insignia.png|35px]] [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]\n| battles            = \n}}\n\n'''Richard Varick''' (March 15, 1753 \u2013 July 30, 1831) was an American lawyer, military officer, and politician. A major figure in the development of post-Independence New York City and State, Varick became the [[List of mayors of New York City|45th Mayor of New York City]] in 1789 and served eleven concurrent one-year terms until 1801.<ref name=\"dlib\">{{cite web|title=Guide to the Papers of Richard Varick 1743-1871 (Bulk 1775-1830)  MS 655|url=http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/nyhs/varick/|website=dlib.nyu.edu|publisher=[[New-York Historical Society]]|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref> \n\nPrevious to his terms as mayor, Varick served as the [[Recorder of New York City|14th Recorder of New York City]] from 1784 to 1789. An office that no longer exists, it is equatable to 'Chief Legal Officer'. Along with [[Samuel Jones (New York comptroller)|Samuel Jones]], Varick codified New York State's first statutes after Revolution in the [[Laws of New York]] (2 vols., 1789). This body of work laid the whole foundation for Varick to institute the [[Law of New York]], the [[New York City Administrative Code]], and the [[Rules of New York City]] during his terms as mayor.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/history/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/varick-richard|title=Richard Varick|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=www.encyclopedia.com|publisher=|access-date=October 16, 2019}}</ref>. Under his leadership, the progenitors of the [[New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene|New York City Department of Health]], the [[New York Stock Exchange]], and many others would be created creating the basis of modern New York City. \n\nDuring the [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]], he served as [[George Washington]]'s aide-de-camp and private secretary. Varick's body of work from this era would lead to the ''Varick Transcripts'' which now live in the [[Library of Congress]]. The value of these documents has been noted throughout their lifetime as invaluable to the understanding of the formation of the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/history/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/varick-richard|title=Richard Varick|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=www.encyclopedia.com|publisher=|access-date=October 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nVarick was a founder of the [[Society of the Cincinnati]] and the [[American Bible Society]]. He was also a longtime trustee of [[Columbia University]].\n\n==Early life==\nHe was born on March 15, 1753, at [[Hackensack, New Jersey|Hackensack]] in [[Bergen County, New Jersey]] to John Varick and Jane (n\u00e9e Dey) Varick.<ref name=\"Cushman2010\">{{cite book|last1=Cushman|first1=Paul|title=Richard Varick : A Forgotten Founding Father : revolutionary war soldier, Federalist politician, mayor of New York|date=2010|publisher=Modern Memoirs|location=Amherst, MA|isbn=978-0-9772337-6-2|url=https://play.google.com/store/books/details?id=aDOUOnCcpQYC}}</ref> His mother grew up in her father's house, the [[Dey Mansion]], which would go on to play a pivotal role in the revolution.\n\nBoth Varick's parents ancestors had emigrated with the [[Dutch West India Company]] in the early to mid 17th century and remained in the greater New York City area. Amongst Varick's ancestors are [[Joris Jansen Rapelje]], a member of the [[Council of Twelve Men]] which was the first democratic body in the history of the United States (1641).\n\n===Education===\nLittle is known about the specifics of Varick's education before university, though surviving letters indicate that he was educated by private tutors and studied Latin, French, and other subjects. He enrolled in King's College (the original name of [[Columbia University]]) in [[New York City]] in 1771 where he studied under [[John Morin Scott]]. Varick clerked for Scott during his education and after being admitted into the New York Bar in October 1774, Scott made him an offer to be a partner in his firm. Unusually, Varick had not yet graduated from King's College despite having passed the bar and never formally graduated. Later in his career, Varick would become a trustee of King's College for over thirty years.<ref name=\"Lefkowitz2003\">{{cite book|last=Lefkowitz|first=Arthur|title=George Washington's Indispensable Men|date=2003|publisher=Stackpole Books|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OHhyDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA219&lpg=PA219&dq=%22george+washington%22+%22richard+varick%22+trusted&source=bl&ots=tGR1fKUCQX&sig=ACfU3U2VhSeS7RTNhnLUqmjqSUy4gc1C8A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj3vtLDuvrkAhUYFjQIHUIzBtM4ChDoATAEegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=%22george%20washington%22%20%22richard%20varick%22%20trusted&f=false|accessdate=1 October 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\n===American Revolutionary War===\n====Service under General Schuyler & Northern Army====\n[[File:Richard varick officer continental army.png|thumb|left|Richard Varick painted c.1787 by [[Ralph Earl]]. The portrait shows Varick in his Continental Army officers uniform although he retired his commission in 1783. The blue decoration is that of the Society of the Cincinnati.]] Eight months into his career in private practice, the [[American Revolutionary War]] began. At the influence of his employer, John Morin Scott, Varick suspended his studies and enlisted in the militia. On June 28, 1775, he was appointed captain of the [[1st New York Regiment]] and after only three days as field officer, was appointed military secretary under General [[Philip Schuyler]]. It was thought that Scott, understanding the administrative and intellectual value of his young partner, secured the appointment. Varick departed New York City with Schuyler on July 4, 1775, to head north to [[Fort Ticonderoga]] and launch the campaign to drive the British out of Canada. En route, the traveling party stopped in Albany briefly where Varick would first meet General [[Benedict Arnold]], who would become a good friend, also played a significant role in Varick's life until Arnold's treason in 1780.\n\nBy the summer of 1776, Schuyler had been felled by multiple illnesses and was reeling from a series of losses on the battlefield. Varick, by this juncture, in part out of necessity, and in part by appointment, was performing three jobs at once: private secretary to Schuyler, quartermaster for all the northern forts held by the Continental Army, and the Northern Army's deputy muster master general. Laterally, actual battlefield commands had been outsourced to Arnold and General [[Horatio Gates]]. Schuyler, recognizing the burden Varick was carrying, promoted him to Lieutenant Colonel. Varick's almost total control of the administration for the Northern Army lead to an even closer friendship between Arnold and Varick.\n\nThat same summer, Arnold was planning his attack effort to stop the British advance down [[Lake Champlain]] in what would be one of the first battles in the history of the [[U.S. Navy]]. With a dearth of available ships, the armada was largely built from scratch by Varick who solved the crisis by contacting his wide network in New York City and the surrounding area to send materials and coastal men who were qualified for such work. While the [[Battle of Valcour Island]] ended in defeat for the navy, it succeeded in slowing the British advance for the winter as they retreaded to their Canadian bases.\n\nVarick also faced run-ins with fellow officers who were not part of Schuyler's faction. General [[Anthony Walton White]], who had briefly served at Washington's aide-de-camp, was accused by Schuyler of looting a private home on the frontier. After denying the charges, White barged into Varick's offices and challenged him to a duel, under the impression that Varick had spoken negatively to his character. Varick, unarmed, narrowly escaped White's attempt to murder him after Varick declined the challenge. \n \nAfter the disastrous [[Battle of Saratoga]], Schuyler was removed from duty by the [[Continental Congress]] in August 1777 and replaced by General Gates. With factionalism rife within the Northern Army, Varick was aligned with Arnold which pitted him against Gates, whom he disliked regardless. Their circle of friendship had also grown to include [[Henry Brockholst Livingston]] and [[Matthew Clarkson]]. Their camaraderie was rudely defined as \"the New York gang\" by [[James Wilkinson]], a partisan of General Gates'.\n\nVarick would quietly and capably continue in his role as the Northern Army's deputy muster master general, though not as Gates' aide-de-camp or private secretary, until January 12, 1780 when the department was abolished by the Continental Congress in a larger reorganization.\n\n====Service under General Arnold====\n[[File:Benedict Arnold. Copy of engraving by H. B. Hall after John Trumbull, published 1879., 1931 - 1932 - NARA - 532921.tif|thumb|Benedict Arnold]]\nVarick briefly resumed his law in private practice, which proved challenging in his politically volatile hometown of New York City\u2014which was under occupation by the enemy. In August 1780, Benedict Arnold approached Varick about joining his staff at his newly appointed position as commanding officer of [[West Point, New York|West Point]] (then an active military instillation) as his [[aide-de-camp]] and inspector-general.<ref name=\"Cushman2010\"/><ref name=\"Jameson1900\">{{cite book|last1=Jameson|first1=J. F.|last2=Buel|first2=J. W.|title=American Reference Library: Encyclopedic dictionary of American Reference|date=1900|publisher=American Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gOtBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA326&lpg=PA326|accessdate=21 June 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWithin three months, Arnold's treason was discovered and he fled to British territory. Varick, along with [[David Franks (aide-de-camp)|David Franks]], were arrested. Varick had been ill in bed when informed both of Arnold's treason and his own arrest. Contemporary reports described Varick as spending several days on the edge of madness about Arnold's defection. Despite Arnold writing to Washington personally to say that his aides were not complicit, both Varick and Franks were detained by Washington as a precautionary measure. After a court of inquiry completed its investigation, they found Varick not guilty, and delivered the following:\n\n<blockquote>\u201c''That Lieutenant Colonel Varick\u2019s conduct with respect to the base Peculations and Treasonable Practices of the late General Arnold is not only unimpeachable but think him entitled (throughout every part of his conduct) to a degree of Merit that does him great honor as an Officer and particularly distinguishes him as a sincere Friend to his Country\u2026''\u201d</blockquote>\n\n====Service under General Washington====\nA by-product of the above was the introduction of Varick to [[George Washington]], which would lead to the two working together for the rest of their careers, and lives. This relationship began in 1781 when Washington petitioned the Continental Congress to establish team of writers to record and preserve all of his, and the army's, papers, planning, and correspondence for use by future generations. This would be under the supervision \u201cof a Man of character in whom entire confidence can be placed\u201d. Washington appointed Varick in this role, which made use of his highly respected administrative skills, and would fully rehabilitate his name after the Arnold scandal. Establishing his office at [[Poughkeepsie]], Varick and his assistants spent more than two years in compiling the forty-four folio volumes known as the [[Varick Transcripts]]. Varick served under Washington solely until Washington retired his commission in 1783.<ref name=\"albanyinstitute\">{{cite web|title=Colonel Richard Varick (1753-1831)|url=http://www.albanyinstitute.org/details/items/colonel-richard-varick-1753-1831.html|website=www.albanyinstitute.org|publisher=[[Albany Institute of History and Art]]|accessdate=21 June 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"metmuseum\">{{cite web|title=Relates to General Richard Montgomery {{!}} Letter from Richard Varick to DeWitt Clinton, Governor of New York, requesting repayment of cash he has advanced for expenditures relating to the Internment<!--sic--> of the Remains of the late General Montgomery {{!}} The Met|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/667757|website=metmuseum.org|publisher=[[The Metropolitan Museum of Art]]|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nUpon completing the assigned duties after years or work, General Washington wrote:\n<blockquote>\u201c''I take this first opportunity of signifying my entire approbation of the manner in which you have executed the important duties of recording secretary; and the satisfaction I feel in having my papers so properly arranged, and so correctly recorded; and beg you will accept my thanks for the care and attention which you have given to this business and beg you be persuaded, that I shall take pleasure in asserting on every occasion, the sense of entertainment of the fidelity, skill and indefatigable industry manifested by you in the performance of your public duties''.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Writings of Washington|url=http://www.archive.org/stream/cu31924092900400/cu31924092900400_djvu.txt|website=www.archive.org|pages=113\u2013114|publisher=New York Free Press|accessdate=16 October 2019}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nAfter he retired from his service in the Continental Army, Varick would remain in service as a colonel in the [[New York State Militia]] until 1801.<ref name=\"Cushman2010\"/>\n\n=====<div style=\"text-align: center;\">The Varick Transcripts</div>=====\nThe Varick Transcripts are deposited in the [[Library of Congress]]. The value of these documents has been noted throughout their lifetime as invaluable to the understanding of the formation of the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/history/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/varick-richard|title=Richard Varick|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=www.encyclopedia.com|publisher=|access-date=October 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs originally provisioned by Congress, the stated duties by General Washington to Colonel Varick as Recording Secretary would include categorizing, transcribing, and assembling all Washington's papers. The resulting 44 letterbooks contain copies of all documents dating from May, 1775 to June, 1785. Categories of papers, records, and correspondence are organized as follows;\n{{columns-list|colwidth=15em|style=width: 600px; font-style: italic;|\n* Continental Congress\n* Continental and State Military Personnel\n* Civil Officials and Private Citizens\n* Foreign Officers and Subjects of Foreign Nations\n* Enemy Officers and British Subjects\n* Continental Army Council Proceedings (War Council Proceedings)\n* General Orders\n* Personal Correspondence\n}}\n\n==Political career==\n===Pre-Mayor===\n[[File:Richard varick 1805 john trumbull.png|thumb|left|Richard Varick (c.1805) by [[John Trumbull]]]] Varick was the [[Recorder of New York City]] from 1784 to 1789. An office that no longer exists, it is equatable to 'Chief Legal Officer'. In this office, along with [[Samuel Jones (New York comptroller)|Samuel Jones]], he codified New York State's first statutes after Revolution in the [[Laws of New York]] (2 vols., 1789). This body of work laid the whole foundation for the [[Law of New York]], the [[New York City Administrative Code]], and the [[Rules of New York City]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/history/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/varick-richard|title=Richard Varick|author=<!--Not stated-->|website=www.encyclopedia.com|publisher=|access-date=October 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nConcurrently to the above, he was a member of the [[New York State Assembly]] from [[Manhattan|New York County]] from 1786 to 1788. During his term as a member of the New York State Assembly, he was [[Speaker of the New York State Assembly|Speaker]] during the sessions of 1787 and 1788. Varick was appointed the [[New York State Attorney General]] from 1788 to 1789.\n\nRemarkably, due to the elitist nature of the [[New York Constitution|New York State Constitution of 1777]], almost all government positions in the city and state of New York were appointed by the [[Council of Appointment]]. Few, if any, general elections or other democratic functions would exist until 1802. Thus, in the year 1788, Varick was simultaneously the Recorder of New York City, a State Assemblyman representing New York City, the Speaker of the House of the State of New York, and the Attorney General of the State of New York. Though Varick is on record protesting the egregious nature of his occupying multiple offices, it was rationalized at the time that as both an expert administrator and lawyer, he was an ideal choice to fill these myriad offices and to build swiftly the various mechanisms of government. And, that the subsequent laws were codified quickly in the nascent days of an independent New York City and State to ensure the function, and growth, of both entities.\n\n===Mayor of New York City===\n[[File:Richard Varick Signature 1796.jpg|thumb|right|Signature of Richard Varick while Mayor of New York (1798)]]\nMost notably, Varick was the [[Mayor of New York City]] for twelve years during the formative post-Independence era from 1789 to 1801.<ref name=\"Marcus1985\">{{cite book|last1=Marcus|first1=Maeva|last2=Perry|first2=James R.|title=The Documentary History of the Supreme Court of the United States, 1789-1800: Suits against states|date=1985|publisher=[[Columbia University Press]]|isbn=9780231088725|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K7jhBkyoKSUC&pg=PA107&lpg=PA107|accessdate=21 June 2017|language=en}}</ref> While Mayor, he focused on the yellow fever epidemics which struck repeatedly.\n\n==Philanthropy & Charity==\n===American Bible Society===\nVarick was a founder of the [[American Bible Society]] in 1816.<ref name=\"sunypress\">{{cite web|title=Richard Varick: A Forgotten Founding Father|url=https://www.sunypress.edu/p-5293-richard-varick-a-forgotten-foun.aspx|website=www.sunypress.edu|accessdate=21 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Wosh1994\">{{cite book|last1=Wosh|first1=Peter J.|title=Spreading the Word: The Bible Business in Nineteenth-century America|date=1994|publisher=[[Cornell University Press]]|isbn=0801429285|url=https://archive.org/details/spreadingwordbib00wosh|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/spreadingwordbib00wosh/page/16 16]|accessdate=21 June 2017|language=en}}</ref> He would later become president (succeeding [[John Jay]]) in 1828 until his death in 1831.\n\n===Society of the Cincinnati===\nHe was an original member of the [[Society of the Cincinnati]] beginning in 1783, and president of the New York chapter until his death. As such, he was responsible for maintaining the legacy of George Washington. From 1790 to 1836, celebrations of Washington's birthday in the City included Tammany Hall dinners, Washington Benevolent Society parades and an intimate open house held each February 22 by [[Mary Simpson (house servant)|Mary Simpson]] (c. 1752-March 18, 1836), at her John Street grocery. Varick was a member of, and generous contributor to, many charitable organizations in New York City.<ref name=\"Cushman2010\"/>\n\n==Personal life & family==\nHe and his wife Maria Roosevelt, daughter of [[Isaac Roosevelt (politician)|Isaac Roosevelt]], were married on May 8, 1786 in New York City and resided at 52 Wall Street initially then moved to a larger home on lower Broadway. His father-in-law was the patrilineal great-great-grandfather of President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt|Franklin Delano Roosevelt]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Whittelsey|first1=Charles Barney|title=The Roosevelt Genealogy, 1649-1902|date=1902|publisher=Press of J.B. Burr & Company|url=https://archive.org/details/rooseveltgenealo00whit|page=[https://archive.org/details/rooseveltgenealo00whit/page/33 33]|accessdate=21 June 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nVarick was one of seven children, his siblings being: Abraham Varick (the great-grandfather of Anna Maria Romeyn Varick, who married [[George Lauder (Scottish industrialist)|George Lauder]] of the [[Lauder Greenway Family]].); Dr. John Varick Jr.; Anne Elting; Sarah Froeligh; Jane De Witt (wife of [[Simeon De Witt]]); and Maria Gilbert.\n\n==Death & burial==\nVarick died on July 30, 1831 and is interred at the [[First Reformed Dutch Church, Hackensack|First Reformed Dutch Church Cemetery]] in [[Hackensack, New Jersey]].<ref>[http://www.northjersey.com/story/entertainment/2017/10/19/celebrities-buried-bergen-county-new-jersey/758867001/ NorthJersey.com]. Accessed November 22, 2017.</ref>\n\n==Honorifics==\nThe Town of [[Varick, New York]], Varick Street in [[Jersey City]] and [[Varick Street (Manhattan)|Varick Street]] (where he once owned property) in [[Manhattan]] in the [[City of New York]] bear his name.<ref>[http://www.lowermanhattan.info/news/downtown_street_names_and_44900.aspx Downtown Street Names and the Stories They Tell] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070822123311/http://www.lowermanhattan.info/news/downtown_street_names_and_44900.aspx |date=August 22, 2007 }}, LowerManhattan.info. Accessed August 22, 2007. \"An extension of Seventh Avenue leading south from Clarkson Street, Varick Street got its name from Richard Varick, who served as the mayor of the city from 1791 to 1801.\"</ref><ref name=\"Longoria2017\">{{cite news|last1=Longoria|first1=Patricia|title=The Dutch roots of Ithaca's Dey Street|url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/local/2017/05/25/dutch-roots-ithacas-dey-street/345293001/|accessdate=21 June 2017|work=[[The Poughkeepsie Journal]]|date=25 May 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|New York City|New York State|Military history}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.loc.gov/collections/george-washington-papers/articles-and-essays/series-notes/series-3-varick-transcripts|The Varick Transcripts] [[Library of Congress]]\n* [http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/nyhs/varick.html Richard Varick Papers,1743-1871] [[New-York Historical Society]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061012123254/http://hackensackhigh.org/~rkc/hackensack/varick/varick.html Photographs of gravesite]\n*[http://politicalgraveyard.com/bio/vanwagenen-vaudain.html Political Graveyard]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | before = [[John Lansing, Jr.]] | title = [[Speaker of the New York State Assembly]] | years = 1787\u20131788 | after = [[John Lansing, Jr.]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[James Duane]] | title = [[Mayors of New York City|Mayor of New York City]] | years = 1789\u20131801 | after = [[Edward Livingston]]}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{succession box | before = [[John Watts (New York)|John Watts]] | title = [[Recorder of New York City]] | years = 1784\u20131789 | after = [[Samuel Jones (NY comptroller)|Samuel Jones]]}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Egbert Benson]] | title = [[New York State Attorney General]] | years = 1788\u20131789 | after = [[Aaron Burr]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{SpeakerNYAssembly}}\n{{NYSAttorneyGeneral}}\n{{PreConsolidationNYCMayors}}\n{{NYC Recorder}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Varick, Richard}}\n[[Category:1753 births]]\n[[Category:People from New York City]]\n[[Category:Mayors of New York City]]\n[[Category:Members of the New York State Assembly]]\n[[Category:New York (state) in the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:New York (state) militiamen in the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:Continental Army officers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Bank of New York]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:American people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:Aides-de-camp of George Washington]]\n[[Category:Columbia College (New York) alumni]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the New York State Assembly]]\n[[Category:New York State Attorneys General]]\n[[Category:New York City Recorders]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Hackensack, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People of New Jersey in the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:Burials at First Reformed Dutch Church, Hackensack]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Federalists]]\n[[Category:19th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:18th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:1831 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "1I0I1I0I1I0", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe Varick Transcripts", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Varick"}
{"title_page": "Dirndl", "text_new": "{{short description|Traditional dress worn in Germany,\u00a0Switzerland, Liechtenstein, Austria and South Tyrol}}\n[[File:Dirndl.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A woman wearing a dirndl.]]\n[[File:KurzsDiandlgwand.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Seated women wearing modern dirndls.]]\n[[File:Diandlgwand.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Different colour variations can depend on the origin of the woman wearing a dirndl.]]\n\nA '''dirndl''' ({{IPA-de|\u02c8d\u026a\u0281ndl\u0329|lang|De-at-Dirndl.ogg}},<ref name=\"auto10\">{{cite web|url=http://germanchoices.blogspot.com/2017/10/dirndl-german-dress-dirndl.html|title=Dirndl - German Dress Dirndl|first=YOUR|last=NAME|website=German Choices}}</ref><ref name=\"auto11\"></{{cite web|url=http://germanchoices.blogspot.co.uk/2017/08/german-beer-maid-costume.html|title=German Beer Maid Costume|first=YOUR|last=NAME|website=German Choices}}</ref> {{lang-bar|Diandl}}) <ref name=\"auto11\"/> is the name of a traditional feminine [[dress]] worn in [[Austria]], [[South Tyrol]] and [[Bavaria]]. It is based on the traditional clothing (''tracht'') of [[Alps]] peasants.<ref name=\"auto10\"/><ref>''Ethnic Dress in the United States: A Cultural Encyclopedia'', eds. Annette Lynch; Mitchell D. Strauss (Lanham, MD: Rowman & Littlefield, 2015), p. 100</ref><ref name=\"austria.info\">{{cite web |url=http://www.austria.info/us/austria-dirndl-temptation/dirndl-basics-1681393.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-11-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412041607/http://www.austria.info/us/austria-dirndl-temptation/dirndl-basics-1681393.html |archivedate=2015-04-12 }}</ref>  Dresses that are loosely based on the dirndl are known as {{lang|de|Landhausmode}} ('country-inspired fashion').\n\nA '''dirndl skirt''' generally describes a light circular cut dress, gathered at the waist, that falls below the knee.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dirndl Skirts|first=Alice|last=Watt|date=26 April 2012|url=http://www.elleuk.com/fashion/what-to-wear/dirndl-skirts#image=1|work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]|location=London|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Spin out with springtime's dirndl skirt|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/fashion/spin-out-with-springtimes-dirndl-skirt-7722321.html|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|location=London|first=Karen|last=Dacre|date=8 May 2012|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe dirndl consists of a [[bodice]] and skirt or a pinafore dress, a low-cut [[blouse]] with short puff sleeves, full [[skirt]] and [[apron]].<ref name=\"onesprime.de\">{{cite news|url=|title=Oktoberfest Dirndl dress: the bow|last=|first=|date=|website=Onesprime.de|accessdate=}}</ref><ref name=\"destination-munich.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.destination-munich.com/german-dirndl.html |title=German Dirndl - an illustrated guide |website=Destination-munich.com |date=2017-03-25 |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"ladyandtherose.com\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://ladyandtherose.com/2012/09/21/how-to-wear-a-dirndl/ |title=How to wear a dirndl &#124; The Lady & the Rose |website=Ladyandtherose.com |date=2012-09-21 |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref> While appearing to be simple and plain, a properly made modern dirndl may be quite expensive as it is tailored, and sometimes cut from costly hand-printed or silk fabrics.<ref name=\"austria.info\"/><ref name=\"destination-munich.com\"/>\n\nThe winter style dirndl has heavy, warm skirts and aprons made of thick [[cotton]], [[linen]], [[velvet]] or [[wool]], and long sleeves. The colors are usually rich and dark. The summer style is lighter and more revealing, has short sleeves, and is often made of lightweight cotton.\n\nAccessories may include a long apron tied round the waist, a [[waistcoat]] or a wool [[shawl]]. In many regions, especially the [[Altaussee|Ausseerland]], vibrantly colored, hand-printed silk scarfs and silk aprons are worn. Women often wear necklaces, earrings and brooches made of silver, the antlers of deer or even animals' teeth. For colder weather there are heavy dirndl coats in the same cut as the dresses, with a high neck and front buttons, thick mittens and wool hats.\n\nDifferent [[Fashion|styles]] were worn in different regions,<ref name=\"austria.info\"/> but they are now more universally generalized.<ref name=\"austria.info\"/>\n\n===Dirndl vs. Tracht and traditional folk costumes===\n[[File:Schwarzwaelderin in Tracht um 1900.jpg|thumb|150px|The female ''[[Tracht]]'' of [[Gutach (Schwarzwaldbahn)|Gutach]] in the [[Black Forest]], around 1900. The red colour of the pompons indicates that the woman was unmarried.]]\n\nThe typical dirndl and folk costume varies from one region, or even village, to another. Folk costume has various details according to the place of origin and social status of the wearer. The modern dirndl is heavily stylized but clearly influenced by typical Bavarian costume. There is also a distinction between the typical dirndl (that is, a garment with an apron made of material with traditional patterns and embroidery) and rural domestic clothing, made from gray or colored linen, sometimes with leather bodice and trim.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 119-5592-12A, M\u00e4dchen mit spielenden Kindern.jpg|thumb|200px|A dirndl on a German young girl in 1933.]]\n\n===Origins===\nThe dirndl originated as a more hardy form of the costume worn today: the uniform of Austrian [[domestic worker]]s during  the 19th century . Simple forms were also worn commonly by working women in plain colors or a simple check. The Austrian upper classes adopted the dirndl as high fashion in the 1870s, making it a highly fashionable and popular must-have item in the nation soon after.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nBoth skirts and pinafore dresses with vest-shaped tank tops, cooking aprons and blouses were commonplace in Europe in the 17th and 18th centuries.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://derstandard.at/1218533838223/Keine-Angst-vorm-Dirndl?_lexikaRange=1 |title=Keine Angst vorm Dirndl - Mode & Kosmetik - derStandard.at \u203a Lifestyle |website=Derstandard.at |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref>\n\nThe basic blouse/skirt/corset idea came from the eastern regions of the [[Swiss Alps]], and was originally simple rural clothing. It became female Austrian servants' [[work clothes]] as well as Alpine peasant attire in the 18th century and exclusively servant\u2019s work clothes in the 19th century.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nAustrian [[Emperor Franz Joseph]] and his wife [[Elisabeth of Bavaria]] liked rustic clothing called a 'Sissi', which equates to what the normal folk called a 'dirndl'.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Development of the dirndl as a fashion mode===\n\nIt appeared in its current state of decorative format and style in eastern Switzerland in the 1890s, and spread in the early 20th century<ref name=\"garderobchik.com\">[https://garderobchik.com/category-glossary_5.html#35 ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130506111201/http://garderobchik.com/category-glossary_5.html |date=2013-05-06 }}</ref> to the south of Germany, Austria, Liechtenstein,<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://derstandard.at/1218533838223/Keine-Angst-vorm-Dirndl?_lexikaRange=1 |title=Keine Angst vorm Dirndl - Mode & Kosmetik - derStandard.at \u203a Lifestyle |website=Derstandard.at |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"garderobchik.com\"/> South Tirol, Trentino and Valcanale Friuli.\n   \nA decisive influence in the development of the dirndl to a fashion mode came from the Jewish brothers Moritz and Julius Wallach (originally from Bielefeld in north-western Germany), who in 1890 founded the ''M\u00fcnchner Volkskunsthaus'' (Munich house of folk culture). \nTheir seamstresses industriously produced the first elegant tracht dresses from colourful printed fabrics, predominantly silk. These were first exhibited by company models at summer parties in the Alps. The breakthrough came in 1910, when the Wallach brothers organized and paid for the traditional costume parade for the 100th anniversary celebrations of the [[Oktoberfest]].<ref name=\"bielefeld\"> Heidi Hagen-Pekdemir: Bielefelder machten das Dirndl erst schick. In: Neue Westf\u00e4lische, 30. September 2015. </ref>\n\nOver time, the dirndl also became acceptable in high society; the Wallach brothers quickly became suppliers to the European aristocracy. The Wallach brothers designed a dirndl for [[Princess Marie-Auguste of Anhalt]], which is said to have aroused excitement at a ball in Paris.<ref name=\"bielefeld\"/> \n\n[[File:Volksfestumzug in Vilshofen a.d. Donau 2012 (3).JPG|thumb|200px|Historically derived modern children's dirndl at a Volksfestumzug in [[Vilshofen an der Donau]] in 2012]]\n\n===Nazi period===\n\nDuring the [[Nazi]] period, the [[Mittelstelle]] German costume of National Socialist Women of the \"[[Reich Commissioner for costume work]]\" was established under [[Gertrud Pesendorfer]].<ref name=\"uibk.ac.at\">{{cite web|url=https://www.uibk.ac.at/geschichte-ethnologie/ee/trachten/projekt.html |title=Projekt \u2013 Universit\u00e4t Innsbruck |website=Uibk.ac.at |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref> In the context of Nazi ideology her designs represented \"renewed costume\".<ref name=\"auto9\">{{cite web|url=http://germanchoices.blogspot.co.uk/2017/10/dirndl-german-dress-dirndl.html|title=Dirndl - German Dress Dirndl|first=YOUR|last=NAME|website=German Choices}}</ref>\n\nThe \"de-catholicised\" <ref name=\"auto9\"/><ref name=\"wolfgangboehmer.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wolfgangboehmer.com/komposition/oper-1/jedermann/|title=Jedermann - Rockoper|website=Wolfgang Boehmer komposition arrangement libretto}}</ref>(''entkatholisiert'')<ref name=\"auto9\" /> style became popular as the Dirndl was de-collared (''de-Cocratisiert'')<!--{{Citation needed|reason=This word doesn't seem to exist outside of this article. I checked several dictionaries, Google ngrams and the first results of a duck duck go search|date=June 2017}}--> (ie: the closed collars removed so it could gain an erotic [[decollete]] collar and\\or off-the-shoulders neckline), the skirt was slightly shortened and the women's arms were no longer  covered beyond the elbow, and it was thus modernized and romanticized as well as eroticized.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"uibk.ac.at\"/> Gertrud Pesendorfer's declared goal was to free the costume of \"overburdening by church, industrialization and fashionable cries\" and \"foreign influences\" and to let the \"rogue sub-culture\" back again.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n===After the Second World War===\n\nDirndls and ''Landhausmode'' were abandoned for a while after World War II. While the wearing of the corresponding garments was scarcely popular in the 1970s, it has grown strongly since the 1990s.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"echoonline.at\">{{cite web|url=http://www.echoonline.at/hauptnews-detail/?tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=4528&cHash=7ffe5edd560b21deb88d5b10f68e12ee |title=HauptNews Detail |website=Echoonline.at |date=2013-10-24 |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://derstandard.at/1389858057909/Von-Dirndln-Trachten-und-Akademikerbaellen |title=Von Dirndln, Trachten und Akademikerb\u00e4llen - Kommentare der anderen - derStandard.at \u203a Meinung |website=Derstandard.at |date=2014-01-24 |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto9\"/><ref name=\"wolfgangboehmer.com\"/>\n\nIn the 21st century, fashion designers have adopted the dirndl, with varying results.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"echoonline.at\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/> It has become a popular Upper Tyrol and Bavarian fashion<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VDN1ve_5d-Q|title=The Dirndl Folk Dress - euromaxx|last=DW (English)|date=10 September 2010|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N7XzktIfPQY&NR=1&featureendscreen|title=Perfektes Dirndl-Dekollet\u00e9: Die modischen Tricks f\u00fcr die Wiesn-Tracht|date=25 September 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> and regular party outfit during [[Oktoberfest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://signora-moda.de/category/kleidung/tracht/|title=Tracht - Signora e la Moda|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite book | last=Schmidt | first=Maximilian |date=1902 | title=Meine Wanderung durch 70 Jahre. Zweiter Teil |language=German | location=Reutlingen |publisher=En\u00dflin & Laiblin | pages=247\u2013260 | isbn= }}</ref> \n.<ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite web|title=Oktoberfest|url=http://www.spatenbeer.com/lessons-oktoberfest.html|publisher=Spaten|accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite web|title=10 Things you didn't know about Oktoberfest|url=http://www.costumecrazy.com.au/blog/blog-posts/10-things-you-didn-t-know-about-oktoberfest/|website=Costume Crazy|accessdate=7 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"lostgirlsworld.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lostgirlsworld.com/2011/04/dirndl/|title=How To Wear a Traditional Bavarian Dirndl - The Lost Girls|website=www.lostgirlsworld.com}}</ref> The ''Dirndlkjoler'' is more common here{{where?|date=August 2017}} with short skirts, bodice just reaching to below the breasts, and dirndl-blouses with deep neckline and bare shoulders. There are also push-up bras that lift and collect the bust at the neckline.<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nIn Switzerland, the dirndl is the official outfit for certain representations, events, cultural shows and singing old folk songs often involving yodeling.<ref name=\"garderobchik.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reference.com/world-view/swiss-traditional-clothes-310edbd3fbc44174|title=What are the Swiss traditional clothes?|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nToday, dirndls vary from simple off-the-shelf styles to exquisitely crafted, very expensive models.<ref name=\"onesprime.de\"/><ref name=\"ladyandtherose.com\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nThe scruffy, sexed-up, open-collar, or economy versions and disjointed dresses that are loosely based on the dirndl are known as ''Landhausmode'' (literally \"country house style\") dresses.<ref name=\"onesprime.de\"/><ref name=\"ladyandtherose.com\"/>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sommerdirndl.com/ |title=Sommerdirndl |publisher=Sommerdirndl |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>[http://www.bavaria-lederhosen.com/en/top-suchbegriffe/ ]{{dead link|date=April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ernstlicht.com\">{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.ernstlicht.com/262-trachten-wear/283-children/285-girls/heidi-dirndl.html |title=Buy Heidi Red Dirndl Online &#124; Germany &#124; Ernst Licht, USA |website=Ernstlicht.com |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://usa.dirndl.com/ |title=Dirndl.com - Original Bavarian Oktoberfest Dirndl Dress and Lederhosen |website=Usa.dirndl.com |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kerstins-landhausmode.com/children_clothes.htm |title=Children |website=Kerstins-landhausmode.com |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bavarian-superstore.de/ |title=Bavarian Superstore, Einkaufen wie Gott in Bayern |language=de|website=Bavarian-superstore.de |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wiesnkoenig-usa.com/dirndl |title=Dirndl |publisher=Wiesnkoenig USA |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref> The children's version is called '' M\u00e4dchenkleid'' (girl's dress). \n\nThese are closed-collar dirndls <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ernstlicht.com/media/catalog/product/cache/1/image/9df78eab33525d08d6e5fb8d27136e95/h/e/heidi-dirndl_new_site.jpg |format=JPG |title=Photographic image |website=4.bp.blogspot.com\\accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"ernstlicht.com\"/> and these are open-collar dirndls <ref>{{cite web|url=http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-1O1QKrMxngw/U6cS5JKXB5I/AAAAAAAAAR0/WiaeneAYTt4/s1600/dirndl1.jpg |format=JPG |title=Photographic image |website=4.bp.blogspot.com\\accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://amusingfashion.blogspot.co.uk/2014/06/fashion-dirndl-dress.html |title=Fashion Design: Fashion dirndl Dress |website=Amusingfashion.blogspot.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref>\n\nGermany and Austria have many manufacturers of the outfits. Both the open-collar and closed-collar versions are popular in those countries. ''Eisbergkleider'' are less popular in North America than in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mydirndl.com/|title=Dirndl & Lederhosen Imported from Germany & Beyond|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn Austria, and other parts of south central Europe, there are literally splashy events known as Dirndlspringen, in which people, often attractive young women, are judged by how well they dive from a diving board into a lake or a swimming pool while wearing the dirndl, using it as a swimdress. Many examples of Dirndlspringen events are found on YouTube.\n\n===North American usage===\nGermans, Austrian, Swiss and Scandinavians people migrated to North America in the 19th century. Germans made a strong contribution to the gene pool of Montana, Minnesota, the Dakotas, Missouri, Wisconsin, New York City <ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite web|url=http://www.germany.travel/en/ms/german-originality/german-clubs/german-clubs.html|title=German Clubs across America|first=Deutsche Zentrale f\u00fcr Tourismus|last=e.V.|publisher=}}</ref> and Chicago. The [[German American]] ethnic group (German: Deutschamerikaner) are their descendants in north America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memoria.ro/?location=view_article&id=1641&l=fr|title=memoria.ro - bibliotec\u0103 digital\u0103 de istorie recent\u0103|last=Aspera|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=hDkVCwAAQBAJ&pg=RA2-PA153&lpg=RA2-PA153&dq=dirndl%20and%20slavic%20blouse#v=onepage&q=dirndl%20and%20slavic%20blouse&f=false|title=Clothing and Fashion: American Fashion from Head to Toe [4 volumes]: American Fashion from Head to Toe|first1=Jos\u00e9 Blanco|last1=F|first2=Patricia Kay|last2=Hunt-Hurst|first3=Heather Vaughan|last3=Lee|first4=Mary|last4=Doering|date=23 November 2015|publisher=ABC-CLIO|via=Google Books|isbn=9781610693103}}</ref> Beginning in 1920 and especially after World War II, many [[Danube Swabians]] migrated to the United States, Brazil, Canada, Mexico, Austria, Australia, and Argentina.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memoria.ro/?location=view_article&id=1641&l=fr |title=bibliotec\u0103 digital\u0103 de istorie recent\u0103 |website=Memoria.ro |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref>\n\nAcross the United States there are dozens of German-American cultural or heritage clubs, such as the Donauschwaben<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2017-01-25|title=Danube Swabians|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Danube_Swabians&oldid=761981460|journal=Wikipedia|language=en}}</ref> heritage clubs.<ref name=\"auto8\"/> In these clubs, members host events and festivals to preserve and/or celebrate their heritage with the surrounding communities. During these festivals, participants often dress in traditional outfits such as dirndls and [[lederhosen]].\n\n==Name==\nIn the South German dialects ([[Austro-Bavarian|Bairisch]]), ''Dirndl'' originally referred to a young woman or a girl, while the word ''Dirndlgewand'' referred to the dress.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=hCbTfFKEUUgC&pg=PA106|title=Munique e Arredores: Alemanha! Por que n\u00e3o?|first=Angela|last=Arten-Meyer|date=1 January 2011|publisher=Books on Demand|via=Google Books|isbn=9783842359796}}</ref> Nowadays, ''Dirndl'' may equally refer to either a young woman or to the dress.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> ''Dirndl'' is a diminutive form of the dated word ''Dirn(e)'' for \"girl\"; in the 20th century, ''Dirne'' (originally a euphemism) has also developed towards meaning \"prostitute\".<ref name=\"auto4\"/> The word is ''Dirn'' in standardized  German  and ''Deern'' in  Low Saxon.<ref name=\"auto4\"/><ref name=\"auto10\"/>\n\n==Dressing etiquette==\nThe dirndl is mostly worn in [[Austria]] and [[Bavaria]]. It is used as an everyday dress primarily by older women in rural areas. Other women may wear it at formal occasions (much like a [[Scotland|Scotsman]] wearing a [[kilt]]) and during certain traditional events. It is hugely popular also among young women at the time of a ''[[Volksfest]]'', such as the [[Oktoberfest]] in [[Munich]] (and similar festivals),<ref name=\"auto5\"/><ref name=\"auto6\"/><ref name=\"auto7\"/> although many women will only wear dirndl-style dresses, called ''Landhausmode'', which may deviate in numerous ways and are often much cheaper.\n\nIn Austria and Bavaria, the dirndl may often be seen on women working in tourism-related businesses, and sometimes waitresses in traditional-style restaurants or [[beer garden]]s. It is also seen in these regions on women in the ''[[Volksmusik]]'' business.\n\nThere is an [[urban legend]] that claims the placement of the [[knot]] on the apron is an indicator of the woman's marital status.<ref name=\"lostgirlsworld.com\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2015/09/germany-oktoberfest-dirndl-fashion/406294/|title=You're Wearing Your Oktoberfest Dress Wrong|last=Horn|first=Heather|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2017-10-02|language=en-US}}</ref>  In this story, which is not based in tradition, tying the sash on the woman's left side indicates that she is single, and a knot tied on the right means that she is married, engaged or otherwise not interested in dating.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Dirndl Code: Expert Tips for a Rollicking Oktoberfest|first=Julia|last=Stanek|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/expert-tips-how-to-get-the-most-out-of-oktoberfest-a-922991.html|accessdate=7 October 2013|date=18 September 2013|work=[[Der Spiegel]]|location=Hamburg}}</ref><ref name=\"lostgirlsworld.com\"/>\n\n==Films featuring women in dirndl costumes==\n{{see also|Heimatfilm}}\n\n*''[[Almost Angels]]''\n*''[[Charlie's Angels (2000 film)|Charlie's Angels]]''\n*''[[Chitty Chitty Bang Bang]]''\n*''[[Heidi]]'' ([[Heidi (1937 film)|1937]] and [[Heidi (1968 film)|1968]])\n*''[[National Lampoon's European Vacation]]'' \n*''[[The Producers (1967 film)|The Producers]]''\n*''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)|Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs]]''\n*''[[The Sound of Music (film)|The Sound of Music]]''\n*''[[The Student Prince]]''\n*''[[The Witch (2015 film)|The Witch]]'' \n*''[[Young Frankenstein]]''\n*''[[Miss Congeniality (film)|Miss Congeniality]]''\n\n==Musical mentions of dirndls==\n*The dirndl is mentioned in the song \"Turn Around\", composed in 1959 by [[Harry Belafonte]], [[Alan Greene]], and [[Malvina Reynolds]]. \"Dirndls and petticoats, where have you gone?\"  This song was originally recorded by the [[Kingston Trio]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Dirndl}}\n{{portal|Austria|Germany|Switzerland}}\n* [[Pinafore]]\n* [[Pinafore dress]]\n* [[Lederhosen]]\n* [[Tracht]]\n* [[Bild Lilli doll]]\n* [[Folk costume]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Gexi Tostmann: ''Das Dirndl (Alpenl\u00e4ndische Tradition und Mode)''. Verlag Christian Brandst\u00e4tter, Wien 1998\n* Heide Hollmer, Kathrin Hollmer: ''Dirndl. Trends, Traditionen, Philosophie, Pop, Stil, Styling''. Edition Ebersbach, Berlin 2011, {{ISBN|978-3-86915-043-7}}\n* Daniela M\u00fcller: ''Alles Dirndl.'' Anton Pustet Verlag, Salzburg 2013, {{ISBN|978-3-7025-0693-3}}\n* Elisabeth Walln\u00f6fer: ''Geraubte Tradition. Wie die Nazis unsere Kultur verf\u00e4lschten.'' Sankt Ulrich, Augsburg 2011, {{ISBN|3867441944}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|Dirndl}}\n*{{commonscat-inline}}\n*https://www.reference.com/world-view/swiss-traditional-clothes-310edbd3fbc44174\n*[http://www.kfj.at/sites/thesite/dirndl.JPG image at an Austrian website]\n*[http://www.oldworldvillage.net/images/heidi/clothing/ladies/dirl3.jpg another image]\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/officegeek/45002967/ modern dirndl]\n*[http://www.postrealism.com/dirndl.htm Photo and History of Dirndl Dress and Austrian Tracht]\n*[http://www.elsenaju.de/Mode/Trachten.htm Folk costume]\n*[https://www.mydirndl.com mydirndl.com] \n*[https://www.dirndl.com/en/ dirndl.com]\n*[https://www.oktoberfest.de/en/shop/tracht-for-women/dirndl-dresses/ oktoberfest.de]\n*[https://www.ernstlicht.com/12-ladies-clothing/97-ladies-dirndls ernstlicht.com]\n*[https://www.reference.com/world-view/swiss-traditional-clothes-310edbd3fbc44174 reference.com]\n\n{{Folk costume}}\n\n[[Category:1870s fashion]]\n[[Category:19th-century fashion]]\n[[Category:German clothing]]\n[[Category:Austrian clothing]]\n[[Category:Swiss clothing]]\n[[Category:Skirts]]\n[[Category:Dresses]]\n[[Category:German culture]]\n[[Category:Austrian culture]]\n\n[[bar:Diandl]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Traditional dress worn in Germany,\u00a0Switzerland, Liechtenstein, Austria and South Tyrol}}\n[[File:Dirndl.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A woman wearing a dirndl.]]\n[[File:KurzsDiandlgwand.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Seated women wearing modern dirndls.]]\n[[File:Diandlgwand.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Different colour variations can depend on the origin of the woman wearing a dirndl.]]\n\nA '''dirndl''' ({{IPA-de|\u02c8d\u026a\u0281ndl\u0329|lang|De-at-Dirndl.ogg}},<ref name=\"auto10\">{{cite web|url=http://germanchoices.blogspot.com/2017/10/dirndl-german-dress-dirndl.html|title=Dirndl - German Dress Dirndl|first=YOUR|last=NAME|website=German Choices}}</ref><ref name=\"auto11\"></{{cite web|url=http://germanchoices.blogspot.co.uk/2017/08/german-beer-maid-costume.html|title=German Beer Maid Costume|first=YOUR|last=NAME|website=German Choices}}</ref> {{lang-bar|Diandl}}) <ref name=\"auto11\"/> is the name of a traditional feminine [[dress]] worn in [[Austria]], [[South Tyrol]] and [[Bavaria]]. It is based on the traditional clothing (''tracht'') of [[Alps]] peasants.<ref name=\"auto10\"/><ref>''Ethnic Dress in the United States: A Cultural Encyclopedia'', eds. Annette Lynch; Mitchell D. Strauss (Lanham, MD: Rowman & Littlefield, 2015), p. 100</ref><ref name=\"austria.info\">{{cite web |url=http://www.austria.info/us/austria-dirndl-temptation/dirndl-basics-1681393.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-11-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412041607/http://www.austria.info/us/austria-dirndl-temptation/dirndl-basics-1681393.html |archivedate=2015-04-12 }}</ref>  Dresses that are loosely based on the dirndl are known as {{lang|de|Landhausmode}} ('country-inspired fashion').\n\nA '''dirndl skirt''' generally describes a light circular cut dress, gathered at the waist, that falls below the knee.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dirndl Skirts|first=Alice|last=Watt|date=26 April 2012|url=http://www.elleuk.com/fashion/what-to-wear/dirndl-skirts#image=1|work=[[Elle (magazine)|Elle]]|location=London|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Spin out with springtime's dirndl skirt|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/fashion/spin-out-with-springtimes-dirndl-skirt-7722321.html|work=[[London Evening Standard]]|location=London|first=Karen|last=Dacre|date=8 May 2012|accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe dirndl consists of a [[bodice]] and skirt or a pinafore dress, a low-cut [[blouse]] with short puff sleeves, full [[skirt]] and [[apron]].<ref name=\"onesprime.de\">{{cite news|url=|title=Oktoberfest Dirndl dress: the bow|last=|first=|date=|website=Onesprime.de|accessdate=}}</ref><ref name=\"destination-munich.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.destination-munich.com/german-dirndl.html |title=German Dirndl - an illustrated guide |website=Destination-munich.com |date=2017-03-25 |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"ladyandtherose.com\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://ladyandtherose.com/2012/09/21/how-to-wear-a-dirndl/ |title=How to wear a dirndl &#124; The Lady & the Rose |website=Ladyandtherose.com |date=2012-09-21 |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref> While appearing to be simple and plain, a properly made modern dirndl may be quite expensive as it is tailored, and sometimes cut from costly hand-printed or silk fabrics.<ref name=\"austria.info\"/><ref name=\"destination-munich.com\"/>\n\nThe winter style dirndl has heavy, warm skirts and aprons made of thick [[cotton]], [[linen]], [[velvet]] or [[wool]], and long sleeves. The colors are usually rich and dark. The summer style is lighter and more revealing, has short sleeves, and is often made of lightweight cotton.\n\nAccessories may include a long apron tied round the waist, a [[waistcoat]] or a wool [[shawl]]. In many regions, especially the [[Altaussee|Ausseerland]], vibrantly colored, hand-printed silk scarfs and silk aprons are worn. Women often wear necklaces, earrings and brooches made of silver, the antlers of deer or even animals' teeth. For colder weather there are heavy dirndl coats in the same cut as the dresses, with a high neck and front buttons, thick mittens and wool hats.\n\nDifferent [[Fashion|styles]] were worn in different regions,<ref name=\"austria.info\"/> but they are now more universally generalized.<ref name=\"austria.info\"/>\n\n===Dirndl vs. Tracht and traditional folk costumes===\n[[File:Schwarzwaelderin in Tracht um 1900.jpg|thumb|150px|The female ''[[Tracht]]'' of [[Gutach (Schwarzwaldbahn)|Gutach]] in the [[Black Forest]], around 1900. The red colour of the pompons indicates that the woman was unmarried.]]\n\nThe typical dirndl and folk costume varies from one region, or even village, to another. Folk costume has various details according to the place of origin and social status of the wearer. The modern dirndl is heavily stylized but clearly influenced by typical Bavarian costume. There is also a distinction between the typical dirndl (that is, a garment with an apron made of material with traditional patterns and embroidery) and rural domestic clothing, made from gray or colored linen, sometimes with leather bodice and trim.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 119-5592-12A, M\u00e4dchen mit spielenden Kindern.jpg|thumb|200px|A dirndl on a German young girl in 1933.]]\n\n===Origins===\nThe dirndl originated as a more hardy form of the costume worn today: the uniform of Austrian [[domestic worker]]s during  the 19th century . Simple forms were also worn commonly by working women in plain colors or a simple check. The Austrian upper classes adopted the dirndl as high fashion in the 1870s, making it a highly fashionable and popular must-have item in the nation soon after.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nBoth skirts and pinafore dresses with vest-shaped tank tops, cooking aprons and blouses were commonplace in Europe in the 17th and 18th centuries.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://derstandard.at/1218533838223/Keine-Angst-vorm-Dirndl?_lexikaRange=1 |title=Keine Angst vorm Dirndl - Mode & Kosmetik - derStandard.at \u203a Lifestyle |website=Derstandard.at |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref>\n\nThe basic blouse/skirt/corset idea came from the eastern regions of the [[Swiss Alps]], and was originally simple rural clothing. It became female Austrian servants' [[work clothes]] as well as Alpine peasant attire in the 18th century and exclusively servant\u2019s work clothes in the 19th century.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nAustrian [[Emperor Franz Joseph]] and his wife [[Elisabeth of Bavaria]] liked rustic clothing called a 'Sissi', which equates to what the normal folk called a 'dirndl'.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Development of the dirndl as a fashion mode===\n\nIt appeared in its current state of decorative format and style in eastern Switzerland in the 1890s, and spread in the early 20th century<ref name=\"garderobchik.com\">[https://garderobchik.com/category-glossary_5.html#35 ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130506111201/http://garderobchik.com/category-glossary_5.html |date=2013-05-06 }}</ref> to the south of Germany, Austria, Liechtenstein,<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://derstandard.at/1218533838223/Keine-Angst-vorm-Dirndl?_lexikaRange=1 |title=Keine Angst vorm Dirndl - Mode & Kosmetik - derStandard.at \u203a Lifestyle |website=Derstandard.at |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"garderobchik.com\"/> South Tirol, Trentino and Valcanale Friuli.\n   \nA decisive influence in the development of the dirndl to a fashion mode came from the Jewish brothers Moritz and Julius Wallach (originally from Bielefeld in north-western Germany), who in 1890 founded the M\u00fcnchner Volkskunsthaus (Munich house of folk culture). \nTheir seamstresses industriously produced the first elegant tracht dresses from colourful printed fabrics, predominantly silk. These were first exhibited by company models at summer parties in the Alps. The breakthrough came in 1910, when the Wallach brothers organized and paid for the traditional costume parade for the 100th anniversary celebrations of the [[Oktoberfest]].<ref name=\"bielefeld\"> Heidi Hagen-Pekdemir: Bielefelder machten das Dirndl erst schick. In: Neue Westf\u00e4lische, 30. September 2015. </ref>\n\nOver time, the dirndl also became acceptable in high society; the Wallach brothers quickly became suppliers to the European aristocracy. The Wallach brothers designed a dirndl for [[Princess Marie-Auguste of Anhalt]], which is said to have aroused excitement at a ball in Paris.<ref name=\"bielefeld\"/> \n\n[[File:Volksfestumzug in Vilshofen a.d. Donau 2012 (3).JPG|thumb|200px|Historically derived modern children's dirndl at a Volksfestumzug in [[Vilshofen an der Donau]] in 2012]]\n\n===Nazi period===\n\nDuring the [[Nazi]] period, the [[Mittelstelle]] German costume of National Socialist Women of the \"[[Reich Commissioner for costume work]]\" was established under [[Gertrud Pesendorfer]].<ref name=\"uibk.ac.at\">{{cite web|url=https://www.uibk.ac.at/geschichte-ethnologie/ee/trachten/projekt.html |title=Projekt \u2013 Universit\u00e4t Innsbruck |website=Uibk.ac.at |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref> In the context of Nazi ideology her designs represented \"renewed costume\".<ref name=\"auto9\">{{cite web|url=http://germanchoices.blogspot.co.uk/2017/10/dirndl-german-dress-dirndl.html|title=Dirndl - German Dress Dirndl|first=YOUR|last=NAME|website=German Choices}}</ref>\n\nThe \"de-catholicised\" <ref name=\"auto9\"/><ref name=\"wolfgangboehmer.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wolfgangboehmer.com/komposition/oper-1/jedermann/|title=Jedermann - Rockoper|website=Wolfgang Boehmer komposition arrangement libretto}}</ref>(''entkatholisiert'')<ref name=\"auto9\" /> style became popular as the Dirndl was de-collared (''de-Cocratisiert'')<!--{{Citation needed|reason=This word doesn't seem to exist outside of this article. I checked several dictionaries, Google ngrams and the first results of a duck duck go search|date=June 2017}}--> (ie: the closed collars removed so it could gain an erotic [[decollete]] collar and\\or off-the-shoulders neckline), the skirt was slightly shortened and the women's arms were no longer  covered beyond the elbow, and it was thus modernized and romanticized as well as eroticized.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"uibk.ac.at\"/> Gertrud Pesendorfer's declared goal was to free the costume of \"overburdening by church, industrialization and fashionable cries\" and \"foreign influences\" and to let the \"rogue sub-culture\" back again.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n===After the Second World War===\n\nDirndls and ''Landhausmode'' were abandoned for a while after World War II. While the wearing of the corresponding garments was scarcely popular in the 1970s, it has grown strongly since the 1990s.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"echoonline.at\">{{cite web|url=http://www.echoonline.at/hauptnews-detail/?tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=4528&cHash=7ffe5edd560b21deb88d5b10f68e12ee |title=HauptNews Detail |website=Echoonline.at |date=2013-10-24 |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://derstandard.at/1389858057909/Von-Dirndln-Trachten-und-Akademikerbaellen |title=Von Dirndln, Trachten und Akademikerb\u00e4llen - Kommentare der anderen - derStandard.at \u203a Meinung |website=Derstandard.at |date=2014-01-24 |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto9\"/><ref name=\"wolfgangboehmer.com\"/>\n\nIn the 21st century, fashion designers have adopted the dirndl, with varying results.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"echoonline.at\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/> It has become a popular Upper Tyrol and Bavarian fashion<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VDN1ve_5d-Q|title=The Dirndl Folk Dress - euromaxx|last=DW (English)|date=10 September 2010|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N7XzktIfPQY&NR=1&featureendscreen|title=Perfektes Dirndl-Dekollet\u00e9: Die modischen Tricks f\u00fcr die Wiesn-Tracht|date=25 September 2012|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> and regular party outfit during [[Oktoberfest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://signora-moda.de/category/kleidung/tracht/|title=Tracht - Signora e la Moda|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite book | last=Schmidt | first=Maximilian |date=1902 | title=Meine Wanderung durch 70 Jahre. Zweiter Teil |language=German | location=Reutlingen |publisher=En\u00dflin & Laiblin | pages=247\u2013260 | isbn= }}</ref> \n.<ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite web|title=Oktoberfest|url=http://www.spatenbeer.com/lessons-oktoberfest.html|publisher=Spaten|accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite web|title=10 Things you didn't know about Oktoberfest|url=http://www.costumecrazy.com.au/blog/blog-posts/10-things-you-didn-t-know-about-oktoberfest/|website=Costume Crazy|accessdate=7 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"lostgirlsworld.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lostgirlsworld.com/2011/04/dirndl/|title=How To Wear a Traditional Bavarian Dirndl - The Lost Girls|website=www.lostgirlsworld.com}}</ref> The ''Dirndlkjoler'' is more common here{{where?|date=August 2017}} with short skirts, bodice just reaching to below the breasts, and dirndl-blouses with deep neckline and bare shoulders. There are also push-up bras that lift and collect the bust at the neckline.<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nIn Switzerland, the dirndl is the official outfit for certain representations, events, cultural shows and singing old folk songs often involving yodeling.<ref name=\"garderobchik.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reference.com/world-view/swiss-traditional-clothes-310edbd3fbc44174|title=What are the Swiss traditional clothes?|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nToday, dirndls vary from simple off-the-shelf styles to exquisitely crafted, very expensive models.<ref name=\"onesprime.de\"/><ref name=\"ladyandtherose.com\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nThe scruffy, sexed-up, open-collar, or economy versions and disjointed dresses that are loosely based on the dirndl are known as ''Landhausmode'' (literally \"country house style\") dresses.<ref name=\"onesprime.de\"/><ref name=\"ladyandtherose.com\"/>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sommerdirndl.com/ |title=Sommerdirndl |publisher=Sommerdirndl |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>[http://www.bavaria-lederhosen.com/en/top-suchbegriffe/ ]{{dead link|date=April 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"ernstlicht.com\">{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.ernstlicht.com/262-trachten-wear/283-children/285-girls/heidi-dirndl.html |title=Buy Heidi Red Dirndl Online &#124; Germany &#124; Ernst Licht, USA |website=Ernstlicht.com |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://usa.dirndl.com/ |title=Dirndl.com - Original Bavarian Oktoberfest Dirndl Dress and Lederhosen |website=Usa.dirndl.com |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kerstins-landhausmode.com/children_clothes.htm |title=Children |website=Kerstins-landhausmode.com |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bavarian-superstore.de/ |title=Bavarian Superstore, Einkaufen wie Gott in Bayern |language=de|website=Bavarian-superstore.de |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wiesnkoenig-usa.com/dirndl |title=Dirndl |publisher=Wiesnkoenig USA |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref> The children's version is called '' M\u00e4dchenkleid'' (girl's dress). \n\nThese are closed-collar dirndls <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ernstlicht.com/media/catalog/product/cache/1/image/9df78eab33525d08d6e5fb8d27136e95/h/e/heidi-dirndl_new_site.jpg |format=JPG |title=Photographic image |website=4.bp.blogspot.com\\accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref name=\"ernstlicht.com\"/> and these are open-collar dirndls <ref>{{cite web|url=http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-1O1QKrMxngw/U6cS5JKXB5I/AAAAAAAAAR0/WiaeneAYTt4/s1600/dirndl1.jpg |format=JPG |title=Photographic image |website=4.bp.blogspot.com\\accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://amusingfashion.blogspot.co.uk/2014/06/fashion-dirndl-dress.html |title=Fashion Design: Fashion dirndl Dress |website=Amusingfashion.blogspot.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref>\n\nGermany and Austria have many manufacturers of the outfits. Both the open-collar and closed-collar versions are popular in those countries. ''Eisbergkleider'' are less popular in North America than in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mydirndl.com/|title=Dirndl & Lederhosen Imported from Germany & Beyond|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn Austria, and other parts of south central Europe, there are literally splashy events known as Dirndlspringen, in which people, often attractive young women, are judged by how well they dive from a diving board into a lake or a swimming pool while wearing the dirndl, using it as a swimdress. Many examples of Dirndlspringen events are found on YouTube.\n\n===North American usage===\nGermans, Austrian, Swiss and Scandinavians people migrated to North America in the 19th century. Germans made a strong contribution to the gene pool of Montana, Minnesota, the Dakotas, Missouri, Wisconsin, New York City <ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite web|url=http://www.germany.travel/en/ms/german-originality/german-clubs/german-clubs.html|title=German Clubs across America|first=Deutsche Zentrale f\u00fcr Tourismus|last=e.V.|publisher=}}</ref> and Chicago. The [[German American]] ethnic group (German: Deutschamerikaner) are their descendants in north America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memoria.ro/?location=view_article&id=1641&l=fr|title=memoria.ro - bibliotec\u0103 digital\u0103 de istorie recent\u0103|last=Aspera|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=hDkVCwAAQBAJ&pg=RA2-PA153&lpg=RA2-PA153&dq=dirndl%20and%20slavic%20blouse#v=onepage&q=dirndl%20and%20slavic%20blouse&f=false|title=Clothing and Fashion: American Fashion from Head to Toe [4 volumes]: American Fashion from Head to Toe|first1=Jos\u00e9 Blanco|last1=F|first2=Patricia Kay|last2=Hunt-Hurst|first3=Heather Vaughan|last3=Lee|first4=Mary|last4=Doering|date=23 November 2015|publisher=ABC-CLIO|via=Google Books|isbn=9781610693103}}</ref> Beginning in 1920 and especially after World War II, many [[Danube Swabians]] migrated to the United States, Brazil, Canada, Mexico, Austria, Australia, and Argentina.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memoria.ro/?location=view_article&id=1641&l=fr |title=bibliotec\u0103 digital\u0103 de istorie recent\u0103 |website=Memoria.ro |date= |accessdate=2017-04-04}}</ref>\n\nAcross the United States there are dozens of German-American cultural or heritage clubs, such as the Donauschwaben<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2017-01-25|title=Danube Swabians|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Danube_Swabians&oldid=761981460|journal=Wikipedia|language=en}}</ref> heritage clubs.<ref name=\"auto8\"/> In these clubs, members host events and festivals to preserve and/or celebrate their heritage with the surrounding communities. During these festivals, participants often dress in traditional outfits such as dirndls and [[lederhosen]].\n\n==Name==\nIn the South German dialects ([[Austro-Bavarian|Bairisch]]), ''Dirndl'' originally referred to a young woman or a girl, while the word ''Dirndlgewand'' referred to the dress.<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=hCbTfFKEUUgC&pg=PA106|title=Munique e Arredores: Alemanha! Por que n\u00e3o?|first=Angela|last=Arten-Meyer|date=1 January 2011|publisher=Books on Demand|via=Google Books|isbn=9783842359796}}</ref> Nowadays, ''Dirndl'' may equally refer to either a young woman or to the dress.<ref name=\"auto4\"/> ''Dirndl'' is a diminutive form of the dated word ''Dirn(e)'' for \"girl\"; in the 20th century, ''Dirne'' (originally a euphemism) has also developed towards meaning \"prostitute\".<ref name=\"auto4\"/> The word is ''Dirn'' in standardized  German  and ''Deern'' in  Low Saxon.<ref name=\"auto4\"/><ref name=\"auto10\"/>\n\n==Dressing etiquette==\nThe dirndl is mostly worn in [[Austria]] and [[Bavaria]]. It is used as an everyday dress primarily by older women in rural areas. Other women may wear it at formal occasions (much like a [[Scotland|Scotsman]] wearing a [[kilt]]) and during certain traditional events. It is hugely popular also among young women at the time of a ''[[Volksfest]]'', such as the [[Oktoberfest]] in [[Munich]] (and similar festivals),<ref name=\"auto5\"/><ref name=\"auto6\"/><ref name=\"auto7\"/> although many women will only wear dirndl-style dresses, called ''Landhausmode'', which may deviate in numerous ways and are often much cheaper.\n\nIn Austria and Bavaria, the dirndl may often be seen on women working in tourism-related businesses, and sometimes waitresses in traditional-style restaurants or [[beer garden]]s. It is also seen in these regions on women in the ''[[Volksmusik]]'' business.\n\nThere is an [[urban legend]] that claims the placement of the [[knot]] on the apron is an indicator of the woman's marital status.<ref name=\"lostgirlsworld.com\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2015/09/germany-oktoberfest-dirndl-fashion/406294/|title=You're Wearing Your Oktoberfest Dress Wrong|last=Horn|first=Heather|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2017-10-02|language=en-US}}</ref>  In this story, which is not based in tradition, tying the sash on the woman's left side indicates that she is single, and a knot tied on the right means that she is married, engaged or otherwise not interested in dating.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Dirndl Code: Expert Tips for a Rollicking Oktoberfest|first=Julia|last=Stanek|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/expert-tips-how-to-get-the-most-out-of-oktoberfest-a-922991.html|accessdate=7 October 2013|date=18 September 2013|work=[[Der Spiegel]]|location=Hamburg}}</ref><ref name=\"lostgirlsworld.com\"/>\n\n==Films featuring women in dirndl costumes==\n{{see also|Heimatfilm}}\n\n*''[[Almost Angels]]''\n*''[[Charlie's Angels (2000 film)|Charlie's Angels]]''\n*''[[Chitty Chitty Bang Bang]]''\n*''[[Heidi]]'' ([[Heidi (1937 film)|1937]] and [[Heidi (1968 film)|1968]])\n*''[[National Lampoon's European Vacation]]'' \n*''[[The Producers (1967 film)|The Producers]]''\n*''[[Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937 film)|Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs]]''\n*''[[The Sound of Music (film)|The Sound of Music]]''\n*''[[The Student Prince]]''\n*''[[The Witch (2015 film)|The Witch]]'' \n*''[[Young Frankenstein]]''\n*''[[Miss Congeniality (film)|Miss Congeniality]]''\n\n==Musical mentions of dirndls==\n*The dirndl is mentioned in the song \"Turn Around\", composed in 1959 by [[Harry Belafonte]], [[Alan Greene]], and [[Malvina Reynolds]]. \"Dirndls and petticoats, where have you gone?\"  This song was originally recorded by the [[Kingston Trio]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Dirndl}}\n{{portal|Austria|Germany|Switzerland}}\n* [[Pinafore]]\n* [[Pinafore dress]]\n* [[Lederhosen]]\n* [[Tracht]]\n* [[Bild Lilli doll]]\n* [[Folk costume]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Gexi Tostmann: ''Das Dirndl (Alpenl\u00e4ndische Tradition und Mode)''. Verlag Christian Brandst\u00e4tter, Wien 1998\n* Heide Hollmer, Kathrin Hollmer: ''Dirndl. Trends, Traditionen, Philosophie, Pop, Stil, Styling''. Edition Ebersbach, Berlin 2011, {{ISBN|978-3-86915-043-7}}\n* Daniela M\u00fcller: ''Alles Dirndl.'' Anton Pustet Verlag, Salzburg 2013, {{ISBN|978-3-7025-0693-3}}\n* Elisabeth Walln\u00f6fer: ''Geraubte Tradition. Wie die Nazis unsere Kultur verf\u00e4lschten.'' Sankt Ulrich, Augsburg 2011, {{ISBN|3867441944}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|Dirndl}}\n*{{commonscat-inline}}\n*https://www.reference.com/world-view/swiss-traditional-clothes-310edbd3fbc44174\n*[http://www.kfj.at/sites/thesite/dirndl.JPG image at an Austrian website]\n*[http://www.oldworldvillage.net/images/heidi/clothing/ladies/dirl3.jpg another image]\n*[https://www.flickr.com/photos/officegeek/45002967/ modern dirndl]\n*[http://www.postrealism.com/dirndl.htm Photo and History of Dirndl Dress and Austrian Tracht]\n*[http://www.elsenaju.de/Mode/Trachten.htm Folk costume]\n*[https://www.mydirndl.com mydirndl.com] \n*[https://www.dirndl.com/en/ dirndl.com]\n*[https://www.oktoberfest.de/en/shop/tracht-for-women/dirndl-dresses/ oktoberfest.de]\n*[https://www.ernstlicht.com/12-ladies-clothing/97-ladies-dirndls ernstlicht.com]\n*[https://www.reference.com/world-view/swiss-traditional-clothes-310edbd3fbc44174 reference.com]\n\n{{Folk costume}}\n\n[[Category:1870s fashion]]\n[[Category:19th-century fashion]]\n[[Category:German clothing]]\n[[Category:Austrian clothing]]\n[[Category:Swiss clothing]]\n[[Category:Skirts]]\n[[Category:Dresses]]\n[[Category:German culture]]\n[[Category:Austrian culture]]\n\n[[bar:Diandl]]\n", "name_user": "Sean Ramsay 3084", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDevelopment of the dirndl as a fashion mode", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dirndl"}
{"title_page": "Tarique Ashraf", "text_new": "'''Tarique Ashraf''' (5 July 1940 - 14 April 1992) was a Pakistani writer and publisher. Tariq Ashraf was the owner of Suhni printing press, editor-in-chief of Suhni Literary Magazine, while his novel Meero Dharial and Jail Dairy are other notable works. It is also claimed by certain Sindhi writers that Tariq introduced great Sindhi short story writer [[Amar Jaleel]] by publishing his stories and even published Suhni's special edition called \"Amar Jaleel Number\" to promote him as a short story writer.\n\n== Biography ==\nTarique Ashraf was born on 5 July 1940 in [[Hyderabad, Sindh|Hyderabad]], [[Sindh]], [[Pakistan]]. His real name was Syed Ashraf Ali Shah. His father's name was Syed Lutuf Ali Shah and mother's name was Bano Bibi. He got school education from Hyderabad and received Master of Arts degree from University of Sindh.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://www.thekawish.com/beta/epaper-details.php?details=2020/April/14-04-2020/Page8/P8-8.jpg|title=\u0646\u0627\u0645\u064a\u0627\u0631\u064a \u06aa\u0647\u0627\u06bb\u064a\u06aa\u0627\u0631 \u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u0627\u0634\u0631\u0641 \u062c\u064a \u0648\u0687\u0648\u0699\u064a \u06a9\u064a 28 \u0633\u0627\u0644 \u0645\u06aa\u0645\u0644|date=2020-04-15|work=Daily Kawish Hyderabad, Page 8|access-date=2020-04-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe had interest with book reading since childhood. His first story was \"Dari\" (The Window) which was published in the literary magazine Badal in 1960. His other early stories were published in \"Mehran\", Rooh Rihan\" and other Sindhi language magazines. In 1960, Tarique Ashraf and his friend Ghulam Nabi Mughal founded publishing house called \"Idara-e-Adab-e-Nau\"<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0627\u062f\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u0627\u062f\u0628 \u0646\u0648 \u062d\u064a\u062f\u0631\u0622\u0628\u0627\u062f |url=http://www.encyclopediasindhiana.org/article.php?Dflt=%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%87%20%D8%A7%D8%AF%20%D8%A8%20%D9%86%D9%88%20%D8%AD%D9%8A%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A2%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%AF |website=Sindhiana, Sindhi Encyclopedia |publisher=Sindhi Lanuage Authority}}</ref> (Institute of Modern Literature) and published his own and other writer's literary works. This publishing house was later on re-named as \"Suhni Publications\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.encyclopediasindhiana.org/article.php?Dflt=\u0633\u0647\u06bb\u064a%20\u067e\u0628\u0644\u064a\u06aa\u064a\u0634\u0646|title=\u0633\u0647\u06bb\u064a \u067e\u0628\u0644\u064a\u06aa\u064a\u0634\u0646 : (Sindhiana\u0633\u0646\u068c\u064a\u0627\u0646\u0627)|website=www.encyclopediasindhiana.org|language=sd|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> It was a time when there was a shortage of Sindhi language magazines and there was a need of a good quality regular Sindhi language literary magazine. To meet this need he launched \"Suhni\" Magazine in 1966. In his editorship, this magazine was proved to be the top class literary journal. This magazine not only introduced many new writers but also published special editions on the work of renowned authors including [[Amar Jaleel]], [[Naseem Kharal|Naseem Kharel]] and [[Shaikh Ayaz]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mughal|first1=Ghulam Nabi|url=http://www.thekawish.com/beta/epaper-details.php?details=2020/April/14-04-2020/Page4/P4-4.jpg|title=\u0648\u064a\u0627 \u0633\u064a \u0648\u064a\u0646\u062c\u0647\u0627\u0631|date=2020-04-15|work=Daily Kawish, Hyderabad|accessdate=2020-04-15|url-status=live|publisher=}}</ref> Tarique was a revolutionary writer. He boldly wrote against One Unit in Pakistan, Policies of [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto|Zulfiqar Ali Bhutto]] and dictatorship of General Zia-ul-Haque. As a result he was jailed in 1975 for 22 months and again in 1983 for three months. He was a man of principles and despite of facing so many difficulties he never compromised over his principles. He produced books and diaries even when he was in the jail.\n\n== Books ==\nFollowing books are on his credit<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sindhsalamat.com/threads/12066/|title=\u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u0627\u0634\u0631\u0641 - \u06aa\u0647\u0627\u06bb\u064a\u06aa\u0627\u0631 \u060c \u0646\u0642\u0627\u062f \u06fd \u0627\u064a\u068a\u064a\u067d\u0631 (\u0648\u0631\u0633\u064a\u0621 \u062a\u064a \u06a9\u064a\u0633 \u0680\u064a\u067d\u0627)|website=SindhSalamat|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.sindhsalamat.com:443/author.php?id=404|title=\u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u0627\u0634\u0631\u0641 {{!}} \u0633\u0646\u068c \u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u062a \u06aa\u062a\u0627\u0628 \u06af\u0647\u0631|website=books.sindhsalamat.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>:\n* Soonhan, Pathar and Piyar (\u0633\u0648\u0646\u0647\u0646\u060c \u067e\u067f\u0631 \u06fd \u067e\u064a\u0627\u0631), short stories (1964)\n* Zindageea Jo Tanha Musafir (\u0632\u0646\u062f\u06af\u064a\u0621\u064e \u062c\u0648 \u062a\u0646\u0647\u0627 \u0645\u0633\u0627\u0641\u0631), short stories (1978)\n* Darid Ja Deenhan, Dard Joon Ratiyoon (\u062f\u0631\u062f \u062c\u0627 \u068f\u064a\u0646\u0647\u0646\u060c \u062f\u0631\u062f \u062c\u0648\u0646 \u0631\u0627\u062a\u064a\u0648\u0646), short stories (1982)\n* Band Akhiun Men, Kujh Sapna Kujh Yadoon (\u0628\u0646\u062f \u0627\u06a9\u064a\u0646 \u06fe \u06aa\u062c\u0647 \u0633\u067e\u0646\u0627 \u06aa\u062c\u0647 \u064a\u0627\u062f\u0648\u0646) (1992)\n* Baweeha Mahina Jail Men (\u067b\u0627\u0648\u064a\u06be \u0645\u0647\u064a\u0646\u0627 \u062c\u064a\u0644 \u06fe) (Two Parts), Jail Diary\n* Jail Gharium Jin San (\u062c\u064a\u0644 \u06af\u0647\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0645 \u062c\u0646 \u0633\u064a\u0646)\n* Adh Mulaqat (\u0627\u068c \u0645\u0644\u0627\u0642\u0627\u062a)\n* Meeru Dhareil (\u0645\u064a\u0631\u0648 \u068c\u0627\u0699\u064a\u0644), Novel\n\n== Death ==\nTarique Ashraf died on 14 April 1992 in [[Karachi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.pk/story/557059/|title=\u0633\u0646\u062f\u06be\u06cc \u0627\u062f\u0628 \u06a9\u06cc \u0646\u0627\u0645\u0648\u0631 \u0634\u062e\u0635\u06cc\u062a \u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u0627\u0634\u0631\u0641 (\u0622\u062e\u0631\u06cc \u062d\u0635\u06c1)|date=2016-07-14|website=\u0627\u06cc\u06a9\u0633\u067e\u0631\u06cc\u0633 \u0627\u0631\u062f\u0648|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Sindhi-language writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Sindh]]\n[[Category:Pakistani writers]]\n[[Category:People from Hyderabad, Sindh]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n'''Tarique Ashraf''' (5 July 1940 - 14 April 1992) was a Pakistani writer and publisher. Tariq Ashraf was the owner of Suhni printing press, editor-in-chief of Suhni Literary Magazine, while his novel Meero Dharial and Jail Dairy are other notable works. It is also claimed by certain Sindhi writers that Tariq introduced great Sindhi short story writer [[Amar Jaleel]] by publishing his stories and even published Suhni's special edition called \"Amar Jaleel Number\" to promote him as a short story writer.\n\n== Biography ==\nTarique Ashraf was born on 5 July 1940 in [[Hyderabad, Sindh|Hyderabad]], [[Sindh]], [[Pakistan]]. His real name was Syed Ashraf Ali Shah. His father's name was Syed Lutuf Ali Shah and mother's name was Bano Bibi. He got school education from Hyderabad and received Master of Arts degree from University of Sindh<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://www.thekawish.com/beta/epaper-details.php?details=2020/April/14-04-2020/Page8/P8-8.jpg|title=\u0646\u0627\u0645\u064a\u0627\u0631\u064a \u06aa\u0647\u0627\u06bb\u064a\u06aa\u0627\u0631 \u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u0627\u0634\u0631\u0641 \u062c\u064a \u0648\u0687\u0648\u0699\u064a \u06a9\u064a 28 \u0633\u0627\u0644 \u0645\u06aa\u0645\u0644|date=2020-04-15|work=Daily Kawish Hyderabad, Page 8|access-date=2020-04-15|url-status=live}}</ref>.\n\nHe had interest with book reading since childhood. His first story was \"Dari\" (The Window) which was published in the literary magazine Badal in 1960. His other early stories were published in \"Mehran\", Rooh Rihan\" and other Sindhi language magazines. In 1960, Tarique Ashraf and his friend Ghulam Nabi Mughal founded publishing house called \"Idara-e-Adab-e-Nau\"<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0627\u062f\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u0627\u062f\u0628 \u0646\u0648 \u062d\u064a\u062f\u0631\u0622\u0628\u0627\u062f |url=http://www.encyclopediasindhiana.org/article.php?Dflt=%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%87%20%D8%A7%D8%AF%20%D8%A8%20%D9%86%D9%88%20%D8%AD%D9%8A%D8%AF%D8%B1%D8%A2%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%AF |website=Sindhiana, Sindhi Encyclopedia |publisher=Sindhi Lanuage Authority}}</ref> (Institute of Modern Literature) and published his own and other writer's literary works. This publishing house was later on re-named as \"Suhni Publications\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.encyclopediasindhiana.org/article.php?Dflt=\u0633\u0647\u06bb\u064a%20\u067e\u0628\u0644\u064a\u06aa\u064a\u0634\u0646|title=\u0633\u0647\u06bb\u064a \u067e\u0628\u0644\u064a\u06aa\u064a\u0634\u0646 : (Sindhiana\u0633\u0646\u068c\u064a\u0627\u0646\u0627)|website=www.encyclopediasindhiana.org|language=sd|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. It was a time when there was a shortage of Sindhi language magazines and there was a need of a good quality regular Sindhi language literary magazine. To meet this need he launched \"Suhni\" Magazine in 1966. In his editorship, this magazine was proved to be the top class literary journal. This magazine not only introduced many new writers but also published special editions on the work of renowned authors including [[Amar Jaleel]], [[Naseem Kharal|Naseem Kharel]] and [[Shaikh Ayaz]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mughal|first1=Ghulam Nabi|url=http://www.thekawish.com/beta/epaper-details.php?details=2020/April/14-04-2020/Page4/P4-4.jpg|title=\u0648\u064a\u0627 \u0633\u064a \u0648\u064a\u0646\u062c\u0647\u0627\u0631|date=2020-04-15|work=Daily Kawish, Hyderabad|accessdate=2020-04-15|url-status=live|publisher=}}</ref>. Tarique was a revolutionary writer. He boldly wrote against One Unit in Pakistan, Policies of [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto|Zulfiqar Ali Bhutto]] and dictatorship of General Zia-ul-Haque. As a result he was jailed in 1975 for 22 months and again in 1983 for three months. He was a man of principles and despite of facing so many difficulties he never compromised over his principles. He produced books and diaries even when he was in the jail. \n\n== Books ==\nFollowing books are on his credit<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sindhsalamat.com/threads/12066/|title=\u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u0627\u0634\u0631\u0641 - \u06aa\u0647\u0627\u06bb\u064a\u06aa\u0627\u0631 \u060c \u0646\u0642\u0627\u062f \u06fd \u0627\u064a\u068a\u064a\u067d\u0631 (\u0648\u0631\u0633\u064a\u0621 \u062a\u064a \u06a9\u064a\u0633 \u0680\u064a\u067d\u0627)|website=SindhSalamat|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.sindhsalamat.com:443/author.php?id=404|title=\u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u0627\u0634\u0631\u0641 {{!}} \u0633\u0646\u068c \u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u062a \u06aa\u062a\u0627\u0628 \u06af\u0647\u0631|website=books.sindhsalamat.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>:\n* Soonhan, Pathar and Piyar (\u0633\u0648\u0646\u0647\u0646\u060c \u067e\u067f\u0631 \u06fd \u067e\u064a\u0627\u0631), short stories (1964)\n* Zindageea Jo Tanha Musafir (\u0632\u0646\u062f\u06af\u064a\u0621\u064e \u062c\u0648 \u062a\u0646\u0647\u0627 \u0645\u0633\u0627\u0641\u0631), short stories (1978)\n* Darid Ja Deenhan, Dard Joon Ratiyoon (\u062f\u0631\u062f \u062c\u0627 \u068f\u064a\u0646\u0647\u0646\u060c \u062f\u0631\u062f \u062c\u0648\u0646 \u0631\u0627\u062a\u064a\u0648\u0646), short stories (1982)\n* Band Akhiun Men, Kujh Sapna Kujh Yadoon (\u0628\u0646\u062f \u0627\u06a9\u064a\u0646 \u06fe \u06aa\u062c\u0647 \u0633\u067e\u0646\u0627 \u06aa\u062c\u0647 \u064a\u0627\u062f\u0648\u0646) (1992)\n* Baweeha Mahina Jail Men (\u067b\u0627\u0648\u064a\u06be \u0645\u0647\u064a\u0646\u0627 \u062c\u064a\u0644 \u06fe) (Two Parts), Jail Diary\n* Jail Gharium Jin San (\u062c\u064a\u0644 \u06af\u0647\u0627\u0631\u064a\u0645 \u062c\u0646 \u0633\u064a\u0646)\n* Adh Mulaqat (\u0627\u068c \u0645\u0644\u0627\u0642\u0627\u062a)\n* Meeru Dhareil (\u0645\u064a\u0631\u0648 \u068c\u0627\u0699\u064a\u0644), Novel\n\n== Death ==\nTarique Ashraf died on 14 April 1992 in [[Karachi]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.pk/story/557059/|title=\u0633\u0646\u062f\u06be\u06cc \u0627\u062f\u0628 \u06a9\u06cc \u0646\u0627\u0645\u0648\u0631 \u0634\u062e\u0635\u06cc\u062a \u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u0627\u0634\u0631\u0641 (\u0622\u062e\u0631\u06cc \u062d\u0635\u06c1)|date=2016-07-14|website=\u0627\u06cc\u06a9\u0633\u067e\u0631\u06cc\u0633 \u0627\u0631\u062f\u0648|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\n== References ==\n\n\n[[Category: Sindhi-language writers]]\n[[Category: Writers from Sindh]]\n[[Category: Pakistani writers]]\n[[Category: People from Hyderabad, Sindh]]\n[[Category: 1940 births]]\n[[Category: 1992 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tarique_Ashraf"}
{"title_page": "Bush discography", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox artist discography\n|Artist       = [[Bush (British band)|Bush]]\n|Image        =  \n|Caption      = \n|Studio       = 7\n|Compilation  = 2\n|Video        = 2\n|Live         = 1\n|Music videos = 24\n|Singles      = 28\n}}\n\nThe [[discography]] of [[Bush (British band)|Bush]], an English [[Rock music|rock]] band, consists of 7 [[studio album]]s, 1 [[live album]], 2 [[compilation album]]s, and 28 [[Single (music)|singles]] released on [[Interscope Records]]. The band had released 4 studio albums before separating in 2002. They reunited in 2010 and have since released 3 albums.\n\n== Albums ==\n\n=== Studio albums ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album details\n! colspan=\"10\"| Peak chart positions \n! rowspan=\"2\"| [[Music recording sales certification|Certifications]]<ref name=\"CRIA\">Certifications for Bush's albums in Canada: \n*For \"Sixteen Stone\" {{cite web|url=http://www.musiccanada.com/GPSearchResult.aspx?st=Sixteen%20Stone&ica=False&sa=Bush&sl=&smt=0&sat=-1&ssb=Artist|title=Bush - Sixteen Stone|publisher=[[Canadian Recording Industry Association]]|accessdate=2011-12-21}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*For \"Razorblade Suitcase\" {{cite web|url=http://www.musiccanada.com/GPSearchResult.aspx?st=Razorblade%20Suitcase&ica=False&sa=Bush&sl=&smt=0&sat=-1&ssb=Artist|title=Bush - Razorblade Suitcase|publisher=[[Canadian Recording Industry Association]]|accessdate=2011-12-21}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*For \"The Science of Things\" {{cite web|url=http://www.musiccanada.com/GPSearchResult.aspx?st=The%20Science%20of%20Things&ica=False&sa=Bush&sl=&smt=0&sat=-1&ssb=Artist|title=Bush - The Science of Things|publisher=[[Canadian Recording Industry Association]]|accessdate=2011-12-21}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"BPI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/index.asp |title=Certified Awards |work=[[British Phonographic Industry]] |accessdate=2008-12-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204050257/http://www.bpi.co.uk/index.asp |archivedate=4 December 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"RIAA\">[https://archive.today/20130104130110/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=3&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=Bush&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2008&sort=Artist&perPage=25 RIAA Gold and Platinum Search for albums by Bush]. Retrieved on 2008-12-15.</ref><br><small>([[List of best selling music artists|sales threshold]])</small>\n|- \n! width=\"30\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br><ref name=\"UK\">UK chart peaks:\n*Top 100 peaks: {{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/32892/bush/|title=Official Charts > Bush|publisher=[[Official Charts Company|The Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=2016-12-24}}  N.B. This site displays 'compressed' chart peaks (exclusion rules applied) for singles charting between 76 and 100.\n*Top 200 peaks to December 2010: {{cite web|url=http://www.zobbel.de/cluk/CLUK_B.HTM|title=Chart Log UK 1994\u20132010 > Darren B \u2013 David Byrne|publisher=zobbel.de|accessdate=2016-12-24}} N.B. This site displays 'uncompressed' chart peaks (no exclusion rules applied) for singles charting between 76 and 200, from November 1994 to May 2001.\n*''The Sea of Memories'': {{cite web|url=http://www.zobbel.de/cluk/111112cluk.txt|title=CHART: CLUK Update 12.11.2011 (wk44)|publisher=zobbel.de|accessdate=2016-12-24}}</ref>\n! width=\"30\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br><ref name=\"AUS\">Australian (ARI